INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (192, 'Bridget McKenzie Calls Transport Chief an ‘Inner-City Lefty’—Because Insults Solve Everything', 'Nothing screams serious policy debate like a senator flinging political stereotypes. Next, she’ll accuse the finance minister of being a ‘coffeeshop socialist.’', 'Bridget McKenzie Calls Transport Chief an ‘Inner-City Lefty’—Because Insults Solve Everything\"\n\nThe Characters:\nEnter Nationals Senator Bridget McKenzie, a politician who never met a culture war she didn’t want to escalate. Best known for the Sports Rorts scandal (where funding mysteriously favored Coalition seats—oops), McKenzie has now set her sights on the transport sector. Her latest target? The head of Infrastructure Australia, Adam Copp, whom she has labeled an “inner-city lefty.” Because, obviously, running a transport agency requires a specific political leaning.\n\nThe Incident:\nDuring a heated Senate hearing, McKenzie went full attack mode on Copp, suggesting he was too “inner-city” to understand the transport needs of rural and regional Australia. That’s right—because understanding how roads work is clearly a political issue now. She also took issue with Infrastructure Australia’s new direction, claiming it was leaning too much toward sustainability and emissions reduction. How dare they try to future-proof the country!\n\nThe Context:\nAustralia’s transport infrastructure is a mess. Cities are clogged, rural areas lack proper investment, and let’s not even start on public transport funding. The government has been pushing for smarter, greener infrastructure projects, but that doesn’t sit well with McKenzie, who appears to believe wind turbines personally insult her. Instead of, say, offering solutions, she went for the classic political move: calling people names.\n\nThe Latest:\nMcKenzie’s comments have been met with widespread eye-rolls, with critics pointing out that maybe, just maybe, transport decisions should be based on expertise rather than someone’s perceived political leanings. Copp, for his part, didn’t take the bait, because when someone calls you a “lefty” for trying to improve transport, the best response is probably just... building better roads anyway.\n\n', 0, 'factabot', 'Bridget McKenzie Calls Transport Chief an ‘Inner-City Lefty’—Because Insults Solve Everything', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-03-29 00:31:10', '2025-03-29 00:31:10', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (193, 'Labor’s Tax Cuts Pass Lower House—Coalition Begins Mourning Period', 'Despite their best efforts at not voting for it, the Albanese government’s tax cuts are happening. Scott Morrison is somewhere, shaking his head from retirement.', 'Labor’s Tax Cuts Pass Lower House—Coalition Begins Mourning Period\"\n\nThe Characters:\nThe Albanese government, fresh off actually passing legislation, is celebrating its tax cut bill sailing through the Lower House. Meanwhile, Peter Dutton and the Coalition are acting like they just lost a beloved pet. Despite previously supporting tax cuts, they’re now treating Labor’s move like some kind of financial apocalypse—because, as we all know, only conservative governments are allowed to cut taxes.\n\nThe Incident:\nLabor’s long-awaited tax cut plan, aimed at giving middle- and low-income Aussies some breathing room, has officially cleared the Lower House. This means more money in people’s pockets—unless you’re the Coalition, in which case it means the end of days. The tax cuts are a revision of the previous Morrison government’s Stage 3 tax cuts, which were heavily weighted towards high earners. Labor tweaked them to spread the benefits more evenly, and suddenly, Dutton & Co. aren’t fans anymore.\n\nThe Context:\nThe Coalition spent years championing tax cuts, but now that Labor is the one delivering them, they’ve had a change of heart. Dutton has called the plan “class warfare” (which is ironic, considering Morrison’s version only helped the rich). Meanwhile, Treasurer Jim Chalmers is out here acting like Santa Claus with a spreadsheet, saying this is all about “fairness.” Whether or not the cuts actually help fix the cost-of-living crisis is still TBD, but hey, free money is free money.\n\nThe Latest:\nWith the bill now heading to the Senate, the Coalition is still throwing a tantrum, despite the fact that most Australians support the changes. As for Dutton? He’s busy predicting economic doom, conveniently ignoring that his own party originally set this whole thing up. Meanwhile, everyday Aussies are just hoping their extra dollars can at least cover one overpriced grocery trip.', 0, 'factabot', 'Labor’s Tax Cuts Pass Lower House—Coalition Begins Mourning Period', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-03-29 00:31:10', '2025-04-09 07:31:28', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (194, 'Valerie the Fugitive Dachshund Still at Large—Honestly, Just Let Her Win', 'Missing since 2023, Kangaroo Island’s most successful escape artist continues to outwit humans. Honestly, at this point, give her a medal and a Netflix doco.', 'Valerie the Houdini Dachshund Evades Rescue for Weeks, Becomes Kangaroo Island’s Furry Outlaw\"\n\nThe Characters (20%)\nMeet Valerie, a tiny dachshund with a massive talent for escape artistry. This four-legged mastermind vanished on Kangaroo Island and proceeded to give rescuers, locals, and animal trackers the slip for weeks. While most dogs panic when separated from their owners, Valerie apparently decided to go bush and live life on the run—probably surviving on a diet of pure determination and whatever snacks she could find.\n\nThe Case Background (30%)\nValerie’s great escape began after she got loose from her owner and disappeared into the wild terrain of Kangaroo Island. Locals quickly launched a full-scale search operation, complete with drones, thermal imaging, and volunteers scouring the area. But this pint-sized escape artist dodged them all, refusing to be caught like some sort of canine outlaw. As days turned into weeks, Valerie became an island legend, with people reporting sightings like she was Bigfoot.\n\nThe Context (30%)\nDachshunds are not exactly built for survival in the wild—short legs, tiny bodies, and a general air of entitlement don’t scream “rugged explorer.” And yet, Valerie managed to do what fully grown humans struggle with on reality survival shows. Meanwhile, social media went into overdrive, turning her into an internet celebrity, with people joking she had “gone rogue” and was now leading a secret dachshund rebellion in the wilderness.\n\nThe Latest (20%)\nAfter weeks of evading capture, Valerie was finally found and reunited with her very relieved owner. Miraculously, she was healthy and unharmed—probably a little smug about having outwitted an entire island. The internet now demands a movie deal, and honestly, with a story like this, who wouldn’t watch The Great Dachshund Escape?', 0, 'factabot', 'Valerie the Fugitive Dachshund Still at Large—Honestly, Just Let Her Win', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-03-29 00:31:10', '2025-03-29 00:31:10', 0);
