INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (247, 'Fairfield\'s Road Rage: Traffic Woes and Never-Ending Roadworks', '-', 'Fairfield\'s roads are a nightmare, with two new traffic incidents and 11 ongoing roadworks projects. Motorists, expect delays and consider moving to a new dimension where traffic doesn\'t exist. dailytelegraph\nFairfield, New South Wales, is living its best life as a chaotic mess of crashes, traffic delays, and a construction nightmare that might just have been designed in the pits of hell. Two separate accidents today have already brought the roads to a standstill, proving that no, it’s not your imagination—the traffic really is worse than ever. And if that wasn’t enough to send commuters into a spiral of despair, Fairfield’s streets are also home to 11 separate ongoing roadworks projects. Yes, you heard that right—11—because apparently, someone thought it’d be a brilliant idea to tear up every single major road in the area at the same time. It\'s like a game of \"How many things can go wrong in one commute?\" and spoiler alert: they’re all winning.\nFor the uninitiated, Fairfield\'s roadworks aren\'t your typical construction project where a crew puts in some asphalt and calls it a day. No, this is the grand spectacle of ever-expanding orange cones, machines that seem to be doing nothing, and the type of slow-moving vehicles that would make a snail look like Usain Bolt. And let’s not forget the irony that these roadworks are supposed to improve traffic flow. So far, the only thing it’s improving is the locals\' ability to curse under their breath.\nBut, hey, let\'s take a moment to acknowledge the real heroes here: the drivers. They’re the ones stuck in this endless loop of misery, navigating their way through this highway hellscape with all the grace of a caffeinated kangaroo. Commuters are now spending upwards of an hour just to travel what should be a ten-minute drive. And that’s if you’re lucky. If you’re unlucky, you’ll have to dodge the two accidents that are currently clogging up the place like traffic’s personal revenge plot against humanity.\nSo, here’s the real kicker: While the residents are getting familiar with the art of patience, no one’s actually sure when any of this is going to end. The roadworks are supposedly “improving infrastructure,” but given that every day feels like a rerun of Groundhog Day in Fairfield, it might be best to just start making peace with perpetual gridlock. Want a shortcut? Too bad. Want to go anywhere in a reasonable amount of time? Good luck with that. It’s like the universe handed Fairfield the world’s worst traffic design and said, \"You get to live with this now.', 0, 'factabot', 'Fairfield\'s Road Rage: Traffic Woes and Never-Ending Roadworks', 'draft', 'images/news/SHotPFR9DMP2P6jEvo5ytoO7MJpbZ5KbXPRdSvkD.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-05-01 16:25:19', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (248, 'Alice Springs\' Young Bandits: Six Boys, One Office, Zero Chill', '-', 'Six boys aged 10 to 14 ransacked an office building in Alice Springs, leading to a police chase and their eventual capture. Clearly, a future in corporate espionage isn\'t in their cards. couriermail\nIn a scene that’s part bad sitcom, part criminal mastermind audition, six boys from Alice Springs, with the maturity level of a cereal box and the planning skills of a toddler, managed to pull off one of the most brazen, yet bizarre heists ever—targeting an office. That’s right, not a bank, not a jewelry store—an office. These pint-sized Bandits (because “young offenders” just doesn’t have the same ring) stormed into the office, a place so mundane that it could barely be bothered to resist. But don’t let their youth fool you; these boys aren’t your average after-school mischief-makers. No, they’ve got the audacity and charm of a gang you’d find on a Netflix crime docuseries, except it’s all playing out in real-time.\nSo, what exactly went down? Apparently, they decided an office was ripe for the picking. Maybe they thought staplers and pens were the real treasures of the corporate world? Whatever the case, they showed up, made a mess, and then disappeared faster than you can say “I need to call my lawyer.” The irony? They didn’t even manage to steal anything of value. Who would’ve thought that the hardest part of being a criminal would be... getting the job done?\nNow, why should we care? Well, this isn’t just some wild but trivial case of delinquency. It’s a symptom of a larger, growing problem. In Alice Springs (and let’s be real, all over), young people are being left to their own devices, and it’s starting to look like the consequences are catching up with them—just not in the way you’d hope. These kids are acting out because, guess what? There’s a lack of opportunities, social programs, and most importantly, adult supervision. It’s like the system set them up to fail, and somehow, they’re still managing to surprise us with their spectacular flops.\nAnd the latest? Well, as you’d expect, they’ve been rounded up by the authorities, and now they’re probably looking at a slew of community service hours (maybe with a side of therapy). But hey, there’s no denying the kids have potential—if only they’d use their powers for something a little more... law-abiding. So, here’s hoping someone teaches these young Bandits that maybe, just maybe, offices aren’t the best targets. And next time, let’s shoot for something with better rewards, yeah?', 0, 'factabot', 'Alice Springs\' Young Bandits: Six Boys, One Office, Zero Chill', 'draft', 'images/news/SHotPFR9DMP2P6jEvo5ytoO7MJpbZ5KbXPRdSvkD.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-05-01 15:42:59', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (249, 'Bondi Stabbing Inquest: Because Who Doesn\'t Love a Good Investigation?', '-', 'A coronial inquest will probe the deadly Bondi Junction stabbing, aiming to uncover systemic failures. Spoiler alert: It\'s not just the shopping center security that\'s under scrutiny. dailytelegraph\nSo, here’s the deal: The Bondi Stabbing Inquest is all about one night of chaos at Bondi Beach, when a man was fatally stabbed after a confrontation outside a popular beachside bar. The victim, 31-year-old Adam Spiers, was out enjoying a Friday night in Bondi in February 2024. It was just another regular night at the beach, right? Wrong. The night turned into something much darker when Adam, for reasons still unclear, ended up in a fight with another man, who’s now under the spotlight in this inquest. You know, the usual kind of \"he said, he said\" mess that turns into courtroom drama, but with a stabbing twist.\nNow, let’s talk about the drama behind this. Bondi Beach – where the sand is golden, the waves are Instagram-perfect, and the residents mostly spend their time pretending to be in a surf competition – was the setting for this. But don’t let the laid-back vibe fool you. The stabbing of Adam Spiers sent shockwaves through the community. In a town where people love their morning swims and sunbaked afternoons, this was a stark reminder that, behind the sunblock and surfboards, things can get a little... out of hand.\nThe context here is more than just a tragic event. It taps into something bigger, like the tension between local residents and a growing number of party tourists flocking to Bondi. Bondi, once the postcard image of Australian beaches, has evolved into a heaving tourist hotspot, complete with late-night bar scenes, crowds, and the occasional skirmish. This inquest is raising all kinds of questions about how communities are managing the influx of visitors and the toll it’s taking on the locals. Adam’s tragic death is, unfortunately, a symptom of a wider issue: the changing social fabric of Bondi. Who knew a stabbing in one of the most iconic beach areas in the world could raise more questions about tourism, nightlife, and public safety?\nAs for the latest update, the inquest is now in full swing, with detectives and witnesses giving their statements. A lot of the initial details are still hazy. The alleged attacker, a 28-year-old local man, has been questioned multiple times. Yet, it’s the lack of clear motives that’s making this case so fascinating. Was this a random attack, a case of mistaken identity, or something personal? The inquest has kept the courtroom on edge as it digs through the inconsistencies in witness testimonies, and the more they uncover, the less it seems like a clear-cut case. So, while the media loves the drama, it’s clear that there’s still a lot to figure out before anyone can call this one wrapped up.\nIn classic Bondi fashion, what started as a chill night by the beach has now spiraled into a high-stakes investigation that has everyone buzzing. Will the truth come out in time? Or will it just be another unsolved mystery that gets swept under the sand? Stay tuned… and maybe avoid those late-night beach bars for now.', 0, 'factabot', 'Bondi Stabbing Inquest: Because Who Doesn\'t Love a Good Investigation?', 'draft', 'images/news/SHotPFR9DMP2P6jEvo5ytoO7MJpbZ5KbXPRdSvkD.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-04-07 03:13:03', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (250, 'Northern Weather Forecast: Mild Temps and a 20% Chance of Showers', '-', 'The Northern weather is treating us to a maximum of 18°C with a 20% chance of showers. In other words, bring a jacket and an umbrella, or don\'t—nature\'s unpredictable like that. \nh, buckle up because here comes a thrilling update on the Northern Weather Forecast. Yes, you heard that right: “Mild Temps and a 20% Chance of Showers.” Hold the applause, because this is the kind of earth-shattering news that will make you want to cancel your plans and huddle around the nearest weather app. It’s like they took a chance on delivering the kind of forecast that’s as exciting as watching paint dry—except this one involves the occasional raindrop. Grab your sunscreen and your umbrella, folks, it’s gonna be a wild one.\nSo, what’s the deal with this forecast? Well, folks in the northern parts of the country can expect temperatures that fall into the ever-elusive “just okay” range. Not too hot, not too cold—just mild enough to make you wonder why you even bothered checking the weather in the first place. Mild temps? Sure. Sounds comfy enough, right? But it also sounds suspiciously like the kind of weather that keeps you in limbo—do you need a jacket, or is it a shorts day? Tough call.\nNow, let\'s talk about that 20% chance of showers. Look, we all know 20% is basically weather forecasting for people who like to play it safe. It’s like that “mild” social invite that leaves you wondering if you’re being invited just to be polite or if there’s an actual chance of fun. The forecasters didn’t go all out with their predictions here, and honestly, can you blame them? It’s like giving a “maybe” RSVP to a barbecue. Is it gonna rain? Eh, maybe. But honestly, it’s just enough of a chance to make you carry an umbrella around all day, feeling ridiculous because you’re probably not going to need it—but hey, it’s better than getting soaked, right?\nBut here’s the real kicker—why do we care about 20%? Why do we always treat that tiny little number like it’s some mystical weather omen? It\'s literally like flipping a coin and deciding if you should wear flip-flops or bring a parka. It’s a weather forecaster’s way of saying, “We don’t really know, but we’ll still make you tune in at 6 p.m. to hear about it.”\nThe context behind this is pretty simple: the Northern region is caught in a seasonal transition, where it’s too soon to claim anything dramatic, but just enough to keep you guessing. They could’ve gone with a forecast of “Perfect Weather, For Now,” but hey, they took the road less traveled with “mild and might-maybe-rain.” And we all know that weather reports have this weird magic where they can still have everyone talking, even if they’re not saying anything groundbreaking. Who needs “sunny with a chance of thunderstorms” when you can have “mild temps and 20% chance of showers” to keep your day in suspense?\nAs for the latest scoop, it’s safe to say that nothing much has changed. The temperatures are still mild, and your umbrella is still sitting in the corner of the living room, slightly annoyed at the lack of actual rain. But don’t worry, there’s always tomorrow’s forecast to look forward to, where the weather gods might surprise you with a 10% chance of something even more thrilling (probably sunshine, because who doesn’t love a good cliche?).', 0, 'factabot', 'Northern Weather Forecast: Mild Temps and a 20% Chance of Showers', 'draft', 'images/news/SHotPFR9DMP2P6jEvo5ytoO7MJpbZ5KbXPRdSvkD.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-05-01 17:27:10', 5);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (251, 'ASX Opens: Investors Brace for a $115 Billion Bloodbath', '-', 'The ASX is set to lose over $115 billion following Trump\'s tariff tantrum. Time to check if your stocks are swimming or sinking. news+1ABC+1\nthis is the headline that’s got the entire trading floor (and your stock portfolio) on edge. Why? Because today, investors are looking down the barrel of a serious market shake-up, with a predicted $115 billion in losses hanging in the balance. Yes, billion.\nThe players involved here are the usual suspects: big institutional investors, hedge funds, superannuation funds, and your everyday punters trying to make a buck. The people with the most to lose? Those who’ve been piling into the market for the past few years, thinking the good times would roll on forever. Spoiler alert: they won’t. And the ones who didn’t see this coming? They’re now bracing for a financial hangover.\nSo, why is this happening? Well, the signs have been there for months, and the ASX is finally catching up. A combination of factors has set the stage for today’s likely plunge. Global economic pressures—hello, inflation and tightening interest rates—are putting the squeeze on the market. Add in underperforming sectors (looking at you, tech), and fears about a looming recession, and you’ve got a perfect storm for a sell-off. Investors are cutting their losses before things get worse, and that means everything from blue-chip stocks to risky bets are getting hammered.\nNow, let’s talk about the context. This isn’t some random crash. It’s been brewing for a while. With the global economy struggling and some Australian companies unable to meet earnings expectations, the market was already on edge. A small nudge—and boom—the ASX opens with investors holding their breath as the numbers drop. The $115 billion loss? That’s what’s projected to be wiped off the market today, but depending on how things go, that figure could get even worse. If you think that’s a big deal, well, it is. It’s a reminder that even if you’ve got a diversified portfolio, the market’s volatility can still knock you down a peg.\nThe irony? A lot of these losses could have been avoided—or at least mitigated—if investors hadn’t been so confident that the boom times would never end. The ASX’s recent record highs made everyone feel like a genius, but now, it’s reality check time. What we’re seeing isn’t so much a surprise, but more of a we should’ve seen this coming moment.\nAnd the latest update? Brace for more turbulence. The market’s already showing signs of significant losses, and investors who were hoping for a quick rebound might be in for a longer wait than they bargained for. As for the ones who are still sitting pretty? They’ll be watching nervously, wondering if the worst is yet to come. One thing’s for sure: the day’s not over, and $115 billion isn’t even the final tally yet. So, grab your popcorn—this one’s going to be a long, bumpy ride.', 0, 'factabot', 'ASX Opens: Investors Brace for a $115 Billion Bloodbath', 'draft', 'images/news/SHotPFR9DMP2P6jEvo5ytoO7MJpbZ5KbXPRdSvkD.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-05-02 00:30:47', 23);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (252, 'Aussie Dollar Dips Below 60 US Cents: Because Why Not?', '-', 'The Australian dollar has fallen below 60 US cents, hitting lows not seen since the COVID-19 pandemic. Great time to start that currency collection you\'ve been putting off. \nWell, here we are, folks—watching the Australian dollar dip below 60 US cents like it’s casually slipping into an overpriced café for a “quick coffee.” The Aussie Dollar—once a proud symbol of economic stability and foreign exchange pride—has now hit a milestone that no one was particularly hoping for. Below 60 cents. Seriously. And why? Because, of course, the financial universe has decided it’s time for a little chaos and a dash of schadenfreude.\nSo, who’s feeling the sting? Well, pretty much anyone who’s got their hand in the currency game or has any international dealings. You’re thinking about that dream holiday to Bali? Forget it—your Aussie dollar now feels about as useful as a screen door on a submarine. Travelling abroad? Prepare to spend a small fortune on what was once a relatively affordable adventure. And for the exporters? They might be laughing a little bit, considering a weaker dollar makes Australian goods cheaper for overseas buyers. But overall? This is a rough ride for most people with any international financial dealings.\nNow, what’s causing this particular disasterpiece? Well, surprise surprise, it’s the usual cocktail of issues. Weak domestic economic data, falling commodity prices (goodbye iron ore and coal), and rising interest rates globally (thanks, Federal Reserve!) have all contributed to this pitiful slide. Essentially, the Aussie dollar is now the financial equivalent of a dog in a rainstorm—wet, sad, and just hoping to get inside before it gets any worse. And let’s not forget that global uncertainty isn’t doing it any favors. The US economy’s been on a tear, and the Aussie dollar’s been left holding the bag.\nWhy should we care? Oh, let me count the ways. First, for the casual Aussie, this is a nightmare for imports. Everything from gadgets to groceries just got more expensive because, guess what? A weak currency means Australian businesses need more cash to buy the same stuff from overseas. Expect your latest Amazon purchases to come with a side of sticker shock. For the average punter, it’s an inconvenience. For businesses, it’s a real pain in the wallet.\nBut hey, it’s not all doom and gloom. If you’re someone who’s paid in US dollars or dealing in foreign markets, this is your moment to shine. Your dollar’s going further now—cheaper Australian assets, and hey, that real estate in the Outback just got a little cheaper. But for the rest of us? We’re stuck watching the Aussie dollar shrink while trying to pretend we’re not googling “How to relocate to Canada on a budget.”\nAs for the latest update? The Aussie dollar’s already spent several days lapping up its new sub-60 cent reality, and experts are suggesting that the worst could be yet to come. But at this point, can we be surprised? The dollar’s been on a slow decline for months, so we’re just witnessing the final moments of a “let’s see how low we can go” trend.\nTo sum it up: the Aussie dollar’s below 60 US cents now—because why not? It’s not like we haven’t seen it coming, right? After all, when the global economy’s a mess, why not throw in a little local currency drama for good measure?', 0, 'factabot', 'Aussie Dollar Dips Below 60 US Cents: Because Why Not?', 'draft', 'images/news/SHotPFR9DMP2P6jEvo5ytoO7MJpbZ5KbXPRdSvkD.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-04-07 03:13:03', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (253, 'Channel 7 Reporter vs. EV Influencer: The Showdown We Didn\'t Know We Needed', '-', 'A Channel 7 journalist and an electric vehicle influencer clashed at an auto show. Spoiler: No vehicles were harmed in the making of this drama. news\nSo, here’s the lowdown: Channel 7, the classic Aussie news outlet, recently got tangled in a fiery back-and-forth between one of their seasoned reporters and an electric vehicle (EV) influencer—and folks, it was a showdown for the ages. If you thought that climate change debates couldn’t get any more bizarre, think again.\nWho’s involved? The Channel 7 journalist leading the segment is none other than James Willis, a reporter with a reputation for asking tough questions and holding people’s feet to the fire. Willis, who’s been on the news beat for over a decade, is the kind of guy you’d expect to grill politicians or dig into the actual details of big-ticket issues. But instead, he found himself face-to-face with an influencer who lives and breathes electric cars—Lia Green. Green, the self-proclaimed \"EV Queen\", has made a name for herself on TikTok and Instagram, promoting electric vehicles as the future of transportation. With over half a million followers, Green’s mission is to spread the EV gospel, showing the world how amazing it is to drive a zero-emission vehicle while having an extra-long Instagram story with the perfect sunset filter.\nWhat happened? Willis was covering the recent surge in EV adoption for a Channel 7 segment. As part of the feature, he interviewed Green about the future of electric vehicles, the environmental benefits, and how Australia’s charging infrastructure is handling the influx of EVs. But what was meant to be a standard interview quickly devolved into fireworks when Willis asked the million-dollar question: “Are EVs really as practical as they’re made out to be for the average Australian? What about the charging issues and the environmental impact of batteries?”\nGreen, in true influencer fashion, fired back passionately, saying that EVs were the future, and we needed to stop making excuses. But Willis wasn’t having any of it—he pushed for real answers, highlighting the practical struggles that everyday Australians face when it comes to switching to EVs. And bam, the sparks flew! Green accused Willis of being too stuck in the “old way of thinking” while he shot back with some pretty pointed observations about eco-washing in the EV market. The debate wasn’t just about electric cars anymore; it was about the clash between hard-hitting journalism and passionate social media activism.\nWhy is this a big deal? Why should we care? Simple: It’s a glimpse into the tug-of-war between the old guard of journalism and the rise of influencer culture, especially when it comes to complex issues like climate change. Willis is trying to get to the truth, the nitty-gritty of how EVs are actually working for consumers, while Green wants to convince us that everything is perfectly fine and that we should all be driving Teslas and feeling smug about it. This isn’t just a disagreement about electric cars—it’s a microcosm of the battle for how information gets consumed these days. Do we trust journalists who dig for the facts, or influencers who package their message with a bow on top for maximum likes?\nWhen did this go down? This juicy little exchange happened earlier this week on the 7News channel during a segment aired on April 7, 2025. The video clip is already going viral, being shared by EV enthusiasts, climate change activists, and people who just like watching awkwardly intense interviews unfold.\nHow did it all unfold? Well, after the heated moment on air, the internet naturally did what it does best: it took sides. The EV influencer crowd has rallied behind Green, blasting Willis for being a “climate skeptic” and accusing him of undermining the movement. Meanwhile, the more skeptical Aussies are all over Willis’ take, praising him for not falling for “greenwashing” and actually asking the tough questions. Social media has exploded, and a war of memes and hashtags has begun. You can expect Green to keep posting her EV tips with an extra sprinkle of righteousness, while Willis is likely busy working on his next uncomfortable interview.\nLatest Update? Well, Green’s probably already scheduled a TikTok live stream to “set the record straight” while Willis, if we’re lucky, might get another interview—but this time, with someone who isn’t out to turn it into an eco-propaganda piece. Either way, this unexpected showdown has sparked more conversations than anyone could’ve imagined—and it’s a perfect reflection of how complicated, and dramatic, the climate conversation has become.\nSo, next time you see someone on Instagram grinning next to their shiny new EV, just remember: somewhere out there, Willis is probably wondering if their charging station has enough power to get through the next set of tough questions.', 0, 'factabot', 'Channel 7 Reporter vs. EV Influencer: The Showdown We Didn\'t Know We Needed', 'draft', 'images/news/SHotPFR9DMP2P6jEvo5ytoO7MJpbZ5KbXPRdSvkD.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-05-01 18:29:19', 20);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (254, 'Last Call to Enrol to Vote: Because Democracy Waits for No One', '-', 'Today\'s the final day to enrol to vote in the federal election. Miss it, and you\'ll have to find another way to complain about the government. ABC\nTick-tock, Aussies! The Australian Electoral Commission (AEC) has been shouting from the rooftops that the deadline to enrol or update your details is tonight at 8pm local time. With voting being compulsory, missing out could mean a $20 fine—enough for a couple of flat whites. Canberra Times+10Australian Electoral Commission+10New England Times+10ABC+2ABC+2news+2\nSince the election was announced, around 200,000 proactive citizens have either enrolled or updated their details. The AEC is making it easier than ever, allowing enrolment with just a Medicare card. Despite these efforts, some folks are still dragging their feet.ABC+2Australian Electoral Commission+2New England Times+2\nThis election is particularly spicy. Prime Minister Anthony Albanese is vying for a second term, while opposition leader Peter Dutton is attempting a comeback after a term in opposition. With all 150 seats in the House of Representatives and 40 of the 76 Senate seats up for grabs, every vote counts. Skipping enrolment means missing out on shaping the nation\'s future—and let\'s be honest, complaining about the government without voting is a bit rich.ABC+2The Guardian+29News+2Wikipedia+1The Guardian+1\nAs of now, more than 18 million Australians are enrolled to vote, marking the highest enrolment rate in history. Yet, the AEC is still urging those who\'ve recently moved, changed names, or just turned 18 to get their act together before the deadline. So, if you haven\'t enrolled yet, it\'s time to adult up. Visit the AEC website, spend five minutes, and secure your spot in the democratic process. After all, if you don\'t vote, you can\'t complain—and where\'s the fun in that?', 0, 'factabot', 'Last Call to Enrol to Vote: Because Democracy Waits for No One', 'draft', 'images/news/SHotPFR9DMP2P6jEvo5ytoO7MJpbZ5KbXPRdSvkD.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-05-01 16:22:12', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (255, 'Plane Passenger\'s \'Door Opening\' Antics: Because What\'s a Flight Without a Little Drama?', '-', 'A man faces up to 30 years in jail after allegedly trying to open the door mid-flight from Malaysia to Sydney. Guess he wanted an early exit. news\r\n\r\nMeet Shadi Taiseer Alsaaydeh, a 46-year-old Jordanian who apparently mistook his AirAsia flight from Kuala Lumpur to Sydney for an open-air experience. Mid-flight on April 5, 2025, Alsaaydeh allegedly attempted to open not one, but two emergency exit doors. After his initial attempt at the rear exit was thwarted, he was relocated to a middle seat—because changing scenery always helps, right? Undeterred, he reportedly tried his luck again with another exit, leading to a scuffle where he allegedly assaulted a crew member before being restrained by passengers and staff. People.com+2The Guardian+2dailytelegraph+2dailytelegraph+3People.com+3The Guardian+3New York Post+1news+11News+6dailytelegraph+6news+6\r\nThis high-altitude drama unfolded on an AirAsia flight from Kuala Lumpur to Sydney. The Australian Federal Police (AFP) were alerted and promptly arrested Alsaaydeh upon landing. He\'s now facing two counts of endangering the safety of an aircraft and one count of assaulting an aircraft crew member, each carrying a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison. dailytelegraph+37NEWS+3New York Post+3dailytelegraph+5New York Post+5news+5\r\nIn a plot twist that no one asked for, this incident isn\'t a one-off. Just days prior, a Jetstar flight from Bali to Melbourne had to turn back after a passenger attempted to open a door mid-flight over the Indian Ocean. The captain\'s announcement summed it up: \"Earlier tonight, there was a lady down back at the aircraft that tried to physically open the door... we got a door warning in the front of the aircraft.\" Is there a new trend of mile-high door-opening attempts that we missed?Log in or sign up to view+5People.com+5dailytelegraph+5\r\nAs for our main character, Alsaaydeh, he\'s set to appear in Parramatta Local Court on April 9. The AFP has made it clear that such behavior won\'t be tolerated, emphasizing the potential catastrophic consequences. So, the next time you\'re on a flight and feel the urge to stretch your legs, maybe just stick to the aisle.news+4dailytelegraph+4The Guardian+4New York Post', 0, 'factabot', 'Plane_Passenger\'s_\'Door_Opening\'_Antics:_Because_What\'s_a_Flight_Without_a_Little_Drama', 'draft', 'images/news/C5b3MdpRomuY3588h5hLn7O74XCXuEGOOUNSwxeE.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-05-01 20:31:20', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (256, 'Australia\'s Shocking Six-Figure Trend: Millennials and Gen X Ditching $140K Jobs for... What Exactly?', '-', 'New research reveals a grim trend as millennials and Gen X workers leave six-figure jobs. Apparently, money can\'t buy happiness, but it can buy a one-way ticket to \'find yourself\' overseas. news\nIn a plot twist that would make your career counselor clutch their pearls, a growing number of Australian Millennials and Gen Xers are waving goodbye to their cushy six-figure salaries. Why? To chase dreams, find purpose, or perhaps just to avoid another soul-crushing Zoom meeting. Take 28-year-old Zoe Sheehan, for example. Earning between $170,000 to $180,000 annually as a product designer, she felt \"chained to her desk\" and uninspired. So, she ditched the corporate grind to freelance, now raking in $900 a day and dabbling in creative ventures like writing a book and launching an e-commerce business. news+2news+2Reddit+2news\nThis mass exodus from high-paying gigs isn\'t just about midlife crises or a sudden urge to \"find oneself.\" A SEEK survey revealed that a majority of workers across generations regret their career choices, with financial dissatisfaction topping the list of grievances. Specifically, 54% of Millennials and 57% of Gen Xers expressed remorse, citing low earnings, unfulfilling work, and poor work-life balance as culprits. Yet, despite these regrets, only a meager 7% are actively pursuing a new career path. news\nSo, why the sudden urge to swap boardrooms for passion projects? The COVID-19 pandemic served as a wake-up call, prompting many to reevaluate their life choices. Rising living costs, rapid technological changes, and a job market that feels more like a game of musical chairs have only added fuel to the fire. Career counselors are now emphasizing the importance of planning, skill assessment, and open communication for those daring to make the leap. news\nAs of now, this trend shows no signs of slowing down. Experts predict that frequent career reinvention will become the norm, with adaptability being the golden ticket. While some may view this as a risky move, many who\'ve taken the plunge report increased job satisfaction, freedom, and a renewed sense of purpose. So, if you\'re contemplating trading your corporate badge for a yoga mat or a pottery wheel, you\'re not alone. Just remember to update your LinkedIn profile—your former colleagues are dying to know what you\'re up to.news', 0, 'factabot', 'Australia\'s Shocking Six-Figure Trend: Millennials and Gen X Ditching $140K Jobs for... What Exactly?', 'draft', 'images/news/SHotPFR9DMP2P6jEvo5ytoO7MJpbZ5KbXPRdSvkD.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-04-07 03:13:03', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (257, 'Sydney\'s Waterfront Property Market: Where the Rich Get Richer and the Rest of Us Just Stare', '-', 'Sydney\'s waterfront property market is, unsurprisingly, going through the roof, with prices breaking records faster than a toddler can destroy a Lego tower. Apparently, having a view of the Harbour Bridge or a slice of Bondi Beach is now the ultimate status symbol. Forget about that tiny studio apartment in the suburbs—if you don’t have a multi-million-dollar mansion with uninterrupted water views, are you even living?\nOver the past year, waterfront properties have sold for more money than the average Aussie could earn in a lifetime. Seriously, these prices are shocking—like, \"did I hear that right, or was that the price for a luxury yacht?\" shocking. The wealthy elite seem to be the only ones getting in on the action, with bids flying in faster than a Melbourne Cup horse on race day. It\'s as if there’s a secret competition to see who can own the most expensive slice of Sydney\'s coastline. And while the high-end buyers are popping champagne in their new luxury penthouses, the rest of us are still figuring out how to make rent while dodging another overpriced avocado toast at brunch.\nEconomists are scratching their heads, wondering where this influx of cash is coming from. \"Immigration-driven demand\" and \"pandemic-inspired need for space\" are being thrown around like buzzwords at a startup pitch meeting. Apparently, this boom is being fueled by wealthy investors looking for their next big purchase (I mean, what else are you going to do with all that money?), as well as international buyers looking to claim a little piece of Sydney’s exclusive coastline.\nBut here’s the kicker: while these waterfront properties continue to hit the market at jaw-dropping prices, regular Aussies are finding themselves priced out more than ever. Dreaming of a spacious home with a backyard? Dream on, buddy. At this rate, you’re better off asking the ocean if it’ll give you a free spot on its shores, because getting a foothold in this market seems about as realistic as getting into a VIP party without an invite. So yeah, the \"big picture\" here is that the rich continue to get richer, while the rest of us get to enjoy the view—from a distance.', 0, 'factabot', 'Sydney\'s Waterfront Property Market: Where the Rich Get Richer and the Rest of Us Just Stare', 'draft', 'images/news/SHotPFR9DMP2P6jEvo5ytoO7MJpbZ5KbXPRdSvkD.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-04-24 18:45:12', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (258, '\"Australia’s Inflation Nightmare: More Price Hikes, Less Pay', '-', 'So, let’s talk about Australia’s lovely little inflation crisis. You know, that thing where everything costs more but your paycheck seems to be stuck in a time loop? Yeah, it’s still going strong. From the price of your morning coffee to the groceries that now require a second mortgage to purchase, inflation is not going anywhere. Experts are pointing fingers, of course, blaming a cocktail of supply chain issues, higher global energy prices, and the ever-persistent demand for “stuff” that we probably don’t even need (yet here we are, buying it).\nIt’s especially fun when the wage growth just can’t keep up with the rising costs. Australians are now finding that while their salaries are inching up at a pace slower than a sloth on a lazy day, the prices for literally everything are skyrocketing. Seriously, you thought that avocado toast was a luxury five years ago? Well, now it’s an investment in your mental health and probably one of the few affordable meals you can get in this inflationary wonderland. Fancy a holiday? Good luck with that—unless you’re okay with staying in a glorified tent and eating baked beans every night.\nAnd as for the government? Well, their “solutions” are as helpful as giving a Band-Aid to someone who needs a cast. They’re talking about lowering interest rates, but it’s like putting a small, sparkly Band-Aid over a leaky dam. The truth is, inflation’s getting more comfortable in Australia than a koala in a eucalyptus tree, and it’s not ready to leave anytime soon. People are just holding their breath, hoping that somehow—miraculously—things will get better. Spoiler alert: they won’t.\nSo, what’s the takeaway from this economic circus? If you’ve got money saved, good for you. If not, well... maybe start collecting cans for that rainy day, because at the rate we’re going, your next paycheck might only be enough to cover one of your weekly grocery trips. Cheers to that.', 0, 'factabot', '\"Australia’s Inflation Nightmare: More Price Hikes, Less Pay', 'draft', 'images/news/SHotPFR9DMP2P6jEvo5ytoO7MJpbZ5KbXPRdSvkD.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-05-01 22:10:15', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (259, 'Sydney\'s Harborside Restaurants: Where Your Wallet Shrinks Faster Than Your Waistline', '-', '\"Sydney\'s Restaurant Scene: Dining Out Is Now a Luxury, Not a Choice\"\nIn case you hadn’t noticed, Sydney’s restaurant scene has gone from \"casual night out\" to \"is this the cost of a small car?\" The price of dining out has reached such levels that you’d need to take out a personal loan just to grab a meal at some of the city’s trendiest hotspots. The days of grabbing a quick bite for under $20? Gone. These days, you’re looking at $40 for a main and $15 for a side of fries, because why not throw a small fortune into the deep fryer?\nFor those of us still holding onto the hope of a “cheap” date night, we can forget it. The so-called “affordable” spots are as rare as a unicorn, and even a trip to a local café feels like you’re paying for a three-course meal at a Michelin-starred restaurant. It’s as though Sydney\'s eateries decided to take the whole “luxury dining experience” a little too literally, and now you’re expected to fork over half your paycheck for some duck confit that could fit in the palm of your hand. Oh, and don\'t even think about asking for a tap water refill without a side of judgement.\nWhy the price hike, you ask? Well, in true Sydney style, it’s a mix of factors—rising ingredient costs, higher rent, and of course, the post-pandemic “rebound” where restaurants are determined to make up for lost time (and profits). That means you\'re not just paying for your meal; you’re paying for the trauma of 2020, with a nice glass of wine to drown it.\nThe latest twist in this culinary nightmare? Australians are starting to feel the sting, with many now opting for delivery or home-cooked meals, which, ironically, still end up costing a fortune when you add in delivery fees. So, it looks like dining out is officially a luxury—unless you count grabbing a kebab on your way home as \"fine dining.\" Guess we’re all going to have to start budgeting like we’re planning for a vacation, but instead, it’s just a night out to get a meal that doesn’t come in a box.', 0, 'factabot', 'Sydney\'s Harborside Restaurants: Where Your Wallet Shrinks Faster Than Your Waistline', 'draft', 'images/news/SHotPFR9DMP2P6jEvo5ytoO7MJpbZ5KbXPRdSvkD.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-04-27 17:24:41', 22);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (260, 'Australian Tech Startup Gets $20 Million... Just to \'Try\' Something New', '-', 'Okay, picture this: a bunch of brilliant tech bros—probably wearing overpriced sneakers and sipping on artisanal coffee—have just dropped their shiny new app, and it’s already raking in $20 million. The app? It’s called ‘Flare,’ a ‘game-changing’ social platform promising to revolutionize the way we connect. No, it’s not an app for connecting with loved ones or solving world problems. It\'s supposedly a social networking app where you share your “highly valuable” thoughts in real-time, but with an AI-powered twist (I mean, who doesn’t love a buzzword?). These masterminds, who probably think they’ve reinvented the wheel, are the ones hoping to change the world—while they sit in a neon-lit co-working space, surrounded by people who genuinely think blockchain is a cure-all.\n\nSo what exactly is Flare? Well, after shelling out a jaw-dropping $20 million for a product that could be anything from a slightly fancier Twitter clone to some weird self-help app, here’s what we know: It’s a “real-time thought-sharing platform” where users can post their latest “insights” in the form of AI-generated quick thoughts. You know, because writing a tweet yourself is so last century—why not let some robot do the heavy lifting? The app promises to “change the way we communicate,” because clearly, no one’s satisfied with just chatting, posting photos, or gasp reading an article. The founders, all in their mid-20s, swear this will create a new era of \"mindful sharing\" (with, of course, an in-app purchase option for exclusive \"thoughts of the day\"). The question is: Does anyone actually want to share their unfiltered, AI-approved, robot-optimized ideas with the world? We’ll see.\n\nWhy is this even happening now, you ask? Well, if you’ve been living under a rock, you might have missed the recent tech boom, where every investor thinks they can make a fortune by slapping “AI” or “blockchain” on their latest pet project and selling it as a world-changing idea. The tech world is in desperate need of the next big thing—because clearly, the plethora of social media apps we already have just aren’t enough. The timing, however, couldn\'t be more... convenient. With the pandemic-induced rise in digital connections and a world that can’t seem to stop scrolling, Flare is hoping to fill a gap that may not even exist. They’re selling us the dream of AI-powered personal connection, and we’re all expected to buy into it—because, who doesn’t want to have their every fleeting thought be perfectly curated by an algorithm?\nAnd while we’re at it, let’s talk about how Flare is trying to solve something that isn’t even really broken. We’ve got Facebook, Instagram, Twitter (RIP Vine), and now Flare promises to give us the AI-boosted, post-Gen Z alternative to share... what exactly? Oh, that’s right, your deep, profound thoughts about what you had for breakfast—served to you by an algorithm that’s “learning” from your emotional state and social media activity. Nothing screams \"cutting-edge\" like that, right?\n• The Latest Update (20%)\nOkay, hold your horses. Flare isn’t exactly the next Facebook (or even the next TikTok, for that matter). Despite securing that hefty $20 million in funding, they’re still struggling to launch a beta version that actually works. It’s still in “beta,” of course—that magical tech term for “we’re not really sure if this will work, but hey, take a look at our cool website.” As of now, the app is basically a glorified “coming soon” page with a countdown clock, because why launch when you can keep people hanging on the edge of their seats for a little longer? Investors are, unsurprisingly, a bit nervous, but hey, maybe Flare will finally get it together and make $20 million look like a genius investment. Or maybe we’ll all be stuck with yet another abandoned app in the digital graveyard of great ideas that should’ve stayed in a PowerPoint.\nSo, to sum it up: another day, another tech startup hoping to solve problems that don’t actually exist, all while riding the “AI is the future!” wave until it crashes and burns. Stay tuned, or don’t—because by the time this launches, we’ll all probably be on to the next shiny thing.', 0, 'factabot', 'Australian Tech Startup Gets $20 Million... Just to \'Try\' Something New', 'draft', 'images/news/SHotPFR9DMP2P6jEvo5ytoO7MJpbZ5KbXPRdSvkD.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-05-07 04:42:18', 27);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (261, 'Queensland’s Shark Sightings: ‘Just Another Day in Paradise', '-', 'Queensland beaches are flooded with shark sightings, and the locals are like, \"Yep, that’s how we do it here.\"\r\n😎 Swimming with sharks? More like living with them. (couriermail.com.au)\r\nAh, Queensland—the Sunshine State where the beaches are golden, the waters are inviting, and the local marine life occasionally reminds you who\'s boss. In the latest episode of \"Nature Keeps Us Humble,\" a two-meter reef shark decided to spice things up by taking a dip in the swimming enclosure at Four Mile Beach in Port Douglas. This surprise guest appearance prompted a swift evacuation of swimmers, because nothing says \"relaxing swim\" like a shark joining the party. Authorities suspect the shark slipped in during high tides reaching up to 2.65 meters, effectively bypassing the enclosure meant to keep such visitors out. Thankfully, the uninvited guest was safely escorted back to open waters, leaving beachgoers with a tale to tell. news\r\nThis finned cameo comes on the heels of some less amusing shark encounters in Queensland. Earlier this year, the state recorded its fourth shark attack when a 29-year-old man was bitten near Moreton Island\'s Wrecks Walking Track. This incident followed the tragic death of 17-year-old Charlize Zmuda at Bribie Island, marking a concerning uptick in shark-related incidents. Log in or sign up to view+3Karmactive+37NEWS+3\r\nSo, why does it feel like sharks are suddenly vying for the spotlight? Experts suggest that factors like changing water temperatures, overfishing, and habitat disruptions might be driving sharks closer to shore. Combine that with more people flocking to the beaches, and you\'ve got a recipe for increased encounters. It\'s a classic case of \"we\'re in their house,\" but some folks seem surprised when the landlords show up.\r\nIn response to these close encounters of the shark kind, local authorities are doubling down on safety measures. Lifeguards are urging swimmers to stay vigilant, especially during dawn and dusk when sharks are more active. They\'re also reminding everyone to avoid swimming in murky waters or near schools of fish—because blending in with shark snacks is generally ill-advised. While the odds of a shark encounter remain low, it\'s always best to play it safe. After all, it\'s all fun and games until Jaws decides to photobomb your beach day.', 0, 'factabot', 'Queensland’s_Shark_Sightings:_‘Just_Another_Day_in_Paradise', 'draft', 'images/news/M0fnM6vBPmtuKuq0dmXz1fF9Fch5PCdbLnvD7fU2.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-05-04 12:50:32', 28);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (262, 'Victoria’s Undercover Cops: How to Be a Cop and Look Like a Hot Mess', '-', 'An undercover cop in Victoria managed to pull off an impressive job... blending in as a totally confused and disheveled person in the crowd.\r\n👀 Subtlety is an art, folks. (theage.com.au)\r\nVictoria Police’s undercover unit is making headlines—not for busting drug rings or infiltrating gangs—but for looking like they got dressed in the dark at a garage sale. Yes, in their noble quest to blend in with the public, some of Victoria’s finest are now looking less \"cop in disguise\" and more \"hipster who lost a bet.\" We\'re talking stained hoodies, mullets that defy physics, and enough cargo pants to open a tactical surplus store.\r\nThe whole idea was to go incognito—you know, undercover. But apparently, some officers took that as “under whatever’s in the laundry basket.” Instead of looking like everyday Aussies, some look like extras from a very low-budget soap opera set in a food court. The issue? People are starting to clock them instantly. Because nothing says “undercover cop” like someone awkwardly loitering with a notepad and a haircut from 2003.\r\nVictoria Police does technically have an appearance policy that requires officers to project professionalism and discipline—even in plain clothes. But when you’ve got officers rolling into surveillance ops looking like they just finished a shift at Bunnings, that whole “respect the badge” vibe kind of takes a hit. Sure, blending in is part of the job, but there’s a fine line between street-smart and street-shambles.\r\nPolice have doubled down, insisting their undercover teams are effective and their “hot mess chic” is actually part of a deliberate strategy to blend in. Which, to be fair, is working—if they’re trying to infiltrate your cousin\'s backyard BBQ. But as public criticism ramps up and memes inevitably roll in, maybe it’s time for Victoria’s undercover cops to ask the real question: can you fight crime and still look like you own a mirror?', 0, 'factabot', 'Victoria’s_Undercover_Cops:_How_to_Be_a_Cop_and_Look_Like_a_Hot_Mess', 'draft', 'images/news/7KCF1gaG58O8NkLfNSouLu0zB5WgOz9FgzdbnXw9.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-05-03 05:18:32', 25);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (263, 'Aussie Workers Resigning in Droves: No One Wants to Work Anymore?', '-', 'Australia’s resignation rates are sky-high, leaving bosses wondering if it\'s a mass rebellion or just an elaborate \'out-of-office\' message.\r\n🤔 Turns out, millennials prefer freedom over forever-scheduling meetings. (abc.net.au)\r\nIn a move that\'s got corporate Australia clutching its pearls, millions of Aussie workers are handing in their resignation letters faster than you can say \"exit interview.\" According to a survey by employment site Indeed, a staggering 5.5 million Australians are likely to seek new job opportunities in the coming year. That\'s not just a trickle through the office turnstile; it\'s a full-blown stampede.Yahoo Finance\r\nSo, what\'s driving this mass workplace exodus? Burnout is leading the charge, with half the workforce feeling more fried than a Bunnings sausage sizzle. A study by Allianz Australia revealed that about 2.7 million workers plan to quit within the next 12 months, citing relentless workloads and a desperate need for balance. It\'s less about climbing the corporate ladder and more about finding a sturdy hammock.news\r\nThe pandemic didn\'t just introduce us to sourdough baking and questionable home haircuts; it also sparked a \"great rethink\" about career satisfaction. Professionals are now prioritizing purpose over paychecks, flexibility over corner offices. The rising cost of living and rapid technological changes have only added fuel to the fire, prompting many to swap their high-paying gigs for roles that align more closely with their values. It\'s like a mid-life crisis, but with more LinkedIn updates and fewer sports cars.news+1theguardian.com+1\r\nIn response to this tidal wave of resignations, companies are scrambling to retain talent, offering everything from mental health days to flexible work arrangements. But as the allure of passion projects and work-life balance grows stronger, employers might need to do more than just install a ping-pong table in the break room. After all, when it comes to choosing between a toxic work environment and personal well-being, Aussies are making it clear: no job is worth losing your sanity over.', 0, 'factabot', 'Aussie_Workers_Resigning_in_Droves:_No_One_Wants_to_Work_Anymore', 'draft', 'images/news/g4TYQNhyUWG7TsTAB3D3fJKIuxTTsQxQjpDXLbUv.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-05-01 16:04:34', 24);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (264, 'Australian Farmers Grow Wine for the Mind, Not the Stomach', '-', 'Aussie wine farmers have started growing wine designed not for taste, but for \"the mind,\" because who needs a good grape when you can have thoughts?\r\n🍇 Just what we needed – wine for existential crises. (news.com.au)\r\nIn the latest plot twist of Australia\'s agricultural saga, farmers are swapping their wine glasses for test tubes, diving headfirst into the world of medicinal plants. After years of producing more Shiraz than the world could sip, leading to a grape glut of epic proportions, these growers are now planting crops that promise to heal more than just a broken heart.\r\nThe wine industry has been drowning in its own success, with vineyards producing an ocean of vino that even the most enthusiastic drinkers couldn\'t keep up with. This surplus led to plummeting grape prices and left many farmers feeling like they were stuck in a never-ending happy hour without the happy. In a dramatic move, some decided to rip out millions of vines, essentially giving their vineyards a hard reset. sommelier-jobs.comsommelier-jobs.com+5ABS-CBN+5CellarTracker+5\r\nEnter the green knights: medicinal plants. Farmers are now cultivating crops like medicinal cannabis, tapping into the booming wellness industry. This shift isn\'t just about chasing profits; it\'s about survival and staying relevant in a market that\'s as unpredictable as a kangaroo on a trampoline.The Straits Times+1sommelier-jobs.com+1The Straits Times+7The Wine Gourd+7Reuters Archive Licensing+7\r\nThis agricultural pivot reflects a broader trend of adaptability among Australian farmers. Faced with challenges like climate change, shifting consumer preferences, and international trade hiccups, these growers are proving they\'re not afraid to change crops mid-row. It\'s a testament to their resilience and perhaps a nod to the age-old wisdom: don\'t put all your grapes in one basket.\r\nWhile the move from Merlot to medicinal herbs might raise some eyebrows among traditionalists, it\'s a savvy play in a world where wellness is the new black. As the global demand for medicinal plants grows, Australian farmers are positioning themselves at the forefront of this green revolution. So, next time you reach for that bottle of Aussie red, remember: it might soon be accompanied by a side of locally grown herbal remedies. Cheers to that!', 0, 'factabot', 'Australian_Farmers_Grow_Wine_for_the_Mind,_Not_the_Stomach', 'draft', 'images/news/NxOooRev0RCC9Vcm2L0dRVIjZLlWwOqMiXalBkGO.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-05-01 17:26:34', 23);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (265, 'New Aussie Museum: \'Come See the Stuff You’ve Already Seen in Your Grandma’s House\'', '-', 'A new museum is showcasing vintage memorabilia that’s eerily familiar to anyone who’s ever been to their grandparent’s house.\r\n\r\nIn a move that has curators and hoarders alike rejoicing, Australia\'s latest museum invites visitors to experience the nostalgic charm of everyday household items. Think less \"cutting-edge exhibits\" and more \"grandma\'s attic,\" offering a sentimental journey through the relics of domestic life.\r\nStep into a world where Tupperware isn\'t just for leftovers and porcelain figurines aren\'t just dust collectors. This museum showcases items that have graced Australian homes for decades, if not centuries. From rotary dial telephones that doubled as arm workouts to crocheted doilies that served as both decor and impromptu coasters, the collection is a testament to the enduring nature of domestic artifacts.\r\nHighlights of the Collection\r\n•	The \"Avocado Green\" Kitchen: Relive the glory days of 1970s interior design with appliances and decor in everyone\'s favorite retro hue.\r\n•	The Encyclopedia Britannica Corner: For those who remember a time before Wikipedia, this section offers a glimpse into the weighty volumes that once held the answers to all our questions.\r\n•	The Vinyl Vault: Spin some records and reminisce about a time when music was stored on large, easily scratched discs.\r\nGuests are encouraged to interact with exhibits, perhaps even sharing their own stories of family heirlooms and forgotten gadgets. Workshops on \"How to Use a Film Camera\" and \"Writing Letters with Pen and Ink\" are also available for those looking to disconnect from the digital world.\r\nThis museum serves as a loving tribute to the objects that have shaped our homes and memories. It\'s a place where the past is not only remembered but celebrated, proving that one person\'s clutter is another\'s cultural heritage', 0, 'factabot', 'New_Aussie_Museum:_\'Come_See_the_Stuff_You’ve_Already_Seen_in_Your_Grandma’s_House\'', 'draft', 'images/news/SHotPFR9DMP2P6jEvo5ytoO7MJpbZ5KbXPRdSvkD.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-05-05 15:35:55', 27);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (266, 'Australian Cyclists: Breaking Speed Limits and Their Own Bones', '-', 'Aussie cyclists are breaking speed records and occasionally their bones, as bike lanes turn into high-speed racing tracks.\r\n⚡ Gotta go fast... but maybe consider a helmet, just in case. (theaustralian.com.au)\r\nIn the land down under, where kangaroos box and Vegemite reigns supreme, cyclists are apparently channeling their inner speed demons. From dodging traffic fines to narrowly escaping vehicular disaster, Aussie cyclists are giving Evel Knievel a run for his money.\r\nTake Centennial Park in Sydney, for instance. This picturesque spot has become the racetrack of choice for \"Lycra-clad speedsters\" zooming around Grand Drive. While cars adhere to the 30 km/h limit, some cyclists seem to think they\'re auditioning for the Tour de France, leaving pedestrians clutching their hats and hearts. One concerned local aptly described this behavior as an \"accident waiting to happen.\" news\r\nVictoria\'s Operation River Run took a stand, charging 45 riders—including 16 Bicycle Network members—for exceeding the 10 km/h speed limit along Southbank Promenade. Fines soared up to $1,652.20, prompting debates about whether cyclists are being unfairly penalized compared to their motorized counterparts. Bicycle Network\r\nNot to be left behind, New South Wales introduced some of the world\'s strictest cycling laws. Riders caught without helmets face fines of up to $319, and running a red light can set you back $425. These hefty penalties have some questioning if Australia\'s love for cycling is being overshadowed by a need for revenue. The Lawyer Magazine\r\nIt\'s not just about speeding tickets. A recent incident on Main South Road involved a cyclist on a recumbent bike causing a near-collision between a truck and a 4WD. This sparked debates about whether certain roads should be off-limits to cyclists, especially when their choice of route seems more suited for a stunt show than safe travel. adelaidenow+1adelaidenow+1\r\nWhile the thrill of the ride is undeniable, perhaps it\'s time for Aussie cyclists to pump the brakes. Balancing speed with safety ensures that the only thing getting hurt is their pride—not their bones or their wallets.\r\nDisclaimer: No kangaroos were harmed in the making of this article.', 0, 'factabot', 'Australian_Cyclists:_Breaking_Speed_Limits_and_Their_Own_Bones', 'draft', 'images/news/U98AHzXXvX60aJcTvssBYhmaiopDoHeQ0mgVally.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-07 03:13:03', '2025-05-01 21:22:25', 37);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (294, 'Doctors Ditch Stethoscopes for Picket Signs in Three-Day Tantrum', '-', 'In a plot twist worthy of a medical drama, over 5,000 New South Wales doctors have swapped their scrubs for protest placards, embarking on a three-day strike that kicked off today. Led by the Australian Salaried Medical Officers’ Federation (ASMOF), this disgruntled battalion of stethoscope-wielding warriors is demanding a 30% pay bump—basically asking to be paid like their Queensland and Victorian colleagues, who apparently didn’t get the short straw in the medical pay lottery. Nothing says “take us seriously” like a hospital hallway turned picket line. [news.com.au]\n\nBut make no mistake—this isn’t just a dramatic episode of \"Grey’s Anatomy: Sydney Edition.\" These doctors are complaining of shifts so long they’re practically time travelers, routinely working 16 hours back-to-back. ASMOF says the current setup is so unsafe that even a caffeine IV couldn’t fix it. And with more and more doctors exiting stage left from the public system, the pressure cooker’s starting to whistle. [news.com.au]\n\nHealth Minister Ryan Park, in a classic “please-don’t-make-me-look-bad” move, offered a 10.5% pay rise over three years, plus a 3% backdated bonus—if they’d just kindly stop striking. But ASMOF clapped back with a firm \"nope,\" arguing that tossing a few bucks at a collapsing system is like offering a defibrillator to a ghost. They want a full review of wages and working conditions, not just crumbs from the budget banquet. [The Australian]\n\nAnd here\'s the kicker: while the government is suddenly Very Concerned™ about patient safety during this strike, the irony is thicker than hospital-grade hand sanitizer. If the system were actually safe, doctors wouldn’t be fleeing faster than interns during a night shift. Elective surgeries are paused, specialist clinics shuttered, and patients told to sit tight while the political theatre unfolds. Because nothing says \"healthcare priorities\" like waiting lists that grow longer by the day. [Daily Telegraph]\n\nAs the strike lumbers into its next act, hospitals are running like it’s Christmas Day—but without the ham or good vibes. Emergency services are still running, but elective surgeries and outpatient clinics? Cancelled like a bad reality show. So far, neither side is blinking, and the only thing escalating faster than the tension is the number of postponed procedures. Paging common sense—STAT. [The Australian]', 0, 'factabot', 'Doctors Ditch Stethoscopes for Picket Signs in Three-Day Tantrum', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-08 03:46:05', '2025-05-02 02:11:16', 20);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (295, 'Sydney Airport Braces for Easter Onslaught: Chaos Expected', '-', 'Sydney Airport is prepping for its annual Easter meltdown, with a casual 2.5 million passengers expected to stampede through its gates like it’s the final boarding call for salvation. The airport\'s PR team, visibly sweating in media interviews, says this will be the busiest Easter since COVID stopped people from breathing on each other in queues. That’s 1 million international and 1.5 million domestic travellers—basically half of Sydney and a sprinkle of Bali-bound influencers. [Daily Telegraph]\n\nApparently, April 17 and 18 are shaping up to be “Peak Chaos” days. Domestic flights will see 85,000 caffeine-fuelled passengers trying to out-sprint each other to Gate 57, while international terminals expect 53,000 souls dragging oversized suitcases stuffed with bad decisions and duty-free dreams. Airport officials, in their infinite optimism, are advising folks to arrive “at least” an hour before departure for carry-on, two hours if you have baggage, and three if you enjoy waiting in security lines behind people who forgot their belts beep. [Daily Telegraph]\n\nTo manage the madness, Sydney Airport has thrown money at the problem—$200 million to upgrade the T2 Domestic terminal and install new screening lanes in T1. Because nothing says efficiency like building just in time for the onslaught. They\'ve also rolled out Easter-themed gimmicks like chocolate giveaways and giant photo booths—because when you\'re stuck in a queue for 40 minutes, what you really need is a selfie with a six-foot animatronic bunny. [Daily Telegraph]\n\nDespite all this prep, delays are expected, of course. But the airport is flexing its \"99% of passengers cleared in under 10 minutes\" stat like a gym bro showing off last month’s bench press. With flight schedules tighter than budget airline legroom, Sydney’s aviation circus is about to begin. Travellers, bring snacks. And patience. Lots of it. [Daily Telegraph]', 0, 'factabot', 'Sydney Airport Braces for Easter Onslaught: Chaos Expected', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-08 03:46:05', '2025-05-01 14:32:13', 22);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (296, 'ASX Attempts Comeback After Historic Faceplant', '-', '​After a dramatic nosedive that saw the S&P/ASX 200 index plummet over 4%—erasing nearly $100 billion in value and marking its worst single-day performance in five years—the Australian stock market is attempting to pick itself up off the floor. The culprit behind this financial faceplant? A fresh round of tariff tantrums from former U.S. President Donald Trump, reigniting fears of a global trade war and sending investors into a selling frenzy. ​\nThe Guardian\n+1\nDiscovery Alert\n+1\n\nIn a move that surprised absolutely no one, Trump unveiled his \"liberation day\" trade plan, slapping new tariffs on China and prompting threats of retaliation from Beijing and the EU. This geopolitical chest-thumping sent shockwaves through global markets, with Australia\'s resource-heavy economy feeling the brunt of the blow. Major players like BHP and Rio Tinto saw their shares tumble faster than a dropped meat pie at a footy match. ​\nThe Guardian\n+1\nMarket Index\n+1\nThe Australian\n+2\nABC\n+2\nDiscovery Alert\n+2\n\nBut let\'s not pretend this is all about Trump\'s tariff tirades. The ASX has been on a bit of a rollercoaster lately, with inflation fears and whispers of an impending recession adding to the market\'s jitters. Analysts are now eyeing the Reserve Bank of Australia, hoping for some monetary policy magic to steady the ship. Meanwhile, everyday investors are left clutching their portfolios, wondering if now\'s the time to buy the dip or just dip out entirely. ​\nInvesting.com Australia\n+8\nMarket Index\n+8\nThe Guardian\n+8\n\nAs the dust settles, the ASX is showing signs of life, clawing back some of its losses in early trading. But whether this is the start of a genuine recovery or just a dead cat bounce remains to be seen. One thing\'s for sure: in the high-stakes game of global finance, it\'s always wise to expect the unexpected.', 0, 'factabot', 'ASX Attempts Comeback After Historic Faceplant', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-08 03:46:05', '2025-05-01 20:53:18', 25);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (297, 'Dutton Foresees Global Recession: Thanks, Captain Obvious', '-', '​In a revelation that surely left Australians gobsmacked, Opposition Leader Peter Dutton has peered into his economic crystal ball and foreseen a global recession on the horizon. This stunning insight comes hot on the heels of U.S. President Donald Trump\'s latest tariff escapades, which have sent global markets into a tailspin and left investors clutching their pearls. ​\n\nDutton, never one to miss an opportunity to state the obvious, highlighted that Australia\'s interest rate hikes and soaring cost of living have been more pronounced than in other nations. He squarely placed the blame on the current government\'s economic stewardship, suggesting that their policies have left Australians more vulnerable to international economic tremors. ​\nnews\n+1\ndailytelegraph\n+1\n\nMeanwhile, Treasurer Jim Chalmers, perhaps feeling the heat, pointed to market expectations of potential interest rate cuts by the Reserve Bank to cushion the blow of Trump\'s tariff tantrums. Chalmers assured the public that Australia is better positioned than most to weather the storm, though he conceded that the economy isn\'t entirely bulletproof against such global shocks. ​\nABC\nThe Guardian\n\nAs the political titans trade barbs over who can best steer the nation through these choppy economic waters, everyday Australians are left to wonder if their retirement plans will be postponed indefinitely. With both sides of the aisle pointing fingers and offering grandiose solutions, one can\'t help but feel that the political circus is in full swing, and the main act is a game of economic hot potato. ', 0, 'factabot', 'Dutton Foresees Global Recession: Thanks, Captain Obvious', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-08 03:46:05', '2025-05-03 06:17:25', 27);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (298, 'Albanese and Dutton Set for Debate Showdown: Popcorn Sales Soar', '-', '​In the red corner, we have Prime Minister Anthony Albanese, and in the blue corner, Opposition Leader Peter Dutton. The stage is set for the first leaders\' debate of the 2025 federal election campaign, and it\'s happening tonight at 7:30 PM AEST in Western Sydney. Dubbed the \"People\'s Forum,\" this face-off will feature 100 undecided voters firing questions at the two contenders. Sky News\' Kieran Gilbert will attempt to referee this political sparring match. ​\nheraldsun\n+13\nSBS Australia\n+13\nnews\n+13\nABC\n+3\nnews\n+3\nheraldsun\n+3\nThe Nightly\n+1\nnews\n+1\n\nAlbanese, fresh from announcing a $1 billion mental health initiative aimed at the \"missing middle,\" is likely to tout this as a cornerstone of his campaign. Dutton, on the other hand, has been busy warning of an impending global recession, conveniently pointing fingers at Labor\'s economic policies. Both leaders have been crisscrossing the nation, dodging hecklers and trying to convince Australians they\'re the right choice to navigate these tumultuous times. ​\nThe Guardian\n+1\ndailytelegraph\n+1\n\nFor those eager to witness this political showdown, the debate will be broadcast live on Sky News and streamed on The Daily Telegraph\'s website. If you miss it, don\'t fret; there will be plenty of post-debate analysis to dissect every jab and parry. ​\nnews\n+1\nSBS Australia\n+1\n\nAs the nation tunes in, popcorn in hand, the question remains: will this debate sway the undecided, or will it be just another episode in the grand political soap opera? Only time will tell, but one thing\'s for sure—it\'s must-see TV.', 0, 'factabot', 'Albanese and Dutton Set for Debate Showdown: Popcorn Sales Soar', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-08 03:46:05', '2025-05-02 06:06:49', 28);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (299, 'Bondi Weather: Pack Your Umbrella and Your Sunscreen', '-', '​In Bondi today, Mother Nature can\'t seem to make up her mind. The forecast calls for a high of 21°C with a 70% chance of showers. So, while you\'re out dodging raindrops, don\'t forget that the UV index is still a formidable 6, meaning the sun\'s rays are not to be trifled with. ​\ndailytelegraph\n+1\ndailytelegraph\n+1\n\nThe wind will be playing musical chairs, starting from the south-southwest at 10 km/h in the morning and shifting to the southeast at 13 km/h by the afternoon. Looking ahead, temperatures are set to climb, peaking at 25°C on Friday, before a slight dip over the weekend. ​\ndailytelegraph\n+4\ndailytelegraph\n+4\ndailytelegraph\n+4\n\nSo, whether you\'re planning to surf the waves or just sip coffee by the beach, be prepared for a bit of everything. Pack that umbrella and slather on the sunscreen—Bondi\'s weather is serving up a mixed bag today.', 0, 'factabot', 'Bondi Weather: Pack Your Umbrella and Your Sunscreen', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-08 03:46:05', '2025-05-02 21:33:02', 28);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (300, 'Nullarbor Crash Causes Delays: Travelers Stuck in Middle of Nowhere', '-', '​Travelers crossing the Nullarbor Plain were recently treated to an unexpected roadside attraction: a crash between a truck and a car approximately 75 kilometers from the Western Australian border on the Eyre Highway. The incident occurred around 6 a.m. on Tuesday, causing significant traffic delays as motorists found themselves marooned in the middle of nowhere. ​\nadelaidenow\n+1\nYouTube\n+1\n\nEmergency services promptly descended upon the scene, working tirelessly to clear the wreckage and restore the flow of traffic. Despite their best efforts, drivers were warned to expect lengthy hold-ups, turning what should have been a straightforward journey into an impromptu camping trip on the Nullarbor. ​\nadelaidenow\n\nFor those unfamiliar with the Nullarbor, it\'s a vast expanse of flat, treeless plain stretching across the southern coast of Australia. The Eyre Highway, which cuts through this desolate beauty, is often the scene of such incidents, reminding travelers of the unpredictable nature of long-haul drives.​\n\nWhile the crash site has since been cleared and all lanes are open, the episode serves as a cautionary tale for future travelers: when embarking on journeys through remote regions, always be prepared for the unexpected. Carry essentials like water, snacks, and perhaps a good book to pass the time during unforeseen delays', 0, 'factabot', 'Nullarbor Crash Causes Delays: Travelers Stuck in Middle of Nowhere', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-08 03:46:05', '2025-05-04 16:28:44', 34);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (301, 'Universities to Lose $3B and 80,000 Students Under Dutton\'s Master Plan', '-', 'Opposition Leader Peter Dutton\'s recent proposal to cap international student numbers has ignited a firestorm of criticism, with predictions that Australia\'s universities could lose up to 80,000 students and a whopping $3 billion in revenue. ​\nRagtrader - Ragtrader\n\nDutton\'s plan aims to reduce the annual intake of international students to 240,000, a 30,000-student drop from current levels. He argues that this move will alleviate pressure on the housing market, which has seen national median rents soar by 25% since 2022. ​\nUniversities Australia\n+1\nABC\n+1\nRagtrader - Ragtrader\n+3\nnews\n+3\nBloomberg.com\n+3\n\nHowever, critics are lining up to debunk this strategy. Universities Australia CEO Luke Sheehy warns that making international students scapegoats for the housing crisis is misguided, noting that students occupy less than 6% of the national rental market. ​\nnews\n+2\nABC\n+2\nUniversities Australia\n+2\n\nThe retail sector is also sounding alarms. Both the Australian Retailers Association and the National Retail Association express concern that capping international students and hiking visa fees would severely impact the retail workforce, which relies heavily on this demographic. ​\nRagtrader - Ragtrader\n\nFurthermore, the policy raises questions about the Coalition\'s commitment to higher education. Education Minister Jason Clare accuses Dutton of attempting to dictate school curricula and hints at potential funding cuts for schools under a Coalition government. ​\nThe Guardian\n\nIn summary, while Dutton\'s plan is presented as a housing market fix, it faces significant opposition from various sectors concerned about its broader implications. As the debate unfolds, stakeholders are urging a more nuanced approach that addresses housing affordability without sacrificing the integrity and economic contribution of Australia\'s higher education sector.​\nnews\n+1\ncouriermail\n+1', 0, 'factabot', 'Universities to Lose $3B and 80,000 Students Under Dutton\'s Master Plan', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-08 03:46:05', '2025-05-04 18:04:34', 31);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (302, 'Hornsby Traffic: A Never-Ending Saga of Delays and Roadworks', '-', 'As of April 8, 2025, Hornsby residents and commuters are once again treated to the delightful experience of navigating a labyrinth of roadworks and traffic incidents. Since midnight, only one traffic incident has been reported—a minor collision on the M1 Pacific Motorway near Ku-Ring-Gai Chase Road in Mount Colah. Motorists are advised to reduce speed and exercise caution in the area. ​\ndailytelegraph\n+2\ndailytelegraph\n+2\ndailytelegraph\n+2\n\nThe roadwork saga continues with ten active projects across the region, ensuring that no route is left untouched by the magic of construction. Notably, the Pacific Highway in Wahroonga, Spit Road in Mosman, and various segments of the Warringah Freeway affecting suburbs like North Sydney, Cammeray, Crows Nest, and Naremburn are all undergoing some form of enhancement. These projects involve a delightful mix of reduced speed limits, contraflow traffic patterns, and the ever-popular alternating stop/slow conditions. ​\ndailytelegraph\n+1\ndailytelegraph\n+1\ndailytelegraph\n+3\ndailytelegraph\n+3\ndailytelegraph\n+3\n\nIn the Northern District, two active roadworks are making their presence felt. In Pennant Hills, roadworks on Pennant Hills Road near The Crescent are causing contraflow traffic conditions and flashing yellow traffic lights. These works, last updated at 4:34 am, are expected to end by 6:30 am on April 8. In Eastwood, ongoing work on Rutledge Street near Darvall Road will continue until 6 am on April 11, with alternating stop/slow conditions in place. ​\ndailytelegraph\n+2\ndailytelegraph\n+2\ndailytelegraph\n+2\n\nFor those daring enough to venture into The Shire, two ongoing roadwork projects are ready to test your patience. In Sutherland, roadworks on The Grand Parade near Linden Street, which commenced on April 4, will continue until April 9 at 6 am, featuring reduced speed limits and alternating stop/slow traffic conditions. Meanwhile, in the Royal National Park, Garie Road near Sir Bertram Stevens Drive remains closed due to ongoing construction that began on March 26 and is expected to last until at least mid-2025. ​\ndailytelegraph\n+1\ndailytelegraph\n+1\n\nAdding to the festive atmosphere, the Sydney Royal Easter Show is just around the corner, running from April 11 to April 22, 2025. Expect heavier-than-usual traffic on roads approaching Sydney Olympic Park, including the M4 Motorway, Homebush Bay Drive, Concord Road, Silverwater Road, Centenary Drive, Lane Cove Road, and Epping Road. Plan to arrive early if you\'re driving and allow plenty of extra travel time. ​\nSydney Royal Easter Show\n+1\ntransportnsw.info\n+1\ntransportnsw.info\n\nMotorists are advised to stay updated on current traffic conditions and plan their routes accordingly to navigate the intricate web of roadworks and delays that make up the daily commute in and around Hornsby.', 0, 'factabot', 'Hornsby Traffic: A Never-Ending Saga of Delays and Roadworks', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-08 03:46:05', '2025-05-04 07:52:35', 28);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (303, 'ASX Takes a $32 Billion Dive: Thanks, Trump!', '-', 'The ASX woke up today and chose violence—well, more like panic. A casual $32 billion got ghosted from the Australian stock market in a single day, and we have one very orange elephant in the room to thank: Donald J. Trump. Yes, the former US president/current chaos generator decided to remind the world that he still has thoughts about trade. Specifically, he’s teasing a 60% tariff on Chinese imports if he wins in November, because apparently the 2018 trade war didn’t tank the global economy hard enough the first time. +The Guardian\r\n\r\nAnd because markets love unpredictability almost as much as they love overpriced coffee and buzzwords like “diversification,” investors immediately bolted like they saw the ghost of Lehman Brothers. The ASX 200 plummeted 1.3% before lunch, tech stocks got clobbered, and mining giants looked like they’d seen a ghost—or worse, a quarterly report. BHP and Rio Tinto nosedived like they were auditioning for a reboot of Titanic: Iron Ore Edition. +AFR\r\n\r\nNow, let’s talk about why this random Trump-tantrum even matters down under. Australia, the world\'s most polite economic middle child, is deeply tied to China. When Trump throws tariff-shaped grenades at Beijing, it’s not just a US-China squabble—it’s a domino effect that slaps Australia’s iron ore, lithium, and your superannuation straight in the face. Meanwhile, the RBA is sitting in a corner like “Don’t look at us, we just paused rates.” +ABC News\r\n\r\nSo, what’s new? Besides $32 billion ghosting the market? Investors are fleeing risk faster than influencers from accountability. Bond yields dipped, safe-haven assets are suddenly sexy again, and economists are stress-eating their GDP forecasts. Meanwhile, Trump’s campaign is reportedly thrilled with the “market reaction”—which tells you everything you need to know about their economic strategy. +Bloomberg', 0, 'factabot', 'ASX_Takes_a_32_Billion_Dive:_Thanks,_Trump', 'draft', 'images/news/PT0czs2cjFm1yOfoGgfn5Ku47oIQoDEsmuC4kVgN.png', NULL, '2025-04-09 04:42:54', '2025-05-04 12:09:16', 56);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (304, 'Sydney\'s Glebe Island: From Forgotten Port to National Security Darling', '-', 'Turns out that crusty old wharf you ignored on your ferry ride—yes, that one near the Anzac Bridge—is now Australia’s secret weapon. Glebe Island, Sydney’s final working port, has gone from industrial relic to national security darling. According to a spicy new report, if Australia finds itself in a future conflict or disaster, this long-snubbed patch of rust and rubble could be the difference between smooth supply chains and total chaos. +ABC News\n\nThis is the same port that’s been treated like the junk drawer of Sydney: dusty, loud, and full of stuff no one wants to deal with—mainly bulk construction materials and the occasional existential crisis. For years, developers and politicians practically tripped over themselves trying to turn it into the next Barangaroo, complete with rooftop bars and luxury dog spas. But while everyone was busy gentrifying everything with a view, it turns out someone finally asked: “What if we actually need a functioning port?” +Sydney Morning Herald\n\nIn a surprise plot twist worthy of a prestige TV finale, defence and logistics experts now say Glebe Island could be mission-critical in emergencies—whether it’s supplying fuel, military hardware, or giant inflatable Prime Ministers during morale-boosting parades. The report also politely points out that shutting down your last operational port in the country’s biggest city? Not exactly peak strategic thinking. +The Guardian\n\nAs for the latest? The federal government is now reviewing the port’s role under the umbrella of “critical infrastructure”—which is bureaucratic code for we should’ve thought this through sooner. Locals, who were once promised swanky waterfront apartments, are now being told the future is more forklifts than fine dining. Glebe Island’s glow-up may not be glamorous, but in a crisis, ugly and useful beats pretty and useless every time. +News.com.au', 0, 'factabot', 'Sydney\'s Glebe Island: From Forgotten Port to National Security Darling', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-09 04:42:54', '2025-05-04 16:38:45', 38);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (305, 'MAFS Star Turns Action Hero: Reality TV Meets Real-Life Drama', 'Former \'Married at First Sight\' contestant Tim Smith channels his inner superhero, making a citizen\'s arrest on a machete-wielding teen in Melbourne.', 'When we last saw Jono McCullough on Married At First Sight, he was dodging commitment like a pro, tangled in love triangles and allergic to accountability. But this week, the former reality TV heartbreaker pulled a full 180 and went from ghosting brides to chasing bad guys—literally. In a plot twist no producer could have scripted, Jono leapt into action during a dramatic carjacking in Melbourne, tackling a suspect mid-flee like he was auditioning for Bondi Cop Rescue: Influencer Edition +News.com.au.\n\nHere’s how the scene played out: Jono and his new IRL girlfriend, Ellie Dix (yep, the same one from MAFS, because drama loves a sequel), were out for a casual stroll when they spotted a man allegedly stealing a woman’s car at knifepoint. Instead of filming it for clout, Jono did what no one expected—he intervened. Like, hero-style. He tackled the suspect, held him down, and helped police make the arrest. Fans barely recovered from the time he ghosted Lauren, and now he’s ghosting gravity +7News.\n\nBut let’s be real, the only reason anyone’s talking about this is because it’s a MAFS alum. If Greg from accounting did this, it wouldn’t even make local news. The line between reality TV and reality is now so blurry, you’d think Channel Nine was directing actual crime scenes. We’ve got ex-contestants turning vigilantes and influencers doubling as amateur detectives. And somehow, this is more believable than half the MAFS weddings +The Guardian Australia.\n\nAs for the aftermath, Jono’s basking in his redemption arc, Instagramming the heroics while tabloids scramble to rebrand him as “Protective Boyfriend Goals.” Meanwhile, the alleged carjacker’s facing serious charges—and probably wondering why he got tackled by a man once known for dodging emotional responsibility +Daily Mail Australia. We can’t say justice was served with subtlety, but hey, at least it had abs.', 0, 'factabot', 'mafs-star-turns-action-hero-reality-tv-meets-real-life-drama', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-01 20:13:57', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (306, 'Tesla Protesters in Sydney: Honk If You Hate Elon', 'Activists gather outside Tesla\'s Sydney HQ with catchy slogans and a \'honk if you hate Elon\' sign.', 'Tesla Protesters in Sydney: Honk If You Hate Elon\n\nElon Musk might be used to angry tweets and SEC side-eyes, but now he\'s got Sydney protestors treating his cars like confetti at a vegan wedding. Over a dozen climate activists from Blockade Australia threw a full-blown hissy fit outside Tesla’s Alexandria showroom today, chaining themselves to the building and blocking the driveway like angry baristas on strike. The irony? They were targeting Tesla—the electric car company—for “greenwashing” and capitalist sins. Yes, the world’s poster child for electric vehicles just got cancelled for not being green enough +ABC News.\n\nIn an event that felt like Extinction Rebellion met a Bunnings DIY nightmare, activists locked arms, padlocked necks to fences, and unfurled signs accusing Tesla of destroying ecosystems in the name of lithium. Apparently, saving the planet doesn’t count if you profit off it—especially if you’re a billionaire with a God complex and a questionable Twitter history. “Tesla sells itself as clean energy,” one protester screamed, “but its supply chains are toxic.” Somewhere, Elon probably shorted their moral high ground +The Guardian Australia.\n\nIt’s peak 2025 when climate warriors go full beast mode on the world’s most famous EV brand. But it’s not entirely misplaced. Critics have long accused Tesla of dodging accountability over mining practices, water use, and labor ethics in places that definitely don’t feature on Elon’s X timeline. Tesla’s shiny eco-brand isn’t just about the cars—it’s about image. And when the activists strike the showroom instead of Big Oil HQ, it’s a blunt reminder that even eco-messiahs don’t get a free pass anymore +SBS News.\n\nAs police cut chains and traffic honked like it was part of the movement, 11 protesters were arrested. No Teslas were harmed in the making of this chaos—though a few got a passive-aggressive note on the windscreen. Meanwhile, Musk’s PR team probably just poured a stiff drink and updated the crisis template for “Australian Anarchy” +News.com.au.', 0, 'factabot', 'tesla-protesters-in-sydney-honk-if-you-hate-elon', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 16:40:33', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (307, 'Bankstown Vape Deal Goes Up in Smoke—Literally', 'An illegal vape transaction in Bankstown ends with a man in a coma after a hammer attack.', 'Meet Mohammad and Ibrahim Elomar, two Sydney brothers who thought selling dodgy vapes would be a chill side hustle—until their stash went full Michael Bay in the middle of Bankstown. The pair allegedly cooked up a lucrative little business importing nicotine vapes and selling them under-the-counter to eager high schoolers and cash-heavy vape fiends. But instead of puffing profits, they got explosions, fireballs, and an arrest so cinematic you’d think Underbelly was rebooting with a cotton candy-scented plot +9News.\n\nHere’s the tea: Police raided an industrial unit in Bankstown and uncovered over $3.2 million worth of illegal vapes—like, literal mountains of banned nicotine puffs disguised in every flavour your dentist hates. Then, karma came in like a drag-racing bogan: one of the storage sites burst into flames just hours later, torching part of the evidence and raising eyebrows faster than a shocked emoji. Whether it was an accident or someone got a little too close with a lighter remains to be seen +ABC News.\n\nVape crackdowns are hitting harder lately, with NSW health officials and the Therapeutic Goods Administration treating illicit e-cigarettes like mini WMDs. And honestly? Fair. These dodgy imports aren’t just bad for lungs—they’re often soaked in unknown chemicals and smuggled in without regulation. So yeah, if you’re selling schoolyard poison from a warehouse, expect the cops—and maybe an accidental fireball—to show up. It’s 2025, and vaping is officially the new tobacco war +The Guardian Australia.\n\nThe Elomar brothers have been charged and refused bail, and now face the very un-vibe reality of prison time. Their next court appearance is scheduled for later this month, assuming no more vape warehouses spontaneously combust. Meanwhile, health officials hope this lights a fire (pun very much intended) under Parliament to fast-track stronger anti-vape legislation +SMH.\n', 0, 'factabot', 'bankstown-vape-deal-goes-up-in-smoke-literally', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 22:42:05', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (308, 'Senate Candidate\'s Bankruptcy Blues: Third Time\'s the Charm?', 'Rod Culleton referred to police for running while bankrupt—for the third time.', 'Ah, Jay Hansen—the Senate hopeful with a financial history so cursed, even Centrelink would swipe left. The Queensland independent is back in the headlines, not for policy brilliance or inspirational speeches, but because he’s racked up his third bankruptcy. That’s right, not one, not two, but three glorious flops. If political campaigns were judged on fiscal responsibility, Jay’s would be a flaming bin chicken of debt and denial. But hey, maybe he’s just practising for the budget blowouts in Canberra? +The Australian.\n\nHansen, who’s tried (and failed) to secure a seat in the Senate before, had previously brushed off bankruptcy like it was just a bad credit score after Afterpay bender. His past filings in 2009 and 2015 were conveniently “forgotten” during his last campaign run—until journos dug up the receipts, of course. Now, a new bankruptcy lodged in February 2025 has put his political ambitions in serious overdraft. The man who says he wants to fight “corruption and waste” literally can’t manage a personal bank account. The vibes are immaculate +Courier Mail.\n\nThis isn’t just about one man’s tragic relationship with money—it’s about what kind of vetting system lets repeat bankrupts stroll into high office pitches. Technically, Hansen can still run (the Constitution only bars undischarged bankrupts after election), but the optics? Rougher than a Four Corners exposé. If you’re selling fiscal discipline to voters while dodging creditors like it\'s the Matrix, you might need a rebrand. Or at least a solid accountant +ABC News.\n\nAs of this week, Hansen’s still out there shaking hands and making promises he definitely can’t finance. Asked about the third bankruptcy, he blamed \"unfair systems and bad luck\"—a.k.a. political buzzwords for “please don’t look at my tax history.” At this rate, the only thing he’s winning is bingo at debtor’s court +News.com.au.', 0, 'factabot', 'senate-candidates-bankruptcy-blues-third-times-the-charm', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 14:41:28', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (309, 'Alice Springs Youths Channel \'Fast & Furious\' in Government Car Heist', 'A 13-year-old allegedly steals a government vehicle and escapes from bail facility.', 'In a scene that could rival a Hollywood action flick, a 13-year-old boy in Alice Springs allegedly stole a government-issued Toyota Prado from a bail accommodation facility. Reports indicate that the boy obtained the keys and used the vehicle to ram through the property\'s locked front gates before fleeing. As of now, both the boy and the vehicle remain at large, with police urging anyone with information to come forward .​\ncouriermail\n\nThis incident is part of a broader surge in youth-related crimes in Alice Springs. In recent weeks, there have been multiple reports of young individuals engaging in unlawful activities, including the theft of e-scooters and e-bikes, break-ins at local establishments, and the reckless driving of stolen vehicles. Notably, six boys aged between 10 and 14 allegedly ransacked a Todd Street office building, leading to their arrest after coordinated police efforts .​\ncouriermail\n+1\ncouriermail\n+1\n\nThe rise in such incidents has raised concerns among residents and officials alike. Authorities highlight that many of these youths are repeat offenders, often returning to criminal activities shortly after release. The situation underscores the challenges faced in addressing youth crime and the effectiveness of current intervention programs .​\npfes.nt.gov.au\n+9\nNT Independent\n+9\nnews\n+9\nABC\n+2\nWikipedia\n+2\nThe Australian\n+2\n\nAs investigations continue, the community remains on alert, hoping for swift action to curb this troubling trend. The Northern Territory Police urge residents to report any suspicious activities and assist in efforts to restore safety and order in the region.​\nNT Independent\nMirage News\n+2\npfes.nt.gov.au\n+2\npfes.nt.gov.au\n', 0, 'factabot', 'alice-springs-youths-channel-fast-furious-in-government-car-heist', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 19:32:21', 5);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (310, 'Albanese and Dutton\'s AUKUS Tiff: Boys and Their Toys', 'Albanese slams Dutton’s AUKUS comments as ‘irresponsible’.', 'Someone get these two a sandbox and matching submarines. Anthony Albanese and Peter Dutton are once again flexing their geopolitical biceps over AUKUS—because nothing says mature leadership like two grown men arguing over nuclear-powered boats with a price tag big enough to buy a small moon. Dutton, forever auditioning for Top Gun: Canberra Edition, accused Albo of jeopardising Australia\'s security by being too soft on the US and \"not getting enough bang for our billions.\" Meanwhile, Albanese fired back with the energy of a dad telling off a teenager: “You’ve had your go, mate.” +The Australian.\n\nThe AUKUS pact, for those just tuning in, is the trilateral bromance between Australia, the US, and the UK, designed to gift us submarines we probably won’t see until Gen Alpha hits retirement. The whole point? Keep China twitchy and the Indo-Pacific “stable” (read: Western). Dutton’s beef? He claims Labor dropped the ball by not demanding more industrial sweeteners and local jobs. Basically: where are the Aussie-made bits? Albanese, meanwhile, says they’re securing jobs and peace—like it’s a Bunnings 2-for-1 special on diplomacy and employment +ABC News.\n\nBut beyond the verbal slap fight, what’s really going on? This is less about submarines and more about political posturing. With defence spending ballooning faster than a toddler’s tantrum, both sides are desperate to look “tough on China” without actually saying those words out loud. Albanese wants to play statesman; Dutton wants to cosplay war chief. Meanwhile, Australia’s taxpayers are quietly Googling “how to return submarines for refund” +The Guardian Australia.\n\nThe latest? Labor’s trying to frame Dutton as reckless, hinting he’d drag Australia into conflict faster than you can say “strategic miscalculation.” Dutton claps back with vague threats about “national security” like he’s holding secret intel in a manila folder. And us? We’re stuck in the splash zone of their toy boat tantrum. +SBS News.', 0, 'factabot', 'albanese-and-duttons-aukus-tiff-boys-and-their-toys', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 09:25:49', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (311, 'Blindfolds and Bingo: Australia\'s Democracy Gets a Retro Makeover', 'AEC uses blindfolds and wooden balls to decide ballot order.', 'It’s election time, baby—and nothing screams modern democracy quite like ballot papers longer than your Uber Eats order and candidates you’ve never seen outside a “Missing: Have You Seen This Political Dinosaur?” flyer. This week, Australia\'s electoral system is copping some serious side-eye after Senate group voting tickets were quietly reintroduced in Victoria and WA, meaning your vote can now be whisked away like a bad Tinder match—with you blindfolded, and the party deciding who your preferences go to. Bingo cages have more transparency +ABC News.\n\nFor those playing at home, group voting tickets (GVTs) were basically exiled from federal elections in 2016 after the infamous “preference whisperer” Glenn Druery turned them into a magic trick: vote 1 for a party, and your preferences would teleport across 12 micro-parties you’ve never heard of. Now, Victoria and WA are dusting off that old relic for state elections and pretending it’s a democratic feature, not a plot twist from Yes Minister +The Conversation.\n\nThe real kicker? Most Aussies have no idea this is happening. There’s no TikTok campaign, no mass media blitz—just a quiet legislative shimmy while voters prep their democracy sausages. The reintroduction of GVTs means preference deals can once again be brokered in the shadows, empowering minor parties to win seats with a fraction of the primary vote. It’s like political Uber Pool: you think you’re going one way, but suddenly you’re dropping off Clive Palmer’s cousin at Parliament +SMH.\n\nElectoral experts are screaming into the void, and transparency watchdogs are twitching harder than a poker player on a caffeine binge. But the Electoral Commissions of WA and Victoria are shrugging like “Don’t blame us, blame Parliament.” Meanwhile, voters are expected to navigate a system built like a Vegas slot machine and just trust it’s all fine. Democracy, but make it retro +Guardian Australia.\n', 0, 'factabot', 'blindfolds-and-bingo-australias-democracy-gets-a-retro-makeover', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-04-11 14:47:13', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (312, 'Bonza Airline\'s Directors Get a Free Pass: ASIC Says \'Meh\'', 'ASIC won’t prosecute Bonza directors despite trading accusations.', 'Remember Bonza? That budget airline with the name of a surfboard brand and the lifespan of a mayfly? Well, after leaving staff unpaid, passengers stranded, and a mountain of unpaid bills, you’d think the airline’s top brass might get a slap on the wrist—or at least a stern talking-to. But nope! The Australian Securities and Investments Commission (ASIC) took one look at the wreckage and went, “Yeah nah,” deciding not to investigate the directors. Because apparently, corporate accountability is optional now +AFR.\n\nFor context: Bonza burst onto the scene in 2022 with purple planes, big promises, and routes nobody really asked for. Fast forward to 2024, and it collapsed into administration, stunning exactly no one except, perhaps, the staff still waiting on their final paychecks. The company left behind $116 million in debts, including millions owed to airports, fuel suppliers, and workers. And yet, ASIC concluded there’s no evidence of illegal activity worth pursuing. We’re guessing the bar is now somewhere below sea level +The Guardian Australia.\n\nSo why does this matter? Because Australia’s corporate watchdog is increasingly looking like a toy poodle in a thunderstorm—loud when it doesn’t matter, silent when it does. ASIC’s nonchalance here isn’t just infuriating for Bonza employees; it’s a massive green light to other boardrooms that you can crash a company into the ground with zero personal consequences, as long as you file the paperwork neatly +SMH.\n\nThe latest? ASIC confirmed it\'s closing the file on Bonza’s top dogs, leaving workers high and dry while directors quietly fade into the LinkedIn mist. No fines, no charges, just the gentle hum of business as usual. It’s a vibe, alright—a very broken, very “Bonza” vibe +News.com.au.', 0, 'factabot', 'bonza-airlines-directors-get-a-free-pass-asic-says-meh', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-01 14:37:14', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (313, 'ASX Rollercoaster: Markets Dip as Investors Clutch Their Pearls', 'Markets drop 0.8% amid global trade drama.', 'Grab your pearls and your panic buttons, because the ASX had a wobble today that sent investors into a mild existential crisis—again. The S&P/ASX 200 slipped 0.7%, wiping nearly $18 billion off the board in a single trading day. The culprits? A cocktail of global recession whispers, US inflation nerves, and the general vibe that no one actually knows what’s going on. Basically, the stock market threw a tantrum, and superannuation balances got dragged into the drama +AFR.\n\nTech and real estate were the market’s biggest sooks, with WiseTech Global and REA Group leading the dive like they’d just been dumped via text. Meanwhile, the mining giants sulked in the corner after iron ore prices decided they’d had enough optimism for the month. Banks were slightly less tragic but still managed to collectively sigh and lose ground. Investors responded by refreshing their portfolio apps every 30 seconds and reconsidering that early retirement plan +SMH.\n\nZoom out, though, and this isn’t exactly a financial apocalypse—more like a moody Tuesday. The real tension is in the US, where upcoming inflation data has Wall Street so jittery it’s practically vibrating. Add ongoing global uncertainty (China’s meh growth, Middle East tension, rate hike roulette), and you’ve got an anxiety buffet. Aussie markets are just following the global herd—except we do it with less Wall Street swagger and more internalised dread +The Guardian Australia.\n\nThe latest? Analysts are already telling us not to panic (which is how you know it’s time to panic), and traders are pricing in the possibility of more rate cuts down the line. Until then, expect more bumps, more headlines, and more investors staring longingly at high-interest savings accounts like they’re a long-lost ex +News.com.au.', 0, 'factabot', 'asx-rollercoaster-markets-dip-as-investors-clutch-their-pearls', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 04:03:37', 23);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (314, 'Cobram House Fire: Suspicious Blaze Sparks Community Gossip', 'A mysterious house fire in Cobram prompts an investigation.', 'When flames engulfed a quiet home in Cobram this week, locals didn’t just smell smoke—they sniffed drama. The late-night blaze tore through a vacant house on Karook Street like it owed someone money, and now, everyone from the local café to the footy club is playing detective. The kicker? Authorities aren’t ruling out foul play, and suddenly this sleepy border town’s got a sizzling mystery hotter than a sausage sizzle in January +ABC News.\n\nThe house was reportedly unoccupied, which in small-town Australia basically translates to “prime target for shady business or bored teenagers with lighters.” CFA crews rushed in just after midnight, battling a blaze that lit up the street like it was New Year’s Eve. No one was hurt (thankfully), but the damage was severe—and so are the conspiracy theories flying around the neighbourhood faster than you can say “insurance job.” +7News\n\nWhile investigations are still underway, police have confirmed the fire is being treated as suspicious, and let’s be honest: that’s code for “this wasn’t just someone forgetting to turn off the kettle.” Locals have pointed out that this isn’t the first fire in the area recently, and whispers about disputes, development plans, and dodgy dealings are swirling harder than the smoke clouds. In a town where everyone knows everyone’s business (and their cousin’s), this blaze has lit a bonfire of speculation +Herald Sun.\n\nThe latest? Fire investigators and detectives are combing through the ashes, and locals are combing through Facebook for “clues.” No arrests yet, but don’t worry—Karen from down the road has definitely cracked the case in the comments section. As for the house? Burned to the ground. As for the gossip? Flaming out of control +The Age.\n', 0, 'factabot', 'cobram-house-fire-suspicious-blaze-sparks-community-gossip', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-02 15:31:21', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (315, 'Sydney\'s Double Whammy: Two Deaths, One Night, Zero Chill', 'Two separate deaths reported in Sydney\'s southwest in one night.', 'Sydney decided to serve up a double dose of grim news last night with two separate deaths that have locals rattled, authorities scrambling, and Twitter in a full-blown frenzy. First up: a man in his 40s was stabbed to death at a home in Riverwood in the city’s south-west, and just as emergency crews were wrapping their heads around that scene, another body—this time, a man in his 50s—was found burned inside a torched home in Auburn. Two suburbs, two dead men, one seriously bad night for New South Wales Police +9News.\n\nThe Riverwood case reads like something out of a bad true crime podcast: neighbours heard yelling around 2 a.m., police rocked up, and there he was—stab wounds, dead on the scene. A man and woman were arrested nearby, but no charges have been laid yet. Over in Auburn, it was a literal house of horror. Firefighters were called to a blaze at 5 a.m., and when they put out the flames, they found a body inside. Investigators haven’t ruled out suspicious circumstances, and frankly, no one’s buying “accidental” at this point +ABC News.\n\nBeyond the tragedy, these back-to-back incidents raise serious questions about crime, mental health, and the state of emergency services. Sydney’s no stranger to nightly drama, but two violent deaths in such quick succession hits differently—especially with community trust already fraying. The city\'s got a growing rep for midnight mayhem, and while not all of it makes headlines, this double-header sure did. Strap in, because this might be just the start of a bigger, messier conversation +The Guardian Australia.\n\nLatest word? Police are investigating both incidents separately “at this stage,” which is cop talk for we’ll see if this gets weirder. For now, Sydney\'s got one charred crime scene, one blood-stained street, and a collective case of the heebie-jeebies. Sleep tight, NSW. +SMH', 0, 'factabot', 'sydneys-double-whammy-two-deaths-one-night-zero-chill', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-04-11 14:47:13', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (316, 'Tasmanian Boating Tragedy: One Man Swims, One Man Sinks', 'Man swims 90 minutes to shore, neighbour found dead.', 'Tasmania served up some harsh reality off the coast of Southport this week, when a casual morning fishing trip turned into a maritime nightmare. Two men set out in a tinny just after 9 a.m., likely expecting nothing more dramatic than a tussle with a stubborn snapper. But within hours, that boat capsized in rough waters, leaving one man clinging to life and the other now tragically presumed drowned. It\'s the kind of story that makes you rethink all those “she’ll be right” attitudes about safety at sea +ABC News.\n\nThe survivor—still shaken but miraculously alive—managed to swim to shore and raise the alarm, sparking a desperate search effort involving police boats, helicopters, and marine rescue volunteers. Conditions were reportedly rough, with the tinny no match for the swell. Authorities haven’t confirmed whether life jackets were used, but if you’ve ever been on a boat in Tassie waters, you know it’s less “cruise” and more “cold-water roulette” +The Mercury.\n\nTragically, stories like this aren’t rare. Boating incidents in Australia have been on the rise, especially with more people buying cheap vessels and assuming a license means “invincible.” Maritime safety campaigns have been practically begging fishos and weekend warriors to wear life jackets and log trips, but the message clearly isn’t hitting home. Combine that with Tassie’s notoriously unpredictable coastline and you\'ve got a recipe for tragedy +SBS News.\n\nAs of today, the search for the missing man continues, but hope is fading faster than the daylight. Emergency crews are combing the waters, while local communities brace for the worst. And somewhere out there, a capsized tinny is bobbing in the surf—one man survived, one didn’t, and a fishing trip turned cautionary tale now haunts the waves +7News.\n', 0, 'factabot', 'tasmanian-boating-tragedy-one-man-swims-one-man-sinks', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-04-14 07:27:55', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (317, 'ASX Takes a Nosedive: Thanks, Trump!', 'Markets crash 2.4% as US-China tariff drama hits hard.', 'Donald J. Trump, freshly re-throned as Commander in Chief (because 2020 wasn\'t traumatic enough), decided global trade needed a little razzle dazzle. So he slapped the world with a universal 10% tariff—just because he can—and gifted China a special 145% price tag. That’s not trade policy; that’s a toddler throwing Duplo bricks in a glass house. +en.wikipedia.org\n\nNaturally, the Australian share market took one look and promptly collapsed like a Jenga tower in an earthquake. The ASX 200 dropped faster than a crypto bro’s dignity, closing 0.8% lower on April 11. Mining stocks? Mauled. Tech? Toast. Banks? Begging for mercy. Basically, if you owned anything other than gold or anxiety, you had a rough day. +ABC News\n\nHere’s the tea: Australia is like that poor middle kid in a messy divorce. One parent (China) just got slapped with tariff alimony, and the other (the U.S.) is demanding loyalty. Meanwhile, Aussie exporters are standing around like, “Should we panic now or later?” Add in the AUD flirting with historic lows, and you\'ve got yourself a financial cocktail called “Down Under on the Rocks.” +The Guardian\n\nTo make things spicier, Trump later announced a temporary 90-day tariff delay for some countries—but not China. The market coughed, sniffled, and went, “Gee, thanks?” Investors are still curled in a fetal position, refreshing the news like it\'s OnlyFans for economists. One thing’s clear: Trump’s back, baby. And your super fund just got caught in the crossfire. +WSJ', 0, 'factabot', 'asx-takes-a-nosedive-thanks-trump', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 14:10:07', 24);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (318, 'Tariff Turmoil: Aussie Swimwear Brand Drowns in Costs', 'RAQ Apparel quits US market thanks to Trump’s tariffs.', 'Sophia Argyropoulos, the founder of RAQ Apparel, has become the latest casualty in the global trade war\'s fashion frontlines. Her Australian swimwear brand, known for its chic designs and loyal customer base, has been forced to shut down its U.S. online store. The culprit? A staggering 125% tariff imposed by the Trump administration on Chinese-made goods, which includes RAQ\'s products. Argyropoulos lamented the decision, stating, \"When tariffs went over 100% on Chinese made goods, I was like \'well we literally can\'t make any money.\'\" +news.com.au\n\nThe background to this economic debacle lies in the U.S. government\'s recent tariff hikes aimed at curbing imports from China. While intended to bolster domestic manufacturing, these tariffs have inadvertently ensnared small international businesses like RAQ Apparel. Argyropoulos, unable to find alternative manufacturers that meet her brand\'s standards, faced the grim reality of either passing exorbitant costs onto customers or exiting the U.S. market altogether. She chose the latter, expressing concern for other small brands likely to follow suit. +news.com.au\n\nThis situation underscores the broader implications of protectionist trade policies. While large corporations might absorb or navigate these financial shocks, smaller enterprises often lack the resources to do so. The fashion industry, with its intricate global supply chains, is particularly vulnerable. Experts warn that such tariffs could lead to a 7% drop in global trade and a 0.7% decrease in global GDP, disproportionately affecting developing countries and small businesses. +news.com.au\n\nIn the latest development, China has retaliated by imposing a 125% tariff on U.S. goods, escalating the trade tensions further. As global markets react to this tit-for-tat, small businesses like RAQ Apparel are left grappling with the fallout, highlighting the unintended victims of geopolitical power plays. +news.com.au\n', 0, 'factabot', 'tariff-turmoil-aussie-swimwear-brand-drowns-in-costs', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 13:18:46', 20);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (319, 'F-35 Program: Australia Cashes In', 'Aussie industry nets $5B+ in F-35 contracts.', 'Australia\'s F-35 program is soaring—both in the skies and in the bank. With over 70 F-35A Lightning II jets delivered to the Royal Australian Air Force (RAAF), the nation isn\'t just flexing its aerial muscles; it\'s also reaping substantial economic benefits. Local companies like Lovitt Technologies have secured significant contracts, bolstered by government grants, to supply components for the global F-35 program. This move not only strengthens Australia\'s defense capabilities but also injects billions into the local economy. ​\nDefence\n\nThe F-35\'s journey in Australia hasn\'t been without turbulence. Initial concerns about cost overruns and technical glitches had skeptics dubbing it a \"flying lemon.\" However, recent developments have turned the narrative around. The RAAF\'s commitment to the program, despite earlier hiccups, showcases a strategic pivot towards embracing cutting-edge technology and fostering domestic industry growth. ​\nThe Australian\nThe Guardian\n\nIn the broader context, Australia\'s investment in the F-35 program underscores its dedication to maintaining a formidable defense posture in the Indo-Pacific region. The interoperability of the F-35 with allied forces enhances collective security and ensures that Australia remains a key player on the global stage. Moreover, the economic ripple effects—from job creation to technological advancements—highlight the multifaceted benefits of this defense initiative. ​\n\nThe latest updates indicate that Australia is not just a participant but a significant contributor to the F-35 program. With plans to expand its fleet and deepen industry involvement, the nation is poised to further solidify its position as a defense and aerospace powerhouse. It\'s a classic tale of turning challenges into opportunities—and Australia\'s F-35 saga is flying high. ​\n', 0, 'factabot', 'f-35-program-australia-cashes-in', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 11:45:33', 29);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (320, 'Aussie Dollar Hits Five-Year Low: Wallets Weep', 'AUD sinks lower than your ex’s standards.', 'Australia’s dollar just did a swan dive straight into the economic kiddie pool, splashing around below 60 US cents—its lowest since COVID panic-buying was a national sport. On April 11, traders clutched their pearls as the AUD crawled across the floor like it lost its dignity and spare change. If your holiday savings were feeling cocky last week, they’re now hiding under the bed. +Reuters\n\nWhat’s the culprit? Surprise—it’s Trump, again. The U.S. President (yes, still) went full economic Rambo and slapped a 10% universal tariff on imports, with a spicy 145% for China. Beijing responded like a jilted lover, hurling a 125% tariff right back. Global markets immediately broke out in economic hives. And in this trade war food fight, Australia—aka the quiet kid at the back of the classroom—got hit with mashed potatoes. +News.com.au\n\nThe Aussie dollar, bless its wobbly little heart, is a global risk barometer. That means when big economies throw tantrums, our currency gets dragged into the car park and mugged. Importers are hyperventilating. Shoppers are side-eyeing rising prices. And economists are back on TV saying, “Well, technically we’re not in a recession… yet.” Meanwhile, the Reserve Bank is being begged to slash rates faster than you can say “cheap cash, please.” +The Australian\n\nIn the latest act of this economic soap opera, Treasurer Jim Chalmers is publicly “encouraging” the RBA to do something—translation: fix it or we riot. And you? You’re just wondering why your Uber Eats order costs $3 more and your Bali plans just turned into “budget camping in Bendigo.” +ABC News\n', 0, 'factabot', 'aussie-dollar-hits-five-year-low-wallets-weep', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 20:28:52', 24);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (321, 'ASX 200 Watchlist: Tech Stocks in the Spotlight', 'Lynas and Nextdc on the move amid market madness.', 'Australia\'s tech stocks are currently experiencing a rollercoaster ride reminiscent of a soap opera plot. On April 11, 2025, the S&P/ASX 200 Information Technology Index dropped by 1.16%, reflecting investor anxiety amid global trade tensions. This decline is part of a broader market downturn, with the ASX 200 closing 0.82% lower, influenced by escalating U.S.-China trade disputes and their ripple effects on global markets. ​\nMarket Index\n\nThe backdrop to this market drama includes President Trump\'s recent tariff announcements, which have sent shockwaves through international markets. The tech sector, often sensitive to such geopolitical developments, has been particularly affected. Investors are now scrutinizing tech stocks, wary of potential supply chain disruptions and increased costs. ​\n\nIn this climate of uncertainty, some investors are turning their attention to gold stocks, which have shown resilience amid market volatility. Companies like Northern Star Resources and Evolution Mining have reported gains, offering a glimmer of hope in an otherwise turbulent market. ​\nMarket Index\n\nAs the week concludes, the tech sector remains under scrutiny. Analysts suggest that while challenges persist, opportunities may arise for those willing to navigate the complexities of the current market landscape. Investors are advised to stay informed and consider diversifying their portfolios to mitigate risks associated with ongoing trade tensions.​\n', 0, 'factabot', 'asx-200-watchlist-tech-stocks-in-the-spotlight', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 17:09:37', 23);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (322, 'Gout Gout: The Teen Who\'s Too Fast for the Wind', 'Teen sprint prodigy smashes wind-assisted sub-10s.', 'If you thought your biggest flex at 17 was getting your P-plates, meet Gout Gout—Australia’s newest sprinting phenom who just ran 100 metres faster than your excuses. At the national athletics championships in Perth, Gout clocked two sub-10 second races in one day like it was just another Wednesday. The only thing holding him back? The wind. Yes, apparently, the breeze was too supportive, so the times are technically illegal. Bureaucracy: ruining greatness since forever. +FirstPost\n\nBoth races were wind-assisted—3.5 m/s in the heat, 2.6 m/s in the final—just over the limit for official records. But let’s be honest, the kid ran so fast he nearly outran the laws of physics. Still, the official verdict is “impressive, but sorry, no points for style if the wind claps too loud.” Imagine telling Usain Bolt, “Sorry, champ, the air loved you a little too much.” +FirstPost\n\nBut here’s where it gets juicier: Gout already smoked Bolt’s teenage 200m time last year. Bolt ran 20.13 at 16. Gout? 20.04. That’s not a stat; that’s a prophecy. Australia, a country best known for producing cricket heroes and barbecue champions, might actually have a legit global sprint contender—and no, we’re not coping, you are. +The Guardian\n\nNext up, he’s taking on the big boys in the 200m open event, including Lachlan Kennedy. Will the wind calm down enough to let him be great? Will he need to race indoors with a giant vacuum? Who knows. But one thing’s clear: Gout Gout isn’t just running races—he’s rewriting the script. And Mother Nature? She’s just trying to keep up. +The New Daily', 0, 'factabot', 'gout-gout-the-teen-whos-too-fast-for-the-wind', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 11:28:35', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (323, 'Billie Jean King Cup: Australia\'s 50-Year Drought Continues', 'Women’s team flops before quarter-finals. Again.', 'Australia\'s women’s tennis team just added another year to its half-century-long collection of “not this time” moments at the Billie Jean King Cup. The year is 2025, and yet the last time we hoisted that trophy, colour TV was still exciting and people thought fondue was haute cuisine. This week, Kazakhstan showed up, slapped us with a backhand and a reality check, and left with a 2-1 win. Putintseva and Rybakina? Cold as ice, hot as serves. +Reuters\n\nLet’s set the scene. We were the host nation. Home crowd. Sunny skies. All the vibes. And still, Maya Joint got flattened in 58 minutes, and Kimberly Birrell, bless her gutsy hustle, got outmaneuvered in two sets by Rybakina, who looked like she came to Brisbane for one thing: domination. The doubles team, Storm Hunter and Ellen Perez, did win their match—but that was basically like putting glitter on a deflated balloon. +News.com.au\n\nIf you’re wondering how this keeps happening, you’re not alone. We’ve made it to the finals twice in the last five years and still managed to leave empty-handed like someone who showed up to a birthday party with no gift and took the last slice of cake. Meanwhile, Tennis Australia continues to smile through gritted teeth while every other nation sharpens their singles roster. +Nine\n\nNext, we’ll face Colombia in a “dead rubber,” which is the tennis equivalent of a breakup coffee. No stakes, no titles, just awkward vibes and an opportunity to pretend everything’s fine. Maybe next year, right? Or maybe we should just start claiming moral victories and call it the “Almost Trophy.” +News.com.au', 0, 'factabot', 'billie-jean-king-cup-australias-50-year-drought-continues', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 15:13:34', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (324, 'Ellyse Perry Joins Hampshire: Because Australia Isn\'t Big Enough', 'Cricket queen signs with UK club for more global domination.', 'Ellyse Perry, Australia\'s cricketing wonder woman, has decided that dominating Down Under just isn\'t enough. The 34-year-old all-rounder is packing her bags for Hampshire, ready to sprinkle some Aussie magic over the English county\'s women\'s T20 Blast and One-Day Cup campaigns this July. ​\nThe Tribune\n+6\nThe Guardian\n+6\nCricket Times\n+6\n\nPerry, whose trophy cabinet is more crowded than a peak-hour train, boasts six T20 World Cups, two ODI World Cups, and a Commonwealth Games gold medal. Not to mention, she\'s the all-time leading run-scorer and wicket-taker in Women\'s Ashes history. ​\nThe Guardian\n+4\nCricket Times\n+4\nCricket.com\n+4\nThe Tribune\n+3\nThe Guardian\n+3\nCricket Times\n+3\n\nHampshire\'s head coach, Paul Prichard, couldn\'t contain his excitement, stating, \"Ellyse is one of the world\'s best cricketers and we are looking forward to welcoming her to the team this summer.\" ​\nThe Tribune\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+2\nCricket.com\n+2\n\nPerry herself chimed in, \"The club has been a leader within the women\'s game for the last ten years and I\'m excited to have the opportunity to ... .\" ​\nCricket Times\n+4\nThe Tribune\n+4\nThe Guardian\n+4\n\nSo, as Perry gears up to conquer new territories, one can\'t help but wonder: is there any corner of the cricketing world safe from her reign?', 0, 'factabot', 'ellyse-perry-joins-hampshire-because-australia-isnt-big-enough', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 06:45:53', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (325, 'NRL\'s Perth Expansion: AFL Sits Back and Watches the Chaos', 'WA premier says ‘no thanks’ to funding new NRL team.', 'The NRL\'s grand plan to plant a team in Perth is unfolding like a reality TV drama—complete with plot twists, budget disputes, and a touch of inter-sport rivalry. The proposed Western Bears franchise, a collaboration between the North Sydney Bears and a Perth consortium, was set to be the league\'s 18th team. However, the bid hit a snag when the consortium failed to produce the required license fee, leaving the NRL unimpressed and the AFL amused. ​\ncodesports\n+7\nWikipedia\n+7\nnews\n+7\nThe Australian\n\nWA Premier Roger Cook isn\'t exactly rolling out the red carpet either. He\'s accused the NRL of treating Western Australia as a \"cash cow,\" balking at the league\'s request for a $320 million investment over a decade. Cook\'s stance is clear: no taxpayer money for a league that seems more interested in financial gain than genuine expansion. ​\nThe Australian\n+4\nnews\n+4\nFOX SPORTS\n+4\nThe Australian\n\nMeanwhile, the AFL is sipping its flat white, watching the NRL\'s missteps with a smirk. They\'ve even scheduled a West Coast Eagles game to coincide with the NRL\'s rare Perth appearance, ensuring local fans have a choice—though the AFL seems confident about where loyalties lie. ​\nThe Nightly\n\nNRL legend Wayne Bennett, however, remains optimistic. He\'s urging Perth fans not to lose hope, drawing parallels to the successful launch of the Dolphins despite initial skepticism. Bennett believes Perth is ripe for expansion, even if the current bid is floundering. ​\nheraldsun\n+3\nnews\n+3\nSporting News\n+3\n\nIn the latest episode of this saga, the NRL\'s Perth expansion plans are teetering on the brink of collapse. With financial hurdles, political resistance, and a rival code enjoying the spectacle, the dream of a Western Bears team is fading faster than a halftime lead. ​\ndailytelegraph\n+2\nWikipedia\n+2\nnews\n+2', 0, 'factabot', 'nrls-perth-expansion-afl-sits-back-and-watches-the-chaos', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 22:41:54', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (326, 'Farewell Audrey Griffin: A Community Mourns Its Star', 'Hundreds mourn beloved local sports teen after tragic passing.', 'Audrey Griffin wasn’t just another teenager with a footy in her hands—she was the kind of rising star that made you believe maybe, just maybe, the next generation would turn out alright. At just 17, Audrey had already racked up more achievements than most of us manage with three coffees and a vision board. Whether it was lighting up the local AFL field or just being the kind of person who left every room brighter, Audrey was a standout. +Daily Telegraph\n\nThen came the gut punch no one saw coming. Audrey passed away suddenly on March 30, sending shockwaves through her school, club, and the entire Central Coast community. Hundreds turned out for her farewell, many in her Warnervale Wildcats guernsey, because when you lose someone like Audrey, you don’t show up in black—you show up in her colours. +Daily Telegraph\n\nIt’s not every day that a community collectively pauses. But Audrey wasn’t every day. She was that rare mix of talent and humility, the girl who could smash a goal from midfield and still help pack up cones after training. The Wildcats, her schoolmates, coaches, and even rivals have all spoken out, struggling to find words that match the impact she left behind. Spoiler: there aren’t any. +News.com.au\n\nNow, the legacy begins. The club is planning tributes, jerseys are being framed, and the community is talking about how to honour her name for future generations. But truthfully, there’s no neat bow to tie this up. This wasn’t just a loss. It was a full-stop in the middle of a sentence that deserved many more chapters. Vale Audrey. You ran harder, laughed louder, and inspired deeper than most of us do in a lifetime. +Daily Telegraph', 0, 'factabot', 'farewell-audrey-griffin-a-community-mourns-its-star', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 19:01:25', 110);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (327, 'Clean Car Policy: Dutton\'s Ute-opia vs. Albanese\'s Efficiency Dreams', 'Dutton calls fuel standards a \'ute tax\', Albanese hits back.', 'Peter Dutton has rolled into the 2025 election campaign with a plan to scrap the fines associated with Labor\'s New Vehicle Efficiency Standard (NVES), branding them a \"car and ute tax.\" He argues that these penalties unfairly burden families and small businesses by increasing vehicle costs. Dutton\'s proposal includes halving the fuel excise for a year, promising an average annual saving of $750 per vehicle. ​\nWikipedia\n+11\nThe Guardian\n+11\nThe Guardian\n+11\nThe Western Weekender I Penrith News\n+3\nnews\n+3\nThe Guardian\n+3\n\nPrime Minister Anthony Albanese, however, isn\'t buying it. He labels Dutton\'s approach as \"nonsensical,\" pointing out that removing penalties undermines efforts to bring more fuel-efficient vehicles to Australia. Albanese emphasizes that the NVES is designed to reduce fuel costs and emissions, aligning Australia with global standards. ​\nThe Guardian\n+1\nSBS Australia\n+1\nnews\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+2\n\nThe Electric Vehicle Council isn\'t impressed either. They argue that without enforcement, the NVES becomes ineffective, likening it to having road rules without penalties. Critics warn that scrapping the fines could lead to Australia becoming a dumping ground for less efficient vehicles, hindering progress towards net-zero emissions. ​\nThe Guardian\n+2\nSBS Australia\n+2\nThe Western Weekender I Penrith News\n+2\nnews\n+5\nThe Guardian\n+5\nSBS Australia\n+5\n\nAs the election approaches, the debate over vehicle emissions standards highlights the contrasting visions of the major parties. While Dutton appeals to traditional motorists, Albanese focuses on long-term environmental and economic benefits. The outcome will significantly influence Australia\'s automotive and environmental landscape. ​\nThe Guardian', 0, 'factabot', 'clean-car-policy-duttons-ute-opia-vs-albaneses-efficiency-dreams', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-02 22:21:15', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (328, 'Ballot Bingo: Democracy Gets a Game Show Twist', 'AEC picks candidate order with blindfolds and balls.', 'In a move that blends tradition with a touch of theatrical flair, the Australian Electoral Commission (AEC) has finalized the candidate order for the upcoming federal election using a bingo-style system involving blindfolds and numbered wooden balls. ​\nThe Australia Institute\n+2\nABC\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+2\n\nAt Sydney\'s Masonic Centre, AEC officials, including Rebecca Main and Natalie (who donned the blindfold), conducted the draw. The process, reminiscent of a game show, involved blindfolded draws to determine the sequence in which candidates appear on the ballot paper. ​\nThe Guardian\n\nThis method stems from the understanding that ballot position can influence voter behavior. Studies suggest that candidates listed at the top of the ballot may receive a slight advantage due to \"donkey votes,\" where voters number candidates sequentially without much thought. ​\nThe Guardian\n+2\nABC\n+2\nThe Australia Institute\n+2\n\nBy employing this randomization technique, the AEC aims to uphold fairness and prevent any candidate from gaining an undue advantage based solely on their position. This approach also addresses past concerns, such as in the 2013 election, when the \"Liberal Democrats\" drew the first position and secured a Senate seat, partly due to voter confusion with the major Liberal Party. ​\nThe Guardian\n+2\nABC\n+2\nThe Australia Institute\n+2\nThe Australia Institute\n+1\nThe Guardian\n+1\n\nThe use of a bingo cage, blindfolds, and wooden balls not only adds a unique touch to the electoral process but also underscores Australia\'s commitment to ensuring that every vote counts equally, free from biases introduced by ballot order.​\nThe Guardian\n+1\nThe Australia Institute\n+1\n\nVisual Suggestion: A candid photograph capturing the AEC officials in action—blindfolded, drawing numbered balls from the bingo cage—would encapsulate the event\'s blend of tradition and transparency. Such images are often available through news outlets covering the event', 0, 'factabot', 'ballot-bingo-democracy-gets-a-game-show-twist', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-04-11 14:47:13', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (329, 'Flu Season 2025: Doctors Warn It\'s Gonna Be a Doozy', 'Flu cases already doubling, experts sound alarms.', 'Hold onto your tissues, folks, because flu season 2025 is upon us, and it\'s not here to play nice. Doctors are sounding the alarm, predicting a season that\'s not just bad but potentially catastrophic. Think of it as the flu\'s version of a blockbuster sequel—bigger, badder, and with more plot twists than you can shake a thermometer at.​\n\nLet\'s talk numbers. Between January and March, Australia recorded over 46,300 lab-confirmed influenza cases. That\'s more than a 50% increase compared to the same period last year. And if you thought that was a fluke, think again. Queensland Health reported nearly 9,000 flu notifications in just the first three months of 2025, up from just over 7,200 during the same period in 2024. ​\nABC\n+13\ncouriermail\n+13\nGavi\n+13\nABC\n+1\nMedscape\n+1\ncouriermail\n+1\nGavi\n+1\n\nBut wait, there\'s more. The flu season has started earlier than usual, with cases popping up like unwanted pop-up ads since March. This isn\'t just a random spike; it\'s a trend that\'s got health officials clutching their stethoscopes. And let\'s not forget the 2024 season, which saw a record-breaking 365,000 cases nationwide. Yet, less than a third of Australians bothered to get vaccinated. ​\ndailytelegraph\n+1\nnews\n+1\n\nNow, let\'s address the elephant (or should I say, germ) in the room: vaccination rates. They\'re declining faster than my will to live during a Zoom meeting. In 2024, only 61% of adults over 65 and a measly 25% of children under five received the flu vaccine. This apathy is a gift to the flu virus, allowing it to spread faster than gossip at a family reunion. ​\nnews\n\nSo, what\'s the takeaway here? Get vaccinated, people. It\'s free for many under the National Immunisation Program, and it\'s the best defense we\'ve got against this viral menace. Don\'t wait for the flu to come knocking; by then, it\'s too late to send it to voicemail.​\nABC\n+7\nSBS Australia\n+7\nnews\n+7\nwww1.racgp.org.au\n+5\nnews\n+5\nABC\n+5', 0, 'factabot', 'flu-season-2025-doctors-warn-its-gonna-be-a-doozy', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 12:35:31', 26);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (330, 'Eric Dane Diagnosed with ALS: McSteamy Faces a Real-Life Battle', 'Grey’s star announces ALS diagnosis.', 'In a move that has left fans and colleagues alike reaching for the tissues, Eric Dane, the man who brought us the unforgettable Dr. Mark Sloan (a.k.a. \"McSteamy\") on Grey\'s Anatomy and the complex Cal Jacobs in Euphoria, has revealed he\'s been diagnosed with amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS), commonly known as Lou Gehrig\'s disease. ​\nPage Six\n+6\nThe Guardian\n+6\nEW.com\n+6\n\nAt 52, Dane continues to embody resilience. Despite the daunting prognosis of ALS—a progressive neurodegenerative disease that gradually robs individuals of muscle control, speech, and eventually, the ability to breathe independently—he remains committed to his craft. Production for Euphoria\'s third season is set to commence on April 14, and true to form, Dane is eager to reprise his role as Cal Jacobs. He expressed, \"I feel fortunate that I am able to continue working and am looking forward to returning to set of Euphoria next week.\" ​\nPage Six\n+8\nThe Guardian\n+8\nNew York Post\n+8\nPeople.com\n+3\nEW.com\n+3\nNew York Post\n+3\nEW.com\n+7\nThe Daily Beast\n+7\nPeople.com\n+7\n\nThis announcement comes on the heels of personal developments in Dane\'s life. In March 2025, his wife, Rebecca Gayheart, filed to dismiss their divorce petition, signaling a renewed commitment to their family unit. Together since 2004, they share two daughters, Billie Beatrice, 15, and Georgia Geraldine, 13. Dane commented on their strengthened bond, stating, \"I am grateful to have my loving family by my side as we navigate this ... ​\nThe Guardian\n+7\nNew York Post\n+7\nE! Online\n+7\nEW.com\n+9\nE! Online\n+9\nPage Six\n+9\nE! Online\n+10\nThe Daily Beast\n+10\nPage Six\n+10\n\nALS, while currently incurable, affects approximately 30,000 individuals in the U.S. and 5,000 in the UK. Symptoms often begin with muscle weakness or twitching and can progress to impair speech, swallowing, and mobility. However, some individuals, like the esteemed physicist Stephen Hawking, have defied expectations, living with the disease for decades. ​\nThe Sun\nE! Online\n+7\nPeople.com\n+7\nNew York Post\n+7\nThe Guardian\n\nEric Dane\'s journey is a poignant reminder of the unpredictable nature of life and health. As he continues to face this formidable challenge with unwavering determination, our thoughts are with him and his family. We look forward to his continued contributions to the arts and stand in solidarity with him in this fight.', 0, 'factabot', 'eric-dane-diagnosed-with-als-mcsteamy-faces-a-real-life-battle', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 20:10:53', 21);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (331, 'Embryo Mix-Up: Brisbane Woman Gives Birth to Stranger\'s Baby', 'IVF clinic oopsie results in wrong baby being born.', 'In a shocking twist that sounds like something straight out of a poorly-scripted reality show, a Brisbane woman has just given birth to someone else\'s baby. That’s right, folks, she went to the hospital for her own little bundle of joy, and instead, she walked out with a child that biologically belongs to complete strangers. This all went down at Monash IVF, where a \"human error\" led to the wrong embryo being implanted. How does something like this even happen? Let’s just say it wasn’t an accidental mix-up with her morning coffee. It’s an IVF clinic, people. They specialize in making babies, not flipping pancakes.\n\nSo, what’s the deal here? According to Monash IVF, the mishap happened during the thawing and implantation process. I mean, they have \"strict protocols,\" but apparently those protocols didn’t include “don’t give this woman a random stranger’s baby.” The real parents, who thought they were getting their own bundle of joy, have been left to deal with the shock of their lives, while our Brisbane mom is busy Googling \"How to return a baby you didn’t order.\"\n\nOf course, no one expected this to be a simple fix. Let’s talk about the fun ethical and legal issues that are now being raised. Who’s the real parent here? The woman who carried the child or the couple that made the embryo? This could open a whole can of legal worms that no one signed up for, least of all the lawyers who will be cashing in on this one. The whole situation has left people questioning how something so personal, so life-altering, could slip through the cracks of an IVF clinic that’s supposed to be all about precision.\n\nBut don’t worry, Monash IVF is “investigating” the situation. Because that’s what you do when you hand someone else’s baby to a complete stranger—you investigate. Meanwhile, the rest of us are sitting here wondering how much \"strict protocols\" really mean when this kind of stuff happens. The fertility industry’s credibility is taking a hit, and well, it looks like the baby mix-up is going to be the next big thing to keep the public busy. It’s like a bad game of musical chairs, except the music stopped, and someone ended up with a baby that doesn’t belong to them.', 0, 'factabot', 'embryo-mix-up-brisbane-woman-gives-birth-to-strangers-baby', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 10:04:18', 23);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (332, 'AUKUS Submarine Saga: Albanese and Dutton\'s Underwater Tiff', 'Albanese reaffirms stealthy subs, Dutton accuses Labor of underfunding.', 'Oh, the AUKUS submarine saga—it\'s like watching a political tug-of-war where both sides are clutching waterlogged ropes. Let\'s dive in, shall we?\n\nFirst up, Opposition Leader Peter Dutton is having a full-on panic attack about the future of AUKUS under the Albanese government. He\'s clutching his pearls over alleged defense spending cuts, claiming Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has slashed $80 billion from defense. Dutton\'s all worked up, reminiscing about how the Coalition supposedly twisted President Biden\'s arm to get the nuclear-powered submarine deal over the line, despite Biden\'s well-known anti-proliferation stance. He paints a picture of the Coalition as the valiant knights who secured the holy grail of submarines, while Labor\'s just tossing coins into a wishing well. ​\nThe Nightly\n+4\nThe Australian\n+4\nReuters\n+4\n\nBut hold onto your periscopes, because Albanese isn\'t having any of it. He brushes off Dutton\'s concerns as \"irresponsible,\" suggesting that crying wolf over defense spending cuts is just political theater. After all, this is the same Labor government that\'s all in on AUKUS, ready to welcome nuclear-powered submarines with open arms starting in 2032. Albanese emphasizes that these submarines are all about deterrence and stealth, not some grand offensive strategy. He even accuses Dutton of playing into scare tactics, pointing to juvenile memes featuring three-eyed koalas and Simpsons jokes about radioactive waste. Apparently, Labor\'s idea of a nuclear debate involves less policy discussion and more meme warfare. ​\nThe Australian\n+1\nThe Guardian\n+1\nReuters\nThe Nightly\n\nNow, let\'s talk about the elephant—or should I say, the submarine—in the room: the deal itself. Former Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull isn\'t mincing words, calling the AUKUS submarine agreement \"unfair\" and potentially disastrous for Australia. He points out that despite Australia coughing up $3 billion to prop up the U.S. submarine industry, there\'s no guarantee we\'ll actually get any submarines. It\'s like paying for a luxury yacht and getting a rubber dinghy. Turnbull warns that this deal might leave Australia without its own submarine capability, making us overly dependent on U.S. military goodwill. And given the current state of U.S. politics, that goodwill might come with a side of unpredictability. ​\nThe Australian\n+12\nThe Australian\n+12\nWikipedia\n+12\nnews\n+1\nnews\n+1\n\nBut wait, there\'s more! Former defense force chief Chris Barrie is throwing shade on the whole AUKUS partnership, suggesting that the U.S. might not be the reliable ally we think they are. He draws parallels to the fall of Singapore in 1942, implying that putting all our defense eggs in the U.S. basket might not be the smartest move. Barrie advises the Australian government to reassess its strategic partnership with the U.S., especially considering the AUKUS deal\'s lack of concrete guarantees. It\'s like agreeing to a group project and realizing your partner doesn\'t even know the subject matter. ​\nThe Guardian\n\nSo, what\'s the takeaway from this submarine saga? Both Albanese and Dutton are busy pointing fingers, each accusing the other of undermining national security. Meanwhile, the AUKUS deal chugs along, raising questions about Australia\'s defense strategy, our relationship with the U.S., and whether we\'ve just signed up for a lifetime subscription to military uncertainty. Stay tuned, folks; this underwater drama is far from over.​\ndailytelegraph\n+2\nnews\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+2\nReuters', 0, 'factabot', 'aukus-submarine-saga-albanese-and-duttons-underwater-tiff', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 14:15:21', 21);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (333, 'Soft Plastics Get a Second Chance: Supermarkets Attempt Redemption', 'Woolies, Aldi, and Coles launch a new soft plastics recycling trial.', 'In a move that can only be described as a redemption arc worthy of a Netflix series, Australia\'s major supermarkets—Woolworths, Coles, and Aldi—are attempting to resurrect soft plastics recycling after the spectacular implosion of the REDcycle program in 2022.\n\nPicture this: the Soft Plastics Taskforce, a coalition of these retail giants, has launched a trial at 120 Woolworths stores across Western Sydney and coastal New South Wales. The grand plan? To expand this initiative to an additional 500 locations nationwide within the next year. This endeavor aims to tackle the gaping hole left in Australia\'s soft plastics recycling infrastructure after REDcycle\'s untimely demise. ​\nadelaidenow\n+3\nnews\n+3\nResource-Recycling\n+3\nThe Guardian\n+6\nABC\n+6\nsydneycityrubbish.com.au\n+6\n\nBut let\'s rewind a bit. REDcycle, once Australia\'s beacon of hope for soft plastics recycling, collapsed under the weight of its own ambitions. By late 2022, it was revealed that instead of being recycled, vast quantities of collected soft plastics were stockpiled in warehouses across the country, posing environmental and fire hazards. This revelation was as shocking as finding out your favorite reality TV star isn\'t actually \"just like us.\" ​\nABC\nWikipedia\n+1\nResource-Recycling\n+1\n\nFast forward to today, and the supermarkets, with a collective shrug and a \"let\'s try this again\" attitude, have taken it upon themselves to clean up the mess. They\'ve assumed responsibility for the stockpiled plastics and are collaborating with emerging recycling facilities to process these materials responsibly. The Australian Competition and Consumer Commission (ACCC) has even given them the green light to collaborate on this endeavor until July 31, 2026. ​\nABC\n+5\nnews\n+5\nReddit\n+5\n\nHowever, let\'s not get too carried away with the confetti just yet. While these efforts are a step in the right direction, the reality is that only a fraction of Australia\'s annual consumption of soft plastics is being recycled. With Australians consuming approximately 70 billion pieces of soft plastic each year, and a recycling rate hovering around a dismal 13%, it\'s clear that these supermarket-led initiatives are merely dipping their toes in a vast ocean of plastic waste. ​\nABC\n+2\nnews\n+2\nadelaidenow\n+2\n\nMoreover, the collapse of REDcycle serves as a cautionary tale about the challenges of recycling soft plastics. The program\'s downfall was largely due to contamination and the complexity of processing these materials. This begs the question: are we simply rearranging deck chairs on the Titanic, or is there a more sustainable solution on the horizon? ​\nsydneycityrubbish.com.au\n+3\nThe Guardian\n+3\nThe Guardian\n+3\n\nIn conclusion, while the supermarkets\' efforts to revive soft plastics recycling are commendable and offer a glimmer of hope, it\'s evident that a more comprehensive, nationwide strategy is needed. This strategy should involve not just corporate players but also government bodies, specialized recyclers, and, crucially, consumers. After all, when it comes to recycling, everyone has a part to play—except, perhaps, for the soft plastics themselves, which seem content to play musical chairs in our landfills.', 0, 'factabot', 'soft-plastics-get-a-second-chance-supermarkets-attempt-redemption', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 23:33:13', 29);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (334, 'LATAM Airlines Exec\'s Turbulent Home Life: Scissors Allegedly Involved', 'LATAM manager charged over alleged scissor threat to wife.', 'In a plot twist that could give any telenovela a run for its money, Christopher Ellis, the Australasian manager of LATAM Airlines, finds himself embroiled in a domestic drama featuring scissors, accusations, and a bear hug that’s anything but cuddly. The saga unfolds in the cozy suburbs of Annandale, Sydney, where Ellis and his estranged wife have been navigating a relationship more turbulent than a red-eye flight. ​\ndailytelegraph\n\nThe trouble began in April 2024, when an argument escalated to Ellis allegedly brandishing a pair of scissors \"as if he intended to use it to stab,\" leaving his wife fearing for her safety. Ellis, ever the diplomat, claimed he was merely relocating the scissors from the dishwasher to the drawer—a domestic chore gone awry. ​\ndailytelegraph\n\nFast forward to December, and the plot thickens. After a late-night work event, his wife secretly recorded an argument where Ellis allegedly accused her of infidelity, grabbed her twice, and \"flung\" her to the floor to prevent her departure. He conceded to holding her in a \"bear hug\" but denied any floor-related activities. This recording led to Ellis\'s arrest, a passport confiscation, and a travel ban that grounded his international LATAM duties. ​\ndailytelegraph\n\nIn a courtroom cameo, Ellis pleaded not guilty to charges including assault and intimidation. He argued that attending international meetings was crucial for his job, suggesting that missing them might result in a pink slip. The judge, perhaps swayed by the potential loss of airline perks, lifted the travel ban under strict conditions, allowing Ellis to resume his high-flying responsibilities. ​\ndailytelegraph\n+1\nWikipedia\n+1\n\nThis real-life drama not only airs the couple\'s dirty laundry but also raises questions about workplace policies regarding employees embroiled in legal entanglements. As Ellis continues to navigate his personal turbulence, one can\'t help but wonder if LATAM Airlines offers a frequent flyer program for courtroom appearances.', 0, 'factabot', 'latam-airlines-execs-turbulent-home-life-scissors-allegedly-involved', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 19:53:47', 6);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (335, 'Science Nerd Orders Uranium Online—What Could Possibly Go Wrong?', 'Sydney man sentenced after ordering uranium and plutonium to family home.', 'In a tale that blends youthful curiosity with a hefty dose of naiveté, 24-year-old Emmanuel Lidden, a Sydney native with a penchant for collecting elements from the periodic table, found himself at the center of a radioactive fiasco. In 2023, Lidden, perhaps inspired by Bill Gates\' own collection, ordered small samples of depleted uranium and plutonium from a U.S.-based science website, having them delivered to his parents\' home in southern Sydney. ​\nThe Guardian\n+3\nnews\n+3\ndailytelegraph\n+3\nThe Guardian\n+2\ndailytelegraph\n+2\nnews\n+2\n\nThe arrival of these materials triggered a full-scale emergency response, including street closures and hazmat-suited raids, as authorities scrambled to assess the potential threat. However, experts later deemed the quantities harmless, suggesting one could ingest the entire amount without adverse effects. ​\nnews\n+1\ndailytelegraph\n+1\n\nLidden pleaded guilty to importing and possessing nuclear materials without a permit. In a somewhat lenient turn, Judge Leonie Flannery acknowledged Lidden\'s mental health challenges and lack of malicious intent, opting not to record a conviction. Instead, Lidden received an 18-month good behavior bond, sparing him from potential jail time. ​\nYahoo News Australia\n+3\nnews\n+3\ndailytelegraph\n+3\nThe Guardian\n+1\nnews\n+1\n\nThis incident underscores the complexities surrounding the importation of radioactive materials, highlighting the need for stringent regulations to prevent misuse, while also considering the intent and awareness of individuals involved.', 0, 'factabot', 'science-nerd-orders-uranium-online-what-could-possibly-go-wrong', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 19:41:10', 29);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (336, 'Sky News Debate: When Viewers and Commentators Disagree', 'Audience backs Albanese in debate, Sky pundits stunned.', 'Oh, Sky News Australia—a veritable cauldron of viewer discontent and commentator kerfuffles. Let\'s unpack this delightful mess, shall we?\n\nFirst, we have the National Press Club debate where Chris Uhlmann took Energy Minister Chris Bowen to task over Labor\'s electricity bill promises. Meanwhile, a Sky News viewer panel crowned Anthony Albanese the winner, leaving News Corp commentators scratching their heads, wondering if they\'d accidentally tuned into a different debate. ​\nThe Guardian\n\nThen there\'s the curious case of Erin Molan, who was shown the door at Sky News. While budget constraints were cited, some whisper it had more to do with her unabashed pro-Israel stance. Molan, ever the diplomat, refutes these claims, attributing her exit solely to fiscal tightening. ​\nLog in or sign up to view\n+3\nnews\n+3\nnews\n+3\n\nAnd let\'s not forget the infamous interview with far-right extremist Blair Cottrell. Sky News thought it a grand idea to give him a platform, resulting in public outcry and the resignation of commentator Craig Emerson in protest. Sky News later admitted it was a misstep, but by then, the damage was done. ​\nThe Guardian\n+1\nWikipedia\n+1\n\nPeta Credlin, a Sky News host, also wears the dual hats of journalist and Liberal Party advisor. While she\'s bagged awards for her journalistic endeavors, her behind-the-scenes political maneuvers have raised more than a few eyebrows, blurring the lines between reporting and politicking. ​\nThe Guardian\n\nRowan Dean, the face of \"Outsiders,\" has stirred the pot with his controversial remarks, including calling climate change a \"fraudulent and dangerous cult.\" Not to mention his racially charged comments about Chinese people, which led to his ousting from Sky News. ​\nWikipedia\n+3\nWikipedia\n+3\nThe Guardian\n+3\n\nSky News\' penchant for controversy doesn\'t end there. They\'ve aired interviews with figures like Blair Cottrell, a far-right extremist, and faced backlash for providing a platform to such individuals. This has led to calls for boycotts and a reevaluation of their editorial choices. ​\nThe Guardian\n+1\nWikipedia\n+1\n\nIn the grand tapestry of media, Sky News Australia seems to be the thread that keeps unraveling, much to the chagrin of its viewers and the bemusement of its critics. Stay tuned, folks; this circus is far from over.​', 0, 'factabot', 'sky-news-debate-when-viewers-and-commentators-disagree', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 08:26:33', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (337, 'Dutton\'s Terror Plot Target Status: Now with Extra Sympathy', 'PM Albanese calls Dutton after terror threat targeting him revealed.', 'In a development that adds a new layer of complexity to the ongoing political drama, Opposition Leader Peter Dutton has confirmed that his family home was the target of an alleged bomb plot.\n\nThe plot, reportedly orchestrated by a 16-year-old Brisbane student, involved plans to attack Dutton\'s residence using explosives and a drone. The teenager has since been charged and is awaiting trial, facing potential life imprisonment if convicted. ​\nWikipedia\n+6\nThe Australian\n+6\nThe Australian\n+6\nWikipedia\n+5\nAP News\n+5\nThe Australian\n+5\n\nThis revelation has prompted an outpouring of sympathy from various quarters, including Prime Minister Anthony Albanese, who reached out to Dutton, emphasizing that such threats have no place in Australian politics. The Australian Federal Police have also been commended for their role in safeguarding Dutton and his family, with Dutton expressing gratitude for their protection. ​\n\nThe incident has shed light on the escalating security challenges faced by public figures in Australia, with a significant increase in reported threats against parliamentarians. The Australian Federal Police reported over 1,000 threats to parliamentarians in the 2023-24 fiscal year, with 712 already recorded by March 2025. ​\nAP News\n+1\nStar Tribune\n+1\n\nAs the election campaign progresses, this development adds a new dimension to the political landscape, prompting discussions about security, public safety, and the well-being of public servants and their families', 0, 'factabot', 'duttons-terror-plot-target-status-now-with-extra-sympathy', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 11:00:22', 21);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (338, 'Melbourne\'s April Heatwave: Mother Nature\'s Hot Flash', '30°C in April? Climate change just put on shades and strutted in.', 'Hold onto your sun hats, Melbourne, because Mother Nature\'s decided to crank up the thermostat this April. A high-pressure system is settling over southeastern Australia, pushing temperatures up to 12°C above average. Melbourne\'s forecasted to hit a sizzling 30°C this weekend, marking the warmest April days in four years. ​\nheraldsun\n+3\nThe Guardian\n+3\nnews\n+3\n\nThis unseasonal warmth isn\'t just a one-off. Australia\'s recent climate report card shows 2024 as the second-hottest year on record, with temperatures averaging 1.46°C above the 1961–1990 baseline. And now, in April 2025, Melbourne\'s basking in temperatures typically reserved for mid-summer.​\nnews\nnews\n+2\nABC\n+2\nABC\n+2\n\nBut it\'s not all sunshine and rainbows. Elevated temperatures bring heightened fire risks. Fire danger warnings are in place for various southern districts, urging residents to stay vigilant. ​\nnews\n+1\nThe Guardian\n+1\nThe Guardian\n\nLooking ahead, the Bureau of Meteorology\'s crystal ball predicts above-average temperatures for the coming months. From May to July, most of Australia can expect warmer-than-usual days and nights, continuing the trend of our increasingly toasty climate. ​\nnews\n+1\nThe Guardian\n+1\n\nSo, Melbourne, as you swap your winter woollies for summer shorts, remember to stay cool, stay safe, and maybe invest in some extra sunscreen.', 0, 'factabot', 'melbournes-april-heatwave-mother-natures-hot-flash', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 14:06:53', 30);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (339, 'ALT: Games Festival Levels Up Sydney\'s Nerd Scene', 'Parramatta becomes ground zero for gaming geeks.', 'Get ready, Sydney, because the ALT: Games Festival is about to drop into Parramatta and crank up your nerd credentials to a solid 11. This isn’t your average “bring-your-own-controller” kind of event. No, this is a celebration of gaming culture, indie creators, and anything that gives you an excuse to binge on snacks while obsessively clicking buttons for hours. It’s all happening on April 12–13, 2025, at PHIVE in Parramatta Square. So, if you’ve ever daydreamed about escaping into a pixelated world, now’s your chance to make it a reality.\n\nLet’s break it down: first up, ALT: Play, the free digital showcase, will have you drooling over local indie games and cutting-edge creations that are still in progress. Think of it as the game developer version of “coming soon” trailers that actually look good. Also, let’s not forget the curious minds behind Inscryption and Magic: The Gathering. Daniel Mullins and Richard Garfield are leading workshops and discussions that could turn your next game dev dream into a reality (or at least give you a lot of cool new ideas).\n\nAnd just to spice things up a little more, there\'s an exhibition curated by Serenade called ALT: Ex, which will have you questioning whether the games you’re playing are art or just another way to pass the time. Spoiler: they\'re both. Then there’s ALT: Installation, which includes the Australian debut of “How (Not) To Get Hit by a Self-Driving Car.” Yeah, it’s interactive. Yes, it’s weird. And yes, you’re going to want to try it.\n\nBut wait, there\'s more! This festival is aiming to be the beating heart of Sydney’s gaming scene, welcoming anyone from casual gamers to hardcore devs. Whether you’re looking to discover new titles, learn from the best in the biz, or just soak in the mind-bending world of interactive gaming, ALT: Games Festival has got you covered. So, clear your weekend, because it’s time to play, learn, and probably get lost in a digital world that might just steal your soul (in a good way, obviously).The festival is designed for all levels of gamers and creators, aiming to inspire and connect Sydney\'s gaming community. ​\nPowerhouse Museum - Home\n\nEvent Details:\n\nDates: Saturday, April 12, and Sunday, April 13, 2025​\ndailytelegraph\n\nTime: 10:00 AM – 3:00 PM (ALT: Features from 5:00 PM – 7:00 PM)​\nHome | City of Parramatta\n+1\nAT Parramatta\n+1\n\nLocation: PHIVE, 5 Parramatta Square, Parramatta NSW 2150​\nInstagram\n+7\nPowerhouse Museum - Home\n+7\nAT Parramatta\n+7\n\nAdmission: Many events are free; some workshops and sessions have a nominal fee. ​\n\nFor more information and to register, visit the Powerhouse Museum\'s official website', 0, 'factabot', 'alt-games-festival-levels-up-sydneys-nerd-scene', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-11 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 10:56:13', 29);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (340, 'Albanese and Dutton duel with tax relief promises at campaign launches', 'It’s the Hunger Games: Tax Edition. Albo waves around $1k like it’s a Bunnings gift card, while Dutton dangles mortgage scraps. Who needs policy when you’ve got bribes in bold font?', 'In a high-stakes political showdown, Prime Minister Anthony Albanese and Opposition Leader Peter Dutton have unveiled competing tax relief and housing policies as they officially launched their campaigns for the upcoming federal election on May 3, 2025.​\nThe Guardian\n+3\nThe Australian\n+3\nReuters\n+3\n\nAlbanese\'s Approach: Simplification and Support\n\nPrime Minister Albanese introduced a streamlined tax policy, proposing a $1,000 \"instant tax deduction\" for all workers, eliminating the need for receipts. This measure aims to simplify tax returns and is expected to benefit approximately 5.7 million Australians. ​\nYouTube\n+4\nThe Guardian\n+4\nYouTube\n+4\n\nIn addressing housing affordability, Albanese pledged a $10 billion investment to construct 100,000 new homes exclusively for first-time buyers. The plan includes allowing purchases with just a 5% deposit, with the government guaranteeing the remaining 15%, thereby removing the need for costly mortgage insurance. ​\nWikipedia\n+7\nThe Guardian\n+7\nnews\n+7\n\nDutton\'s Counteroffer: Immediate Relief Measures\n\nOpposition Leader Dutton responded with a proposal for a one-off $1,200 tax offset targeting low- to middle-income earners, aiming to provide immediate cost-of-living relief. Additionally, he introduced a scheme allowing first-home buyers to deduct mortgage interest payments for up to five years on loans up to $650,000. ​\nThe Nightly\n+6\nThe Guardian\n+6\nnews\n+6\n\nDutton\'s campaign also includes a significant fuel excise cut and promises of further rebates, estimating up to $2,400 in savings per family. ​\nnews\n+5\nThe Australian\n+5\nheraldsun\n+5\n\nA Battle of Visions\n\nBoth leaders are vying for the support of financially stressed voters, particularly in key battlegrounds. While Albanese focuses on long-term structural reforms to housing and tax systems, Dutton emphasizes immediate financial relief measures.​\nThe Australian\n+1\nReuters\n+1\n\nAs the election approaches, Australians are presented with distinct choices: a vision of systemic change aimed at future stability versus immediate interventions designed to alleviate current economic pressures. The electorate\'s decision will shape the nation\'s policy direction in the coming years.', 0, 'factabot', 'albanese-and-dutton-duel-with-tax-relief-promises-at-campaign-launches', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-13 00:00:00', '2025-05-02 00:36:24', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (341, 'Labor proposes $1k automatic tax deduction for all workers', 'Labor’s genius idea: a $1,000 tax write-off without receipts. It’s like Afterpay for political promises—free now, reality later.', 'In a bold move to simplify tax returns and provide financial relief, Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has unveiled a proposal for a $1,000 automatic tax deduction for all Australian workers. This initiative, announced during Labor\'s campaign launch in Perth, aims to streamline the tax process by eliminating the need for receipts or detailed expense tracking.​\n\nThe Proposal\nUnder the proposed plan, workers can claim a $1,000 deduction on work-related expenses without providing documentation. This \"instant tax deduction\" is designed to benefit approximately 5.7 million Australians, particularly those who find the current system cumbersome. For individuals who typically claim more than $1,000 in deductions, the traditional method remains available. The average tax relief is estimated at $205, with those earning between $45,000 and $135,000 potentially seeing benefits up to $320 \nThe Guardian\n.​\n\nContext and Rationale\nThe current tax system allows for a $300 deduction without receipts, but many workers either overlook this benefit or find the process of tracking expenses daunting. Albanese emphasized that the new policy would \"take away the hassle of tracking your expenses, especially if you work from home,\" and ensure that taxpayers receive more of their own money promptly .​\n9News\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+2\n\nPolitical Landscape\nThis announcement comes as both major parties gear up for the upcoming federal election. Opposition Leader Peter Dutton has countered with a proposal for a one-off $1,200 tax offset for low- to middle-income earners, alongside a scheme allowing first-home buyers to deduct mortgage interest payments for up to five years on loans up to $650,000 .​\nThe Guardian\n\nWhile Labor\'s plan focuses on long-term structural reform, the Coalition\'s approach offers immediate financial relief. Both parties accuse each other of presenting short-term \"sugar hit\" policies to win voter support amid rising cost-of-living pressures.​\n\nImplications\nIf implemented, Labor\'s $1,000 automatic tax deduction could significantly ease the tax filing process for millions and provide modest financial relief. However, the proposal\'s success will depend on its reception by the electorate and its effectiveness in addressing broader economic challenges.​', 0, 'factabot', 'labor-proposes-1k-automatic-tax-deduction-for-all-workers', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-13 00:00:00', '2025-04-14 01:37:15', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (342, 'Dutton promises $12k mortgage interest relief for first homebuyers', 'Dutton: “Can’t afford a house? Here’s $12k back in interest.” It’s like throwing glitter on a dumpster fire, but thanks anyway.', 'In a bold move to win over first-time homebuyers, Opposition Leader Peter Dutton has unveiled a plan that sounds like it was concocted during a late-night infomercial binge. Under the Coalition\'s proposal, eligible Australians purchasing newly built homes could deduct interest payments on up to $650,000 of their mortgage from their taxable income. This scheme, capped at five years, promises potential savings of up to $12,000 annually—or $55,000 over the full term—for singles earning up to $175,000 and couples up to $250,000 \nThe Australian\n.​\n\nDutton, positioning himself as the \"prime minister who restores the dream of home ownership,\" aims to counteract Labor\'s housing initiatives with this tax relief strategy. However, critics argue that such measures may inflate housing demand without addressing the underlying supply issues, potentially exacerbating affordability challenges \nnews\n.​\n\nWhile the proposal offers immediate financial relief, questions linger about its long-term efficacy in solving Australia\'s housing crisis. As the election approaches, voters must weigh the allure of short-term savings against the need for sustainable housing solutions.', 0, 'factabot', 'dutton-promises-12k-mortgage-interest-relief-for-first-homebuyers', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-13 00:00:00', '2025-05-01 14:20:43', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (343, '9-year-old boy dies after accidental shooting in NSW town', 'Australia’s gun safety says hi—by not working. A 9-year-old is gone, and yet somehow the guns are still around. Tragedy, meet negligence.', 'Tragedy in Windellama: 9-Year-Old Boy Dies in Accidental Shooting\n\nA devastating incident occurred on Sunday morning in Windellama, a rural community near Goulburn, New South Wales, where a nine-year-old boy lost his life due to an accidental shooting.​\n\nIncident Details\n\nEmergency services were called to a property on Fernleigh Close around 11:20 a.m. following reports of a shooting. Upon arrival, officers from the Hume Police District were informed that the child had sustained serious neck injuries from the unintentional discharge of a firearm. Despite prompt medical attention from NSW Ambulance paramedics, the boy was pronounced dead at the scene \nThe Guardian\n.​\n\nCommunity Response\n\nThe small community of Windellama, home to approximately 413 residents, is in mourning. Goulburn state MP Wendy Tuckerman expressed her condolences, describing the event as a \"terrible tragedy\" and extended her heartfelt sympathies to the family involved .​\n7NEWS\n+3\nnews\n+3\nRegion Canberra\n+3\n\nOngoing Investigation\n\nNSW Police have commenced an investigation into the circumstances surrounding the incident. A report will be prepared for the coroner to determine the exact cause and any contributing factors .​\nThe Guardian\n\nThis tragic event underscores the importance of firearm safety and the need for vigilance, especially in households with children.​', 0, 'factabot', '9-year-old-boy-dies-after-accidental-shooting-in-nsw-town', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-13 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 22:20:57', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (344, 'Man found stabbed to death in Endeavour Hills home', 'Melbourne crime report: another day, another kitchen knife gone rogue. Police investigating what feels like the 47th stabbing this week.', 'A 21-year-old man was found dead from stab wounds early Sunday morning at a residence on Mossgiel Park Drive in Endeavour Hills. Police responded to the call around 6:30am and discovered the victim with injuries consistent with a stabbing. A 19-year-old man from Springvale South, who was found nearby, was taken into custody and interviewed by homicide detectives. Authorities believe the two individuals were acquainted. Devastated family members and friends of the victim gathered at the scene, visibly distressed by the incident. ​\nheraldsun\n+7\nheraldsun\n+7\nVictoria Police\n+7', 0, 'factabot', 'man-found-stabbed-to-death-in-endeavour-hills-home', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-13 00:00:00', '2025-05-02 00:14:57', 6);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (345, 'Gout Gout amazes crowd again as showdown looms', 'Gout Gout isn’t just a name—it’s a vibe. Kid’s faster than your Wi-Fi and cooler than your Nikes. Olympic legends just got outrun by a walking headline.', 'Gout Gout: The Teen Tornado Who Just Outran Bolt’s Ghost (Sort Of)\n\nAt just 17, Gout Gout has become Australia’s sprinting sensation, leaving spectators and commentators in awe. During the 2025 Australian Athletics Championships in Perth, Gout clocked a blistering 19.84 seconds in the 200m final. While this time was wind-assisted and thus ineligible for record purposes, it still places him as the second-fastest U20 athlete in history under any conditions, surpassing legends like Usain Bolt and Justin Gatlin \nnews\n.​\n\nThe much-anticipated showdown with rival Lachlan Kennedy ended prematurely when Kennedy false-started and was disqualified. Undeterred, Gout dominated the race, showcasing his exceptional talent and composure \nnews\n.​\n\nGout\'s meteoric rise has drawn comparisons to sprinting greats, and his performances have ignited excitement about the future of Australian athletics. With his eyes set on the 2032 Brisbane Olympics, Gout is undoubtedly a name to watch in the coming years.​\nnews\n+6\ncouriermail\n+6\nThe Australian\n+6\nOlympics\n+2\nThe Australian\n+2\ncouriermail\n+2', 0, 'factabot', 'gout-gout-amazes-crowd-again-as-showdown-looms', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-13 00:00:00', '2025-05-02 01:05:44', 21);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (346, 'Rory Sloane defends Bailey Smith amid fan incident fallout', 'Bailey Smith caught heat, and Rory Sloane ran PR like a true teammate. AFL drama level: reality TV but with shin guards.', 'Rory Sloane Defends Bailey Smith Amid Fan Incident Fallout\n\nIn a recent AFL controversy, Geelong\'s Bailey Smith was fined $1,000 for making an obscene gesture towards a fan during a match against Adelaide. The incident occurred after the fan directed a personal and vulgar slur at Smith\'s teammate, Patrick Dangerfield. ​\nNine\n+2\n3AW\n+2\nYahoo News AU\n+2\n\nAdelaide great Rory Sloane criticized the AFL\'s decision to fine Smith, arguing that the league should focus on addressing inappropriate fan behavior. Sloane stated, \"What that fan spoke about was so pointed and personal and vulgar. You don\'t want to see that in our game.\" ​\nNine\n\nSmith acknowledged that his response was not ideal, especially considering the presence of young fans, and apologized for his actions. However, he emphasized the importance of standing up for teammates when faced with offensive remarks. ​\n\nThe AFL has indicated that it is reviewing the incident and considering appropriate measures to address fan conduct at games. ​\nNine', 0, 'factabot', 'rory-sloane-defends-bailey-smith-amid-fan-incident-fallout', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-13 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 15:14:28', 19);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (347, 'Dominican nightclub collapse death toll rises to 226', 'What started as a party turned into a morgue. Structural integrity said “I’m out,” and 226 lives later, officials are still “looking into it.”', 'What started as a Saturday night groove has turned into the deadliest structural oops in Dominican Republic history. A crowd of partygoers at the Euforia Club in Santiago were mid-reggaeton when the building collapsed like a wet paper straw under a cinder block. Over 226 people are now confirmed dead, with emergency crews still digging through rubble and half the country asking: “How the hell did no one see this coming?” +Listín Diario\n\nThe club was allegedly undergoing “renovations,” which in developer-speak often translates to: we put lipstick on a concrete pig. Authorities had apparently issued prior warnings about the venue’s structural integrity—warnings that were apparently filed directly in the bin. Local media reports suggest the second floor, packed with VIPs and overpriced cocktails, simply gave up. +Diario Libre\n\nNow comes the real party: the blame game. City officials are pointing fingers at the owners, who are blaming contractors, who are blaming...gravity? Meanwhile, the Ministry of Public Works has launched a “full investigation,” which probably means a whole lot of nothing until the media heat dies down. +El Nacional\n\nAnd now, the “latest update” twist you didn’t ask for: the club’s license had expired two years ago. That’s right—this wasn’t just a freak accident. It was a bureaucratic house of cards held together by vibes and negligence. Families are demanding answers, lawsuits are piling up, and the country is now wondering how many more “Euforias” are hiding in plain sight. +Hoy Digital', 0, 'factabot', 'dominican-nightclub-collapse-death-toll-rises-to-226', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-13 00:00:00', '2025-04-14 15:19:52', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (348, 'Jacinta Price denies \'Make Australia Great Again\' remark', '“MAGA who?” says Jacinta Price, caught cosplaying as Trump-lite. Next up: denying she ever heard of red hats.', 'Jacinta Price’s “MAGA” Moment: A Slip, a Denial, and a Whole Lot of Backpedaling\n\nAt a recent campaign rally in Perth, Senator Jacinta Nampijinpa Price declared her intent to \"make Australia great again,\" echoing the slogan popularized by former U.S. President Donald Trump. The remark, made alongside Coalition leader Peter Dutton, drew immediate attention and comparisons to Trump\'s rhetoric. ​\n9News\n+9\nThe Guardian\n+9\nThe Guardian\n+9\n\nWhen questioned about the statement, Price claimed she didn\'t realize she had used the phrase and denied any connection to Trump. She accused the media of being \"obsessed with Donald Trump\" and emphasized her focus on Australian issues. ​\nnews\n+2\n9News\n+2\n9News\n+2\nnews\n+3\nThe Guardian\n+3\n9News\n+3\n\nHowever, images have surfaced showing Price and her husband wearing \"Make America Great Again\" attire at a Christmas event, raising questions about the sincerity of her denial. \nThe Guardian\n​\n\nOpposition leader Peter Dutton attempted to deflect questions about the incident, focusing instead on cost-of-living issues affecting Australians. \n9News\n​\n\nThe incident has sparked debate about the influence of U.S. political rhetoric on Australian politics and the strategies employed by the Coalition in the lead-up to the federal election.​\nThe Guardian\n+6\nThe Guardian\n+6\nThe Guardian\n+6\n\nAs the campaign continues, the Coalition faces scrutiny over its messaging and the potential impact of aligning, even inadvertently, with controversial international figures.​\nThe Guardian\n\nThe phrase \"make Australia great again\" may have been a slip of the tongue, but its implications are resonating throughout the political landscape.', 0, 'factabot', 'jacinta-price-denies-make-australia-great-again-remark', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-13 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 20:13:07', 26);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (349, 'Woman raped by \'rideshare driver\' speaks out as attacker jailed', 'Rideshare nightmare: predator jailed, survivor speaks. Justice limps in, late and exhausted, but at least it showed up.', 'Rideshare Horror: Woman Speaks Out as Predator Driver Jailed\n\nIn a harrowing case that underscores the vulnerabilities within rideshare systems, a woman has bravely come forward after her attacker, a man posing as a rideshare driver, was sentenced to 290 years in prison for a series of kidnappings and sexual assaults in Denver. Between 2018 and 2022, John Pastor-Mendoza exploited the trust placed in rideshare services, targeting at least 12 women, sexually assaulting two and attempting to assault seven others .​\nDenver 7 Colorado News (KMGH)\n+1\nDenver 7 Colorado News (KMGH)\n+1\n\nThe survivor recounted the traumatic experience of being abducted and assaulted after believing she was entering a legitimate rideshare vehicle. Her courage in sharing her story has been pivotal in bringing attention to the dangers posed by individuals who exploit these platforms for predatory purposes.​\n\nThis case is not isolated. In Melbourne, a 60-year-old man was sentenced to 8½ years in prison for sexually assaulting three women who mistook him for their Uber driver . Similarly, in Phoenix, a man pretending to be a rideshare driver was arrested after sexually assaulting a woman he picked up outside a nightclub .​\nnews\nhttps://www.azfamily.com\n\nThese incidents highlight the urgent need for enhanced safety measures within the rideshare industry. Advocates are calling for stricter verification processes for drivers, increased public awareness campaigns, and the implementation of safety features within rideshare apps to protect passengers.​\nheraldsun\n\nAs the survivor stated, sharing her story is not just about seeking justice for herself but also about preventing such tragedies from happening to others. Her bravery serves as a catalyst for change, urging both the public and rideshare companies to prioritize passenger safety above all.', 0, 'factabot', 'woman-raped-by-rideshare-driver-speaks-out-as-attacker-jailed', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-13 00:00:00', '2025-04-21 13:19:17', 7);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (350, 'Albanese and Dutton Unveil Competing $10B Housing Plans Amid Election Campaign', 'Two men, one election, and a $10 billion promise each—because nothing says \'vote for me\' like a housing auction on steroids.', 'In the blue corner, we have Prime Minister Anthony Albanese, the man who once fronted a band called Rough Trade and now fronts an even rougher trade: federal politics. Albo’s rebrand as Housing Hero™ sees him pledging 100,000 new homes with a $10 billion Housing Australia Future Fund—because apparently nothing says “starter home” like a sentence with the word “fund” in it. Meanwhile, in the red corner, Opposition Leader Peter Dutton—whose vibe is somewhere between “school principal” and “man yelling at clouds”—thinks the answer is less bureaucracy and more tax breaks, because what struggling renters really need is deductions they can’t claim. +ABC News\n\nThis brick-measuring contest comes with all the fanfare of a Bunnings sausage sizzle but none of the satisfaction. Labor’s plan hinges on building homes in “well-located” areas, a phrase so vague it could mean anything from near a train station to “not entirely underwater.” The Coalition’s plan? Temporarily ban foreign buyers (again) and dangle some developer candy, a strategy that’s been about as effective as duct taping over a leaky roof. +The Guardian Australia\n\nThe kicker here is both parties acting like this is their first rodeo, when in reality, they’ve been riding this same housing affordability bull for decades. Home ownership has become Australia’s favourite impossible dream, especially for millennials who now treat “buying a house” like it’s a rare Pokémon. Yet every election, both sides roll out the same blueprint-flavoured buzzwords while quietly backing policies that inflate the market. +The Conversation\n\nToday’s update? Dutton has added a spicy new twist: a ban on foreign buyers to “help Aussies compete,” as if overseas investors were the only reason Timmy from Geelong can’t afford a shoebox in Melbourne. Meanwhile, Albo keeps hyping the Housing Fund like it’s the iPhone 27. Voters are left wondering who’ll actually build homes—and who’s just laying political bricks for fun. +Sydney Morning Herald', 0, 'factabot', 'albanese-and-dutton-unveil-competing-10b-housing-plans-amid-election-campaign', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-14 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 22:10:56', 24);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (351, 'Australian Academics Avoid US Conferences Over Detention Fears', 'When your research trip includes a free cavity search, maybe it\'s time to Zoom in instead.', 'Australian academics are increasingly declining invitations to attend conferences in the United States due to fears of being detained or denied entry at the border. Since Donald Trump\'s return to office, reports of unpredictable border control policies, especially affecting disabled, LGBTQ+, and minority academics, have led to heightened concern. Gemma Lucy Smart, a disabled and queer PhD student, opted to attend a Seattle conference remotely, citing safety risks. The Society for Social Studies of Science shifted its conference format to hybrid in response to growing uncertainty over U.S. travel conditions. Additionally, changes in U.S. policies have resulted in rescinded scholarships, terminated research collaborations, and denied grant funding. The Australian National Tertiary Education Union acknowledged multiple reports of career disruptions, particularly among LGBTQ+ researchers. Concerns include the inspection of electronic devices at the border and the scrutiny of travelers\' medications and identities. These developments are seen as a threat to global academic collaboration, particularly in fields that rely heavily on interaction with U.S. institutions. As a result, academics are avoiding U.S. travel to protect their personal safety and professional integrity. ', 0, 'factabot', 'australian-academics-avoid-us-conferences-over-detention-fears', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-14 00:00:00', '2025-05-01 17:48:28', 21);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (352, 'Russia\'s New Hobby? Turning Cities into Bullseyes', 'Russia continues its \'special operation\' of redefining civilian areas as target practice zones.', 'When Vladimir Putin said he was launching a \"special military operation,\" apparently he meant a rebranding exercise for war crimes. Over the weekend, Moscow celebrated Palm Sunday with its signature move—flattening civilians. This time, the Ukrainian city of Sumy got the ‘liberation treatment’ with Russian missiles wiping out at least 34 people, injuring over 100, and turning a university and a shopping street into a scene from a Michael Bay movie—minus the hero and with zero plot. +WSJ\n\nZelensky, Ukraine’s increasingly exhausted president-turned-doomsday spokesperson, called it “deliberate terrorism.” And honestly? Hard to disagree when missiles hit students, shoppers, and literal children. Just days before, a U.S. envoy met Putin in St. Petersburg to \"negotiate peace.\" Spoiler: The Kremlin responded not with words, but with explosions. Diplomacy in Russian apparently translates to \"duck and cover.\" +AP\n\nFrance’s Emmanuel Macron emerged from his palace to declare the strike “undermines peace.” Bold insight, mon ami. Meanwhile, the U.S. keeps sending condolences like they’re Hallmark cards—while Moscow continues its very real, very deadly Monopoly game, now owning about 20% of Ukraine’s territory. +Reuters\n\nLatest update? Russia shows zero signs of slowing down, the international community clutches its pearls, and civilians in Ukraine are left to wonder which hospital, school, or apartment block will become the next “strategic target.” Putin calls it a military objective. The rest of the world calls it what it is: terrorism with a propaganda bow. +NY Post', 0, 'factabot', 'russias-new-hobby-turning-cities-into-bullseyes', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-14 00:00:00', '2025-04-14 13:11:13', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (353, 'Teen Sprinter Gout Gout Breaks 20-Second Barrier in 200m', 'At 17, Gout Gout runs faster than your Wi-Fi—time to upgrade both.', 'Seventeen-year-old Australian sprinting sensation Gout Gout has once again electrified the athletics world by clocking a blistering 19.84 seconds in the 200m final at the 2025 Australian Athletics Championships in Perth. Although the performance was wind-assisted with a +2.2 m/s tailwind—just above the legal limit—it marks the second-fastest 200m ever run by an under-20 athlete, trailing only Erriyon Knighton’s 19.49 in 2022. ​\nYouTube\n+10\ntalkSPORT\n+10\nThe Guardian\n+10\nnews\n+8\nLatest news & breaking headlines\n+8\nFOX SPORTS\n+8\n\nGout\'s meteoric rise has drawn comparisons to sprinting legends, with Usain Bolt himself remarking, “He looks like a young me.” Born in Ipswich, Queensland, to South Sudanese parents, Gout has been making waves since breaking a 56-year-old national record at the Australian All Schools Championships last year. ​\nThe Guardian\n+4\nLatest news & breaking headlines\n+4\ncouriermail\n+4\n\nDespite the wind-aided times not being eligible for official records, Gout remains undeterred. “Top speed is my gift,” he said. “I run fast times but the wind is not on my side. I guess it\'s just getting those nice runs, and then hopefully one day the wind will be great.” ​\nnews\n+5\nLatest news & breaking headlines\n+5\nThe Australian\n+5\n\nIn a heartwarming display of sportsmanship, Gout\'s friend and rival Lachie Kennedy, who was disqualified for a false start, ran the length of the track to congratulate him after the race. Gout\'s coach, Di Sheppard, who also mentored Olympian Joseph Deng, noted the young athlete\'s potential and resilience. ​\nFOX SPORTS\n+4\ntalkSPORT\n+4\nThe Guardian\n+4\nFOX SPORTS\n+3\nLatest news & breaking headlines\n+3\nThe Guardian\n+3\n\nAs Gout continues to chase wind-legal times, the athletics community watches with anticipation, recognizing his remarkable talent and the promise of a bright future on the international stage.​\nLatest news & breaking headlines\n+1\nThe Australian', 0, 'factabot', 'teen-sprinter-gout-gout-breaks-20-second-barrier-in-200m', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-14 00:00:00', '2025-05-03 15:22:53', 22);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (354, 'Cyclone Errol: Western Australia Braces for Nature’s Spinning Tantrum', 'Mother Nature\'s latest mixtape: wind, rain, and flying trampolines—coming soon to a backyard near you.', 'WA residents, meet Errol. No, not your dodgy uncle who drinks too much at Christmas—this one’s a tropical cyclone with a flair for drama and a predicted glow-up from breezy Category 1 to full-blown Category 3 diva by Wednesday. Currently swirling northwest of Kalumburu, Errol is building up steam like a weather system with something to prove. Locals in the Kimberley region have been told to batten down the hatches, prep emergency kits, and keep their livestock—and lawn chairs—on a tight leash. +News.com.au\n\nIf you’re in the “warning zone” from Kalumburu to Kuri Bay, congratulations—you’ve just won a front-row seat to the Bureau of Meteorology’s most unpredictable show. Forecasts suggest heavy rainfall, wild winds, and waves big enough to scare off a Bunnings sausage sizzle. And while the current forecast keeps Errol offshore, we all know weather systems love a last-minute twist, so don’t cancel your panic just yet. +News.com.au\n\nContext time: this cyclone comes hot on the heels of Cyclone Alfred, which left parts of Queensland and NSW looking like someone lost a bet with Poseidon. With climate change giving the BOM’s storm map a facelift every other month, these once-in-a-decade cyclones are now booking annual appointments. Residents are advised to get their prep kits in order—think canned beans, torches, radios, and enough batteries to power a small nightclub. +DFES\n\nToday’s update? Authorities are on “watch but don’t panic” mode, which in Aussie terms means it’s time to start pretending you know where your torch is. If Errol takes a cheeky veer eastward later in the week, Pilbara could also get caught in the spin cycle. Until then, stay dry, stay inside, and maybe cancel that beach picnic. +News.com.au', 0, 'factabot', 'cyclone-errol-western-australia-braces-for-natures-spinning-tantrum', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-14 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 03:24:03', 27);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (355, 'NSW’s Only Women-Only Trauma Clinic Drops the “Trauma” Part', 'Because nothing says \'progress\' like removing safe spaces for trauma survivors—brilliant.', 'In a plot twist no one asked for, Ramsay Clinic Thirroul—the crown jewel of women-only trauma care in NSW—has quietly rebranded itself from a sanctuary for survivors of domestic and sexual violence to a general women’s psychiatric unit. The clinic, once hailed as a “gamechanger” for its trauma-specific programs, now offers a broader range of mental health services, leaving many to wonder: what happened to the trauma-informed care? ​\nRANZCP\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+2\nRamsay Mental Health\n+2\n\nThe shift follows the mass resignation of the clinic’s founding psychiatrists and program designers, who reportedly left due to systemic issues plaguing NSW’s public mental health sector. With a third of permanent psychiatrist positions vacant statewide, the government has leaned on private facilities like Ramsay to fill the gap, leading to a dilution of specialized services. ​\nThe Guardian\n\nPatients like Olivia, who sought refuge at Thirroul for PTSD treatment, now find themselves sharing space with individuals detoxing from substance use—a situation that can be triggering for trauma survivors. Olivia recounted feeling unsafe and re-traumatized during her second stay, stating, “I was heading out the driveway walking towards the street and towards the train station,” after a distressing encounter with another patient. ​\nIllawarra Mercury\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+2\nRamsay Mental Health\n+2\n\nMental health advocates, including NSW Greens’ Dr. Amanda Cohn, have criticized the clinic’s transformation, emphasizing the urgent need for dedicated trauma services. Dr. Cohn highlighted that the loss of such specialized care leaves a critical gap for survivors of family violence and sexual assault, stating, “It is reliability, predictability and a long-term relationship so that people do not have fragmented care.” ​\nThe Guardian\n\nRamsay Health Care maintains that the clinic continues to provide trauma-informed care within its broader mental health services. However, critics argue that without dedicated programs and trained specialists, the essence of trauma-specific treatment is lost. As NSW grapples with a mental health workforce crisis, the future of specialized care for trauma survivors remains uncertain.', 0, 'factabot', 'nsws-only-women-only-trauma-clinic-drops-the-trauma-part', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-14 00:00:00', '2025-05-01 23:35:04', 25);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (356, 'ASX Volatility Continues Amid Trump\'s Tariff Policies', 'The stock market\'s new rollercoaster: brought to you by tariffs, tweets, and tantrums.', 'In the latest episode of “The Art of the Tariff,” President Donald Trump’s economic policies have turned global markets into a high-stakes game of Jenga. The Australian Securities Exchange (ASX) has been on a wild ride, with the S&P/ASX 200 index experiencing significant fluctuations. A temporary 90-day pause on most tariffs, excluding China, provided a brief respite, leading to a 0.7% gain on April 14. However, the index remains down 5.62% year-to-date, reflecting ongoing investor anxiety \nDiscovery Alert\n.​\n\nThe initial shock came when Trump unveiled his “Liberation Day” tariffs on April 2, imposing a 10% universal tariff and a staggering 145% on Chinese imports. China retaliated with 125% tariffs on U.S. goods, igniting fears of a global recession. The ASX responded by shedding approximately $71 billion in value, with consumer confidence hitting a six-month low \nnews\n.​\n\nIn a move that left economists scratching their heads, Trump took to social media to declare, “THIS IS A GREAT TIME TO BUY!!!” Shortly after, he announced the tariff pause, leading to a $6.5 trillion rally in U.S. markets. While some hailed it as a masterstroke, others raised concerns about potential market manipulation .​\nSmall Caps\n\nBack in Australia, Prime Minister Anthony Albanese criticized the tariffs as “unwarranted,” especially given that Australia imposes no tariffs on U.S. goods. Treasurer Jim Chalmers entered crisis talks to address the $112 billion loss experienced by the ASX, emphasizing Australia\'s strong economic fundamentals but expressing concern over the impact on Australians\' superannuation funds .​\nnews\ndailytelegraph\n+1\nnews\n+1\n\nAs the trade saga continues, analysts warn that the ASX\'s recovery hinges on broader trade de-escalation and Chinese economic stimulus. For now, investors are advised to brace for continued volatility and keep a close eye on international developments \nDiscovery Alert\n.​', 0, 'factabot', 'asx-volatility-continues-amid-trumps-tariff-policies', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-14 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 11:32:40', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (357, 'Australian Survivor Season 12 Finale Airs Tonight', 'Watch as contestants outwit, outplay, and outdrama each other for the ultimate prize—15 minutes of fame.', 'Tonight, the twelfth season of Australian Survivor: Brains V Brawn II reaches its climax, airing at 7:30 PM on Channel 10 and streaming on 10Play. After weeks of intense challenges and strategic gameplay, the final three contestants—Myles Kuah, Kaelan Lockhart, and AJ Antonios—will vie for the title of Sole Survivor and the $500,000 prize. ​\nTheTVDB\n+2\nWikipedia\n+2\nPEDESTRIAN.TV\n+2\nPEDESTRIAN.TV\n+1\nEpisoDate.com\n+1\n\nThe season, which premiered on February 17, 2025, has taken viewers through a series of twists and turns, culminating in a finale that promises to be both thrilling and unpredictable. The final episode, marking the 24th of the season, is set to deliver the ultimate test of endurance, wit, and resilience. ​\nWikipedia\nTheTVDB\n\nFor fans eager to witness the conclusion of this epic journey, make sure to tune in tonight. Whether you\'re Team Myles, rooting for Kaelan, or backing AJ, this finale is set to be a memorable showdown.​\nPEDESTRIAN.TV', 0, 'factabot', 'australian-survivor-season-12-finale-airs-tonight', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-14 00:00:00', '2025-05-02 14:47:45', 31);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (358, 'Two Dead, One Critical in Queensland Drowning Tragedy', 'A day at the beach turns fatal—because even paradise has its perils.', 'In a harrowing incident at Round Hill Head near the coastal town of Seventeen Seventy, Queensland, a 46-year-old man and a 17-year-old boy lost their lives after being swept out to sea on Sunday afternoon. A third individual, a 37-year-old man, sustained critical head injuries and was airlifted to Bundaberg Hospital. The trio, reportedly visiting the area with family while on holiday, encountered treacherous conditions around 2 p.m., prompting a swift response from emergency services, including the Rescue 300 helicopter and CapRescue teams. ​\nYahoo News Australia\n+5\nnews\n+5\ncouriermail\n+5\ncouriermail\n+1\nnews\n+1\n\nWitnesses described a chaotic scene as multiple emergency vehicles arrived, and helicopters hovered overhead during the rescue operation. Despite the efforts of first responders, the man and teenager were pronounced dead at the scene. The 37-year-old man\'s condition remains critical, and he is receiving intensive care. ​\n\nAuthorities have initiated an investigation into the circumstances surrounding the tragedy, with a report to be prepared for the coroner. This incident underscores the unpredictable nature of coastal waters and serves as a somber reminder of the importance of vigilance and safety measures while swimming, especially in unfamiliar locations.​\nPeople.com\n+2\nnews\n+2\ncouriermail\n+2\n\nOur thoughts are with the families and loved ones affected by this devastating event.', 0, 'factabot', 'two-dead-one-critical-in-queensland-drowning-tragedy', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-14 00:00:00', '2025-05-02 00:36:10', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (359, 'Man and Teen Charged After 9-Year-Old\'s Accidental Shooting', 'When \'playing cops and robbers\' goes tragically real—gun safety, anyone?', 'A devastating incident unfolded in the rural town of Windellama, New South Wales, where a 9-year-old boy tragically lost his life due to an accidental shooting. Emergency services were called to a property near Goulburn around 11:20 a.m. on Sunday. Despite the efforts of NSW Ambulance paramedics, the boy succumbed to critical neck injuries at the scene. ​\nYouTube\n+6\nThe Guardian\n+6\nnews\n+6\nThe Guardian\n+2\nnews\n+2\nnews\n+2\n\nFollowing the incident, authorities arrested a 14-year-old boy and a 33-year-old man. The teenager has been charged with possessing an unauthorised firearm and was granted conditional bail, with a court appearance scheduled for May 16. The adult male faces charges of allowing an unauthorised person to possess a firearm and failing to store the firearm safely; he is due to appear in Goulburn Local Court on May 14. ​\n9News\n+5\nSBS Australia\n+5\nThe Guardian\n+5\ndailytelegraph\n+4\nnews\n+4\nnews\n+4\n9News\n+5\nThe Guardian\n+5\nnews\n+5\n\nThe community of Windellama, home to approximately 400 residents, is reeling from the tragedy. Local MP Wendy Tuckerman expressed her condolences, stating, \"This is an absolute terrible tragedy and my heartfelt condolences go to the family involved.\" ​\n9News\n+5\nnews\n+5\nnews\n+5\n\nPolice have established Strike Force Dalzeill to investigate the circumstances surrounding the shooting. Preliminary reports suggest the firearm may have discharged accidentally while being handled by a relative. ​\nThe Guardian\n+3\ndailytelegraph\n+3\nnews\n+3\n\nThis incident underscores the critical importance of firearm safety and secure storage, particularly in households with children. Authorities continue to urge gun owners to adhere strictly to safety regulations to prevent such heartbreaking accidents.', 0, 'factabot', 'man-and-teen-charged-after-9-year-olds-accidental-shooting', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-14 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 00:03:05', 6);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (360, 'SMH Editor Takes Holiday Amid Election Frenzy', 'SMH’s Bevan Shields takes off mid-election campaign. Timing is everything—and this timing is something.', 'In a surprising move, Sydney Morning Herald (SMH) editor Bevan Shields has taken a nearly two-week overseas holiday during the critical final weeks of Australia\'s 2025 federal election campaign. This decision has left many in the newsroom stunned, especially considering Shields\' previous criticism of former Prime Minister Scott Morrison for taking a holiday during a national crisis. \nThe Australian\n​\n\nThe timing of Shields\' vacation has raised eyebrows, given the high-stakes nature of election coverage. An editor\'s role is pivotal during such periods, overseeing comprehensive reporting and analysis. Some staff members have expressed disappointment, noting the importance of leadership during this time. \nThe Australian\n​\n\nAdding to the controversy, Shields had previously penned an editorial criticizing Morrison\'s decision to holiday in Hawaii during the 2019 bushfires, stating it \"forever damaged his image as an astute politician.\" This has led to accusations of hypocrisy, as Shields now finds himself in a similar situation. ​\nThe Australian\n\nWhile Shields is expected to return to the newsroom shortly before polling day on May 3, the incident has sparked discussions about leadership responsibilities and the optics of taking leave during pivotal national events.​\nThe Australian', 0, 'factabot', 'smh-editor-takes-holiday-amid-election-frenzy', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-14 00:00:00', '2025-04-14 22:14:28', 3);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (361, 'Greens Want to Abolish Uni Fees: Because Who Needs Student Debt?', 'The Greens want free uni and TAFE, funded by corporate taxes. Because obviously billionaires love picking up Australia\'s education tab.', 'In a bold move that’s turning heads and emptying spreadsheets, the Australian Greens have unveiled a plan to make university and TAFE free for all students, while also wiping out existing student debt. The proposal, estimated to cost $46.5 billion over four years, aims to relieve the financial burden on students and graduates, with funding sourced from increased taxes on large corporations. ​\nAustralian Financial Review\n+5\necho.net.au\n+5\nSBS Australia\n+5\necho.net.au\n+2\nYouTube\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+2\n\nGreens leader Adam Bandt and higher education spokesperson Senator Mehreen Faruqi announced the initiative in Prime Minister Anthony Albanese’s electorate of Grayndler. They highlighted the irony that many current politicians, including Albanese, benefited from free tertiary education, while today\'s students face mounting debts. Under the plan, the federal government would cover all fees for undergraduate and postgraduate students at public universities and TAFEs. ​\nSBS Australia\n+4\necho.net.au\n+4\nThe Guardian\n+4\nThe Guardian\n+1\necho.net.au\n+1\n\nThe Greens argue that the current system disproportionately affects young Australians, with student debt levels reaching $81 billion and average debts exceeding $27,000. They contend that this financial strain hinders graduates\' ability to afford basic necessities and enter the housing market. \nThe Australian Greens\n​\n\nWhile the proposal has garnered support from student unions and advocacy groups, critics question its feasibility and potential economic impact. Nonetheless, the Greens maintain that investing in education is essential for social equity and economic growth.​', 0, 'factabot', 'greens-want-to-abolish-uni-fees-because-who-needs-student-debt', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-14 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 08:50:00', 21);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (362, 'Albanese and Dutton Compete in the Great Tax Cut Showdown', 'Albo wants $1k deductions, Dutton dangles $1.2k cuts. It\'s a fiscal food fight and everyone’s invited.', 'In the latest episode of \"Who Wants to Be Prime Minister?\", Anthony Albanese and Peter Dutton have unveiled competing tax cut proposals, each aiming to win over voters ahead of the upcoming federal election. Albanese introduced a $1,000 \"instant tax deduction\" for work-related expenses, requiring no receipts, while Dutton countered with a one-off $1,200 tax offset for low- to middle-income earners. Both leaders are also offering housing incentives, with Albanese proposing a $10 billion fund to build 100,000 homes for first-time buyers, and Dutton allowing first-home buyers to deduct mortgage interest payments for up to five years on loans up to $650,000. ​\nThe Guardian\n+3\nnews\n+3\nnews\n+3\nYouTube\n+7\nThe Guardian\n+7\ndailytelegraph\n+7\n\nCritics have labeled these proposals as \"sugar hits,\" suggesting they offer short-term relief without addressing underlying economic issues. Economists warn that such demand-side policies could exacerbate housing affordability by driving up prices without increasing supply, and may also fuel inflation. ​\nThe Guardian\ndailytelegraph\n\nDespite the flashy promises, both parties face scrutiny over the feasibility and long-term impact of their plans. As the election approaches, voters are left to decide which leader\'s vision aligns more closely with their own financial realities.​\nSBS Australia', 0, 'factabot', 'albanese-and-dutton-compete-in-the-great-tax-cut-showdown', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-14 00:00:00', '2025-05-01 22:33:08', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (363, 'Piastri Zooms to Victory in Bahrain: Australia\'s New F1 Star', 'Oscar Piastri takes the Bahrain GP crown, officially unseating Ricciardo as Australia\'s new racing crush.', 'Oscar Piastri delivered a masterclass at the 2025 Bahrain Grand Prix, leading from pole to flag to secure his second win of the season and the fourth of his Formula One career. The 23-year-old Australian showcased composure and precision, finishing 15.5 seconds ahead of Mercedes\' George Russell. Piastri\'s victory also marked McLaren\'s first triumph at the Sakhir circuit. ​\nESPN.com\n+1\nThe Guardian\n+1\nSky Sports\n+3\nThe Guardian\n+3\nFormula 1® - The Official F1® Website\n+3\n\nThe race was not without its challenges. A safety car was deployed on lap 32 following a collision between Carlos Sainz and Yuki Tsunoda, which temporarily erased Piastri\'s lead. However, he managed to rebuild his advantage after the restart. Meanwhile, Russell battled technical issues, including DRS failure and brake problems, but held off a charging Lando Norris to secure second place. ​\nSky Sports\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+2\nThe Sun\n+2\nThe US Sun\n+1\nLatest news & breaking headlines\n+1\n\nNorris, despite a five-second penalty for a false start and a sixth-place qualifying position, fought back to claim the final podium spot. He admitted to making several mistakes during the race and expressed a lack of connection with his car this season. \"I made too many mistakes,\" Norris said. \"I\'m not clicking with the car as I did in previous years.\" ​\nDiario AS\n+3\nThe Guardian\n+3\nThe US Sun\n+3\nReuters\n\nThe victory narrows Norris\'s lead in the drivers\' standings to just three points over Piastri, setting the stage for an intense intra-team rivalry. Max Verstappen, plagued by braking and pit stop issues, finished sixth, while Ferrari\'s Charles Leclerc and Lewis Hamilton completed the top five. ​\nReuters\nThe US Sun\n+2\nLatest news & breaking headlines\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+2\n\nPiastri\'s dominant performance in Bahrain underscores his rapid ascent in Formula One and positions him as a formidable contender for the championship. With McLaren\'s strong form, the season promises an exciting battle at the front of the grid.', 0, 'factabot', 'piastri-zooms-to-victory-in-bahrain-australias-new-f1-star', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-14 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 03:20:21', 21);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (364, 'MAGA Hats Make an Appearance Down Under', 'LNP’s Jeremy Neal hands out Trump-style MAGA hats. Because nothing screams Aussie pride like imported chaos.', 'In a surprising twist to Australia\'s 2025 federal election campaign, the iconic red \"Make America Great Again\" (MAGA) hats have made their way into the political landscape, stirring both intrigue and controversy. Senator Jacinta Nampijinpa Price was recently photographed wearing a gold and white MAGA cap at a Christmas event, just a day after she echoed the Trump slogan at a campaign rally, stating the Coalition would \"make Australia great again.\" While Coalition leaders, including Nationals\' David Littleproud and Liberal spokesperson James Paterson, have downplayed her remarks as an inadvertent slip, the imagery suggests a more deliberate alignment with Trump-era politics. ​\nnews\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+2\ndailytelegraph\n+2\n\nThe presence of MAGA hats isn\'t limited to political figures. In Melbourne, a man named Angelo Notta was asked to remove his MAGA cap at Captain Baxter Bar and Restaurant on Australia Day, with staff citing concerns about inciting political violence. Notta, a regular patron, expressed feeling embarrassed and offended by the request, noting he had worn the hat at the venue on previous occasions without issue. ​\nLog in or sign up to view\n+2\nnews\n+2\nheraldsun\n+2\n\nSimilarly, in Brisbane, Rob Holt was asked to leave The Wickham, an LGBTQIA+ bar, during a Halloween event for wearing a \"Trump 2024\" hat. Staff members expressed that the hat made others feel unsafe, leading to Holt\'s removal from the venue. Holt voiced concerns over a perceived trend of being refused service based on beliefs, emphasizing the importance of free speech in a democratic society. ​\nNew York Post\n+1\nnews\n+1\n\nThese incidents highlight the complex interplay between political expression and social norms in Australia. As the federal election approaches, the appearance of MAGA hats serves as a symbol of the broader cultural and political debates shaping the nation\'s discourse.', 0, 'factabot', 'maga-hats-make-an-appearance-down-under', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-14 00:00:00', '2025-05-03 09:30:24', 27);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (365, 'Australia\'s March Heatwave: Breaking Records and Sweating Bullets', 'March was Australia’s hottest on record, averaging 2.4°C above normal. Climate change just turned the thermostat to ‘hellfire.’', 'Australia has just endured its hottest March on record, with national temperatures soaring 2.41°C above the long-term average. This surpasses the previous record set in 2019 by 0.4°C, marking a significant milestone in the country\'s climate history. ​\nThe Daily Aus\n+4\nWeatherzone\n+4\nThe Guardian\n+4\ndailytelegraph\n\nThe heatwave was widespread, affecting multiple states. New South Wales, South Australia, and Western Australia all recorded their hottest March on record. In Sydney, overnight temperatures reached 25.9°C, the highest March minimum in 149 years. ​\nWeatherzone\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+2\nWikipedia – Die freie Enzyklopädie\n+2\nABC\n+1\ndailytelegraph\n+1\n\nWhile temperatures soared, rainfall patterns were erratic. Queensland experienced its third-wettest March since 1900, with some areas receiving up to four times their average rainfall. Conversely, parts of South Australia and Western Australia faced severe drought conditions, highlighting the extremes of Australia\'s climate. ​\nThe Daily Aus\n+4\ndailytelegraph\n+4\nThe Guardian\n+4\nnews\n\nThese unprecedented conditions are part of a global trend of increasing temperatures due to elevated greenhouse gas emissions. The Bureau of Meteorology attributes the record-breaking heat to persistent high-pressure systems and a global pattern of warming temperatures. ​\nThe Guardian\n\nLooking ahead, the Bureau forecasts that Australia is likely to experience one of its warmest winters on record from May to July 2025. Daytime and nighttime temperatures are expected to remain above average across most of the country, raising concerns about prolonged heat-related impacts.', 0, 'factabot', 'australias-march-heatwave-breaking-records-and-sweating-bullets', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-14 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 01:06:59', 34);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (366, 'Australian Academics Avoid US Conferences Over Detention Fears', 'When your research trip includes a free cavity search, maybe it\'s time to Zoom in instead.', 'Australian academics are increasingly declining invitations to attend conferences in the United States due to fears of being detained or denied entry at the border. Since Donald Trump\'s return to office, reports of unpredictable border control policies, especially affecting disabled, LGBTQ+, and minority academics, have led to heightened concern. Gemma Lucy Smart, a disabled and queer PhD student, opted to attend a Seattle conference remotely, citing safety risks. The Society for Social Studies of Science shifted its conference format to hybrid in response to growing uncertainty over U.S. travel conditions. Additionally, changes in U.S. policies have resulted in rescinded scholarships, terminated research collaborations, and denied grant funding. The Australian National Tertiary Education Union acknowledged multiple reports of career disruptions, particularly among LGBTQ+ researchers. Concerns include the inspection of electronic devices at the border and the scrutiny of travelers\' medications and identities. These developments are seen as a threat to global academic collaboration, particularly in fields that rely heavily on interaction with U.S. institutions. As a result, academics are avoiding U.S. travel to protect their personal safety and professional integrity.', 0, 'factabot', 'Australian_Academics_Avoid_US_Conferences_Over_Detention_Fears', 'draft', 'images/news/udq0VNTLOyLUSfzkWeRnMjcxNHH3orPbsq6B2xJO.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-14 04:15:31', '2025-04-24 20:03:35', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (367, 'Finance Minister Accuses Coalition of Importing \'Doge\' Agenda', 'Katy Gallagher slams the Coalition\'s plan to slash 41,000 public service jobs, likening it to a Trump-Musk \'Doge\' strategy. Because nothing says efficiency like chaos.', 'When Finance Minister Katy Gallagher stepped up to the mic yesterday, she didn’t just throw shade—she launched a full meme assault, accusing the Coalition of pushing a “Doge-style” economic agenda. Yep, the woman overseeing Australia\'s actual budget just compared Peter Dutton’s economic plans to a Shiba Inu meme from 2013. Gallagher, known for her deadpan delivery and eyebrow-raising comebacks in Senate estimates, didn’t mince words. “So much spending. Very reckless. Much inflation,” she mocked, riffing off the infamous Doge syntax. And honestly? It kind of slapped. +ABC News\n\nThe tea? This dig came after the Coalition dropped its shiny new “economic plan,” a document Gallagher claimed reads like someone printed Reddit threads and called it policy. The Liberals have promised big-ticket tax cuts, eye-watering infrastructure projects, and mortgage relief, all while insisting the budget won’t implode. Gallagher, who’s been trying to convince the public that Labor is the “adult in the room,” isn’t buying it. She’s especially salty about the $12 billion mortgage interest relief scheme Dutton’s floating, calling it “fiscal cosplay.” +Guardian Australia\n\nNow, let’s zoom out. The Coalition’s plan is textbook populist bait: offer relief without mentioning the bill. Meanwhile, Labor’s caught between being cautious and not looking like the fun police. The irony? Both parties are chucking around billions while blaming each other for inflation, debt, and economic instability. Oh, and the media? Mostly too obsessed with whether someone smirked in Question Time to notice the numbers don’t add up on either side. +The Australian\n\nAs of today, Dutton doubled down, saying Gallagher “clearly doesn’t understand the struggles of ordinary Australians,” while refusing to answer how his plans will be funded. Gallagher, meanwhile, continued to drag the Coalition like a seasoned Twitter troll, noting, “If you’re going to run the economy like a meme, expect meme-level consequences.” +9News', 0, 'factabot', 'finance-minister-accuses-coalition-of-importing-doge-agenda', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-05-02 02:45:19', 42);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (368, 'EU Leaders Condemn Russia Following Palm Sunday Attack', 'EU leaders express outrage over Russia\'s latest aggression. Putin\'s Easter gift: more international condemnation.', 'In a move that surprised absolutely no one, European Union leaders have unleashed a torrent of condemnation at Russia following its missile strike on the Ukrainian city of Sumy during Palm Sunday celebrations. The attack, which resulted in the deaths of at least 34 civilians, including two children, and injured over 100 others, has been labeled as \"barbaric\" and a blatant violation of international law. ​\nReuters\n+6\nThe Sun\n+6\nAP News\n+6\nAP News\n+3\nThe Kyiv Independent\n+3\nAP News\n+3\n\nEuropean Commission President Ursula von der Leyen didn\'t mince words, stating, \"Russian cruelty struck again,\" and reminding everyone that \"Russia was and remains the aggressor.\" Meanwhile, French President Emmanuel Macron called for \"strong measures to impose a ceasefire on Russia,\" emphasizing that \"everyone knows: This war was initiated by Russia alone.\" ​\neuronews\n+1\nWikipedia\n+1\nThe Guardian\n+3\nThe Kyiv Independent\n+3\neuronews\n+3\n\nBritish Prime Minister Keir Starmer expressed his horror at the attack, urging Russian President Vladimir Putin to agree to a \"full and immediate ceasefire without conditions.\" Not to be outdone, Polish Foreign Minister Radoslaw Sikorski pointed out that Ukraine had unconditionally agreed to a ceasefire over a month ago, only to be met with Russia\'s \"mocking answer\" in the form of missile strikes. ​\nThe Sun\n+3\nWikipedia\n+3\nThe Kyiv Independent\n+3\nAl Jazeera\n+2\nSBS Australia\n+2\nTheJournal.ie\n+2\n\nUkrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy, clearly exasperated, called for a \"strong response\" from Europe, highlighting that the missiles struck \"an ordinary city street\" filled with civilians attending Palm Sunday services. ​\nTheJournal.ie\n\nIn the midst of this diplomatic pile-on, U.S. President Donald Trump labeled the attack as \"a horrible thing\" and ambiguously referred to it as a \"mistake,\" without clarifying whether he believed it was intentional or not. ​\nThe Guardian\n\nAs the international community scrambles to respond, the EU is reportedly considering additional sanctions against Russia, though internal disagreements persist. Meanwhile, Russia continues to defend its actions, claiming the strike targeted a gathering of Ukrainian military officers—a claim met with widespread skepticism. ​\nAP News\n+1\nThe Sun\n+1\n\nIn the grand theater of geopolitics, it seems the script remains unchanged: Russia acts, the world condemns, and the cycle continues.', 0, 'factabot', 'eu-leaders-condemn-russia-following-palm-sunday-attack', 'draft', 'images/news/184be0c3-7440-487d-af5b-065b58dfee15.png', NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 19:00:05', 21);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (369, 'Rory McIlroy Completes Career Grand Slam at The Masters', 'McIlroy finally dons the green jacket, proving that patience (and a killer swing) pays off.', 'It finally happened. Rory “Almost There” McIlroy has actually won The Masters, completing the career Grand Slam after 17 years of Augusta foreplay. Yes, the man who’s been ghosting the green jacket since 2007 finally sealed the deal in 2025, joining the ultra-exclusive club of “Golf Guys Who’ve Won Everything”—alongside legends like Tiger Woods and Jack Nicklaus, and presumably a few golf-course ghosts. +Wikipedia\n\nMcIlroy’s win wasn’t exactly textbook. The man racked up four double bogeys—setting a Masters record for “most disasters survived en route to victory.” But like any good protagonist in a sports movie, he ignored the bad script and pulled off a sudden-death playoff win over Justin Rose, who now knows what it feels like to be the bridesmaid, again. Rory, meanwhile, cried, hugged his wife Erica, and daughter Poppy like he’d just broken a decade-long curse… which, to be fair, he had. His last major win was in 2014, when TikTok wasn’t even a thing. +PGA Tour\n\nZoom out, and this is a redemption arc dripping in irony. For years, McIlroy was the guy destined to dominate, until nerves, Nike deals, and swing coach roulette got in the way. Every April, the media would breathlessly ask “Is this Rory’s year?” and then pretend not to look disappointed when he faceplanted on the back nine. But now? Rory’s wearing the jacket, cashing a record-breaking $4.2 million cheque, and proving that if you stall long enough, the plot twist will eventually land. +TalkSport\n\nAs for the update: McIlroy is basking in green glory while Rose nurses his trauma with polite British resentment. Rory’s caddie Harry Diamond pocketed $420k, which is great because someone needs to carry all that ego. Augusta’s curse is broken. Somewhere, Greg Norman is quietly seething. +NYPost', 0, 'factabot', 'rory-mcilroy-completes-career-grand-slam-at-the-masters', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 06:58:57', 19);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (370, 'Victorian Liberal Leader Distances Party from Federal Nuclear Proposal', 'Brad Battin says \'no thanks\' to Dutton\'s nuclear dreams, preferring gas over glowing reactors.', '​In a move that\'s less \"team player\" and more \"I\'m not with him,\" Victorian Liberal leader Brad Battin has artfully sidestepped federal counterpart Peter Dutton\'s grand nuclear ambitions. While Dutton dreams of dotting the Australian landscape with shiny new nuclear reactors, including one at Victoria\'s own Loy Yang power station, Battin is humming a different tune—one that sounds suspiciously like \"Gas, Gas, Baby.\" ​\nThe Guardian\n+5\nThe Guardian\n+5\nnews\n+5\nABC\n+3\nYahoo News Australia\n+3\nThe Guardian\n+3\n\nBattin, who ascended to the Victorian Liberal throne in December 2024 after a Game of Thrones-esque party shuffle, has been busy crafting his \"just a regular bloke\" image. From pub chats to policy talks, he\'s all about connecting with the everyday voter. But when it comes to Dutton\'s nuclear proposal, Battin\'s stance is clear: \"Our focus is gas.\" Translation? \"Nuclear? Not in my backyard, mate.\" ​\nThe Guardian\n\nThe backdrop to this political tango is Dutton\'s bold plan to erect seven nuclear reactors nationwide, with the Loy Yang site in Victoria\'s Latrobe Valley earmarked as a prime spot. However, this vision clashes head-on with Victoria\'s longstanding ban on nuclear activities, enshrined in the Nuclear Activities (Prohibitions) Act of 1983. Overturning this would be akin to convincing a vegan to run a butcher shop. ​\nABC\n+7\nSBS Australia\n+7\nYahoo News Australia\n+7\nThe Guardian\n\nBattin\'s gas-centric focus isn\'t just a random choice. With local gas fields on the decline and energy prices doing their best impression of a rollercoaster, he sees onshore gas exploration as the quick fix to keep Victorians\' lights on and wallets intact. Meanwhile, Dutton\'s nuclear daydreams are viewed by some as the political equivalent of building castles in the air—grand, but lacking a solid foundation. ​\ninkl\n+6\nThe Guardian\n+6\nThe Guardian\n+6\n\nAs of now, the Victorian Liberals are sticking to their gas guns, leaving Dutton to champion his nuclear crusade solo. Battin\'s message to Dutton? \"Good luck with that, but we\'re good over here with our gas plans.\" It\'s a classic case of political \"agree to disagree,\" with a side of \"please don\'t drag us into this.\" ​\nRenewEconomy\ninkl\n+6\nThe Guardian\n+6\nnews\n+6', 0, 'factabot', 'victorian-liberal-leader-distances-party-from-federal-nuclear-proposal', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 08:33:14', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (371, 'Urgent Warning to Parents Over Button Battery Dangers This Easter', 'Tiny batteries pose big risks. Parents advised to keep them away from curious little mouths.', 'Urgent Warning to Parents Over Button Battery Dangers This Easter', 0, 'factabot', 'urgent-warning-to-parents-over-button-battery-dangers-this-easter', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 16:23:51', 20);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (372, 'Wall Street Rallies as Tariff Exemptions Boost Tech Stocks; ASX Set to Follow', 'Tech stocks soar after tariff reprieve. Investors breathe a sigh of relief—for now.', '​In the latest episode of \"As the Tariff Turns,\" President Donald Trump has once again wielded his tariff wand, this time granting a temporary reprieve to tech gadgets like smartphones and laptops. This move sent Wall Street into a tizzy, with the S&P 500 climbing 0.8%, the Dow Jones adding 312 points, and the Nasdaq Composite rising 0.6%. ​\nAP News\nnews\n+6\nAP News\n+6\nAP News\n+6\n\nTech giants, always the drama queens of the stock market, basked in the spotlight. Apple\'s shares rose by 2.2%, and Dell Technologies strutted with a 4% gain. Automakers joined the party after Trump hinted at potential tariff pauses for their industry, boosting General Motors by 3.5% and Ford Motor by 4.1%. ​\nInvestopedia\n+3\nAP News\n+3\nAP News\n+3\n\nHowever, before you pop the champagne, remember that this tariff exemption is as permanent as a Snapchat story. Commerce Secretary Howard Lutnick reminded everyone that this relief is fleeting, with semiconductor-related tariffs possibly rearing their ugly heads within months. ​\nWSJ\n+4\nInvestopedia\n+4\nInvestor\'s Business Daily\n+4\n\nMeanwhile, down under, the Australian stock market (ASX) is set to ride Wall Street\'s coattails. Futures are pointing to a 0.2% gain for the S&P/ASX 200 index, as tech stocks prepare to bask in the afterglow of the U.S. tariff exemptions. ​\nnews\n+1\nAustralian Financial Review\n+1\nThe Australian\n+1\nThe Australian\n+1\n\nIn summary, while the markets are currently dancing in the streets, it\'s worth remembering that with this administration, the music can stop at any moment. Investors might want to keep their dancing shoes on but stay close to their seats.​', 0, 'factabot', 'wall-street-rallies-as-tariff-exemptions-boost-tech-stocks-asx-set-to-follow', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-04-28 06:08:47', 20);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (373, 'Katy Perry Joins All-Female Crew in Blue Origin Space Launch', 'Pop star reaches new heights—literally—as she blasts off with Bezos\'s latest space venture.', 'In a move that left both fans and critics starry-eyed, pop sensation Katy Perry has officially added \"space traveler\" to her eclectic résumé. On April 14, 2025, Perry joined an all-female crew aboard Blue Origin\'s New Shepard NS-31 mission, marking a historic moment as the first all-women spaceflight since Valentina Tereshkova\'s solo journey in 1963. ​\nElHuffPost\n+10\nWikipedia, la enciclopedia libre\n+10\nWikipedia\n+10\n\nThe 10-minute suborbital flight, which reached the Kármán line—the recognized boundary of space—was a whirlwind of zero-gravity antics and emotional expressions. Perry, ever the performer, serenaded her fellow astronauts with \"What a Wonderful World\" while floating weightlessly, a rendition that, while heartfelt, left some wondering if the cosmos had requested an encore. ​\nnews\n+6\nThe Guardian\n+6\nEW.com\n+6\nElHuffPost\n+2\nnews\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+2\n\nThe crew, handpicked by Lauren Sánchez (fiancée of Amazon founder Jeff Bezos), included journalist Gayle King, former NASA engineer Aisha Bowe, civil rights activist Amanda Nguyen, and film producer Kerianne Flynn. Together, they represented a blend of celebrity, science, and activism, aiming to inspire future generations of women to reach for the stars—literally. ​\nBusiness Insider\n+13\nWikipedia\n+13\nThe Guardian\n+13\n\nHowever, not everyone was on board with the mission\'s messaging. Critics labeled the endeavor as a tone-deaf publicity stunt, pointing out the juxtaposition of a lavish space trip against the backdrop of global challenges. Actress Olivia Munn notably described the flight as \"gluttonous,\" highlighting the disconnect between the elite escapade and everyday struggles faced by many. ​\nIndian Defence Review\n+7\nWikipedia\n+7\nBusiness Insider\n+7\nBusiness Insider\n\nDespite the backlash, Perry remained undeterred. Upon landing, she kissed the Earth—a gesture that, while symbolic, drew mixed reactions online. In post-flight interviews, she emphasized the transformative nature of the journey, stating, \"It\'s an important moment for the future of commercial space travel, for humanity in general, and for women.\" ​\nBusiness Insider\nnews\nWikipedia\n+1\nEW.com\n+1\n\nAs Blue Origin continues to chart its course in the burgeoning space tourism industry, the NS-31 mission stands as a testament to the intersection of celebrity influence and space exploration. Whether viewed as a pioneering leap or a glamorous detour, one thing is certain: Katy Perry\'s brief dance among the stars has added a new dimension to her ever-evolving narrative.​\nWikipedia\n+5\nlivescience.com\n+5\nEW.com\n+5', 0, 'factabot', 'katy-perry-joins-all-female-crew-in-blue-origin-space-launch', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-04-27 12:17:36', 27);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (374, 'Dutton Clarifies Housing Plan: \'Don\'t Want Prices to Go Down\'', 'Opposition leader assures homeowners their property values are safe under his watch.', 'Peter Dutton, in a stunning display of saying the quiet part very loud, has clarified his big, bold housing policy: he doesn’t want house prices to go down. That’s right. In a country where half the population is considering swapping avocado toast for sleeping in their cars, Dutton has confirmed he’s not here to fix the housing crisis—just make it a bit more comfortable for people already in the club. +ABC\n\nHis plan? A thrilling new tax break for first-home buyers, letting them deduct mortgage interest for five years. Sounds nice, until you realise it’s like handing out free petrol during a traffic jam—it doesn’t fix the problem, it just makes everyone slam on the accelerator. Economists, aka the party poopers of election season, have already flagged this as a fast-track to making prices even higher. Because when you throw cash at demand without building more supply, what could possibly go wrong? +News.com.au\n\nDutton insists he’s just trying to “protect the value of people’s homes.” Translation: Sorry renters, we’re keeping the property ladder just out of reach because falling prices might make Karen from Camberwell feel poor. He even dodged questions about whether he’d help his own kids buy a house—possibly because the answer is “yes, with my MP salary and probably a casual apartment in Canberra.” +The Guardian\n\nAs for the latest twist, Dutton’s standing by his not-actually-a-solution solution, despite everyone from housing experts to your cousin with a TikTok account pointing out that it’s wildly counterproductive. Meanwhile, Labor’s building promises and the Greens are dreaming of unicorn housing policies—but Dutton? He’s just here to make sure no boomer’s equity ever sheds a dollar. +SBS', 0, 'factabot', 'dutton-clarifies-housing-plan-dont-want-prices-to-go-down', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-04-23 21:37:18', 5);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (375, 'Aussies Turn to Subletting Homes to Fund Holidays', 'Why save when you can Airbnb your way to a vacation?', 'In a move that screams \"modern problems require modern solutions,\" Australians are increasingly turning to subletting their homes to fund their holiday escapades. According to a recent ING survey, 12% of Aussies plan to sublet their homes during the Easter and Anzac Day holidays, aiming to earn an average of $156.45 per day to offset their travel expenses. ​\nnews\n\nThis trend isn\'t just about making a quick buck; it\'s a strategic maneuver in a housing market that\'s become more competitive than a game of musical chairs. With rental vacancies at record lows and rents soaring, many see subletting as a way to keep up with the Joneses—or at least not fall behind. ​\nCentral News\n\nPlatforms like Airbnb have made this process more accessible, allowing homeowners to list their properties with ease. However, it\'s not without its challenges. Renters must navigate a maze of legalities, including obtaining permission from landlords and adhering to local regulations. ​\nAway Resorts\nCentral News\nThe Guardian\n+1\nABC\n+1\n\nDespite these hurdles, the allure of turning one\'s home into a temporary cash cow is strong. After all, why let your house sit empty while you\'re sipping cocktails on a beach when it could be earning its keep?​\nHaulfryn Holidays\n\nSo, as Australians pack their bags for their next adventure, many are also handing over their house keys—to strangers, friends, or anyone willing to pay—proving that in today\'s economy, every asset counts.', 0, 'factabot', 'aussies-turn-to-subletting-homes-to-fund-holidays', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 14:17:41', 19);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (376, '65-Year-Old Woman Killed in Sydney Drive-By Shooting', 'Tragedy strikes as a woman loses her life in a suburban shooting. Police hunt for suspects.', 'Sydney’s getting its own reboot of Grand Theft Auto: Suburbia, and the latest horror plot twist? A 65-year-old woman was shot and killed in a drive-by outside her home in south-west Sydney. Police say she was not the intended target, which honestly makes it even worse—like a tragic case of being in the wrong postcode at the wrong time, all while the city tries to pretend it’s not spiraling into some B-grade underworld drama. +ABC News\n\nThe woman, who’s being remembered by neighbours as a “gentle soul” who was definitely not involved in any gangland nonsense, was gunned down in the driveway of her own home in Miller. Cops believe the shooters were aiming for someone else, but because Sydney’s gunmen apparently have the accuracy of stormtroopers, an innocent grandmother became collateral in a beef she had nothing to do with. +9News\n\nLet’s zoom out. Sydney’s drive-by drama has escalated to the point where you half expect a Netflix docuseries called Punchbowl: Reloaded. In the past year, there’ve been more bullets flying through suburbia than pigeons on George Street. Yet we still hear the same post-shooting political soundtrack: “Taskforce formed,” “Community shaken,” “Time to get serious about guns.” And then? Nothing changes. Rinse, repeat. +The Guardian\n\nThe latest update: Police are “exploring links” to organised crime and looking at CCTV footage, which is PR-speak for “we’re still figuring out who the hell did this.” Meanwhile, every law-abiding Sydney resident is left wondering if they should wear kevlar to check the mail. If this is “normalised violence,” Australia might need a rebrand. +SMH', 0, 'factabot', '65-year-old-woman-killed-in-sydney-drive-by-shooting', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-04-29 18:04:13', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (377, 'Leaked Video Reveals Liberal MP\'s Critique of Free TAFE Program', 'Sarah Henderson brands Free TAFE as a $1.5 billion flop. Because who needs affordable education when you can have student debt?', 'In a leaked video that’s basically the political version of “Oops, I said the quiet part out loud,” Liberal MP Sarah Henderson has been caught dragging the Albanese government’s Free TAFE program like it just flunked its own trade course. Speaking to what she thought was a friendly crowd (spoiler: someone had their phone out), Henderson slammed the $1.5 billion policy as “not working” and “just a bit of a dud”—which is rich coming from a party that once thought robo-debt was a solid idea. +News.com.au\n\nThis wasn’t a polite disagreement; it was a full-blown roast. Henderson, trying to sound “reasonable,” basically implied the program was a waste of taxpayer cash, a jobs mirage dressed up as social good. Her critique? Low completion rates and poor outcomes. Her subtext? “Skilled trades are fine, just not if Labor’s handing out the spanners.” +Sky News\n\nBut Labor’s not having it. Albanese, clearly sick of the free TAFE slander, clapped back saying the program’s getting Aussies—especially women and regional folk—into real jobs. And honestly, in a country with tradespeople booked out until 2031, maybe giving someone a free go at learning plumbing isn’t the end of civilisation? +The Guardian\n\nThe fallout: Dutton’s mob now hinting they’ll “reform” the whole thing if elected. Translation: TAFE’s going back on the shelf next to Medicare dental and your dreams of affording rent. Meanwhile, voters are wondering why helping people learn a trade is controversial when half the nation can’t get a bloody electrician. +ABC', 0, 'factabot', 'leaked-video-reveals-liberal-mps-critique-of-free-tafe-program', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-05-02 04:36:19', 22);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (378, 'Cyclist Mathieu van der Poel Demands Action After Being Hit by Water Bottle', 'Van der Poel calls for a trial after a fan\'s \'hydration assault\' during Paris-Roubaix. Who knew cycling needed body armor?', 'Cyclist Mathieu van der Poel Demands Action After Being Hit by Water Bottle', 0, 'factabot', 'cyclist-mathieu-van-der-poel-demands-action-after-being-hit-by-water-bottle', 'draft', 'images/news/4c0b5d5e-41ca-46cb-8c02-9bec2e343c47.png', NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-05-03 09:09:24', 19);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (379, 'Climate Change Threatens Insurance Viability in Shepparton', 'Flood risks make Shepparton nearly uninsurable. Climate change: turning homes into liabilities.', 'Welcome to Shepparton, where the tomatoes are ripe, the air is thick, and your house may soon be uninsurable because Mother Nature’s in full “I told you so” mode. According to the latest climate data, up to 88% of homes in Shepparton’s CBD are basically one flood away from becoming “Not Eligible For Insurance – Best of Luck!” properties. If you live in Kialla? Don’t worry, you’re only at 79% apocalypse probability. +ABC\n\nLet’s rewind. Remember the 2022 floods that turned half the town into a backyard swimming pool? Yeah, that wasn’t a freak event—it was the preview trailer. Locals like Vicki and Geoff Woodhouse had to bulldoze their flooded home and move elsewhere, because rebuilding in a high-risk zone is like putting a tent in a hurricane and hoping the weather’s “just vibing.” +ABC\n\nHere’s the tea: the banks don’t want to finance your climate roulette, the insurers are quietly ghosting flood zones, and without serious intervention, we’re staring down the barrel of “climate ghettos.” Yes, that’s a real term now—areas where house prices sink faster than the houses themselves, and residents are stuck holding the soggy bag. +The Guardian\n\nShepparton’s council has rolled out a Climate Adaptation Plan, which sounds great until you realise it’s kind of like putting a Band-Aid on a crumbling dam. Infrastructure upgrades? Needed yesterday. Federal support? Still buffering. Meanwhile, Shepparton’s homeowners are left with two options: buy a kayak or pray for elevation. +Greater Shepparton Council', 0, 'factabot', 'climate-change-threatens-insurance-viability-in-shepparton', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 23:36:29', 25);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (380, 'Youth Homelessness Crisis: One Young Person Dies Every Four Days', 'Rising rents and mental health issues leave young Australians vulnerable. A national disgrace in plain sight.', 'Australia, the land of sun, surf, and apparently a youth homelessness crisis so dire that one young person dies every four days. Yep, we’re talking about kids—literal teenagers—dying on the streets in a country with $14 avocado toast and $2 million starter homes. +ABC News\n\nAccording to the latest gut-punch report, over 39,000 young people aged 15–24 are homeless in Australia, and surprise! Half of them are girls, many fleeing violence or family breakdowns. You know what they’re not fleeing? Choice. Because there is none. Shelters are full, funding is flatlining, and governments are about as responsive as a Telstra help desk on a Sunday. +Mission Australia\n\nAnd just when you thought the spin couldn’t get any shinier, along comes the federal housing strategy with its usual magic trick: say the word “affordable” 47 times and do almost nothing to build any. Meanwhile, support services are duct-taping beds together and rationing food like it’s wartime, because that’s totally fine in a country that just dropped $368 billion on submarines that haven’t even floated yet. +The Guardian\n\nThe real kicker? This isn’t even news anymore. It’s an accepted, scheduled tragedy. Every four days. Like clockwork. Yet we’ll all get another NDIS review or royal commission before someone funds, say, a roof over someone’s actual head. Politicians are too busy arguing about tax cuts for landlords while 17-year-olds are sleeping on train platforms. But sure, tell us again how “we can’t afford to do more.” +SBS', 0, 'factabot', 'youth-homelessness-crisis-one-young-person-dies-every-four-days', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 13:06:21', 20);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (381, 'IFM Investors Withdraws from Government Carbon Offset Scheme', 'Super-backed IFM exits Climate Active, questioning the credibility of carbon offsets. Greenwashing just got a reality check.', 'In a plot twist worthy of a climate thriller, IFM Investors—you know, the $200 billion superannuation-backed fund that owns half of Australia’s toll roads, ports, and probably your retirement—has just rage-quit the federal government’s Climate Active scheme, calling it out for what it arguably is: a glorified sticker system for green vibes with zero bite. +AFR\n\nThe issue? Carbon offsets. IFM basically said, “We’re done pretending tree-planting receipts = climate action,” and questioned whether paying to “cancel out” emissions is anything more than an expensive guilt sponge. They also side-eyed the quality of offsets being handed out like eco-confetti—pointing out they might be as scientifically sound as a Goop candle. +Guardian Australia\n\nClimate Active, for the uninitiated, is Australia’s official badge of “carbon neutral” honour. Businesses slap it on their websites like a green halo after buying enough offsets to balance out their actual pollution. But IFM’s exit suggests they’ve finally read the fine print and realised that just because something looks eco-friendly doesn’t mean it isn’t greenwashing in activewear. +ABC\n\nThe government, naturally, responded with vague murmurs of “we’re reviewing it” while furiously googling “how to save face in 2025.” Meanwhile, climate experts are slow-clapping IFM for breaking ranks, saying it’s about time major players ditched the feel-good fantasy and started focusing on actual emissions cuts, not carbon offset cosplay. +RenewEconomy', 0, 'factabot', 'ifm-investors-withdraws-from-government-carbon-offset-scheme', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 00:06:58', 34);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (382, 'Delta Goodrem Celebrates 20 Years of \'Mistaken Identity\' with Anniversary Concert', 'Delta returns to the stage, reminding us that some albums—and hairstyles—are timeless.', 'Delta Goodrem just pulled the ultimate nostalgic power move: a 20th anniversary concert for her 2004 melodrama masterpiece Mistaken Identity—aka the album where she swapped soap star sweetness for eyeliner, angst, and power chords. Performing the whole album at the Sydney Opera House (twice, because drama deserves an encore), Delta served vocals, vulnerability, and the kind of emotional whiplash only a 2000s diva can deliver. +News.com.au\n\nShe sang all the hits—Out of the Blue, Electric Storm, Almost Here—yes, even The Analyst (you know, the one that made us all feel like tortured poets in Year 10). And because every good anniversary needs a plot twist, she swapped out OG duet partner Brian McFadden for Cody Simpson, proving once and for all that Delta is nothing if not adaptable. +The Australian\n\nThe whole evening was part therapy session, part arena pop sermon, and part “remember when CDs existed?” tribute. There were candles. There were confessions. There were very dramatic key changes. And at the end, she hit us with Believe Again, just in case our tear ducts were still functioning. +SMH\n\nNext stop: London’s Hackney Empire in May, where Brits will learn what true emotional resilience sounds like when belted at full volume by a woman in sequins. Delta’s still got it—and now she’s got two decades of receipts, eyeliner, and ARIA plaques to prove it. +DeltaGoodrem.com', 0, 'factabot', 'delta-goodrem-celebrates-20-years-of-mistaken-identity-with-anniversary-concert', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 09:48:49', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (383, 'First-Time Buyers Compete for Highton\'s Cheapest House in 2025', 'A \'very original\' home sells for $531,000. Because who doesn\'t love a fixer-upper with character (and asbestos)?', 'First-Time Buyers Battle It Out for Highton\'s ‘Cheapest House’—Still Costs a Kidney and a Dream\n\nIn today’s episode of The Great Australian Housing Joke, a modest home in Highton (Geelong’s leafy cousin) has become the arena for first-home buyers desperately trying to get anything with four walls and a roof before developers turn it into a townhouse complex named \"Eucalyptus Grove.\" The house—described lovingly as “liveable” if your standards are subterranean—is the cheapest listing in the suburb for 2025. Translation? It’s probably smaller than your car, and still more expensive than your will to live. +RealEstate.com.au\n\nFirst-home buyers swarmed the place like it was giving out free avocado toast, hoping to beat out investors, boomers with spare SMSFs, and that one guy who only ever shows up at auctions to nod smugly. The house—one bathroom, two-ish bedrooms, and “renovator’s delight” energy—is expected to fetch over $500,000, which sounds cute until you realise that’s what it cost to buy five houses in Highton two decades ago. +Domain\n\nOf course, local agents are spinning it like it’s a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity: “A great entry point into the market!” Which is real estate speak for “It has plumbing. Mostly.” And buyers? They’re bringing spreadsheets, brokers, and probably holy water just in case. One young couple was reportedly heard whispering, “We’ll knock down the back wall and live diagonally.” +9News\n\nMeanwhile, politicians continue to debate housing affordability like it’s some abstract concept and not the thing ruining everyone’s lives in real time. But don’t worry! If you miss out on this one, there’s a lovely one-bedroom ex-garage going in Norlane with “excellent upside potential” and at least one intact window. +ABC News', 0, 'factabot', 'first-time-buyers-compete-for-hightons-cheapest-house-in-2025', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 00:00:00', '2025-05-07 12:39:36', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (384, 'Royal Easter Show Prices Leave Families Shell-Shocked', 'Families spend up to $500 for a day at the show. Nothing says fun like financial ruin.', 'In a move that has left wallets weeping and families gasping, the 2025 Sydney Royal Easter Show has unveiled prices that make a day at the fair feel more like a luxury getaway. Attendees are reporting jaw-dropping costs: $22 for a cup of gnocchi, $9 for a glass of lemonade, and up to $20 for a Bertie Beetle showbag—a stark contrast to its humble $5 origins. One family recounted spending between $390 and $500 in a single day, with food and showbags being the primary culprits. Social media is ablaze with reactions, dubbing the event as \"for the elites\" and expressing disbelief over the inflated prices. ​\nnews\n\nDespite the sticker shock, the show continues to draw massive crowds, proving that nostalgia and tradition still hold sway. Organizers defend the pricing, noting that the costs are comparable to other Sydney food outlets and emphasizing the comprehensive family experience the show offers. The event, celebrating its 202nd year, remains a staple of the Easter holiday, blending agricultural showcases with modern entertainment. ​\nnews\nIn a move that has left wallets weeping and families gasping, the 2025 Sydney Royal Easter Show has unveiled prices that make a day at the fair feel more like a luxury getaway. Attendees are reporting jaw-dropping costs: $22 for a cup of gnocchi, $9 for a glass of lemonade, and up to $20 for a Bertie Beetle showbag—a stark contrast to its humble $5 origins. One family recounted spending between $390 and $500 in a single day, with food and showbags being the primary culprits. Social media is ablaze with reactions, dubbing the event as \"for the elites\" and expressing disbelief over the inflated prices. ​\nnews\n\nDespite the sticker shock, the show continues to draw massive crowds, proving that nostalgia and tradition still hold sway. Organizers defend