INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (385, 'Victorian Liberal Leader Distances Party from Federal Nuclear Proposal', 'Brad Battin says \'no thanks\' to Dutton\'s nuclear dreams, preferring gas over glowing reactors.', 'In a move that\'s less \"team player\" and more \"I\'m not with him,\" Victorian Liberal leader Brad Battin has artfully sidestepped federal counterpart Peter Dutton\'s grand nuclear ambitions. While Dutton dreams of dotting the Australian landscape with shiny new nuclear reactors, including one at Victoria\'s own Loy Yang power station, Battin is humming a different tune—one that sounds suspiciously like \"Gas, Gas, Baby.\" ​\r\nThe Guardian\r\n+5\r\nThe Guardian\r\n+5\r\nnews\r\n+5\r\nABC\r\n+3\r\nYahoo News Australia\r\n+3\r\nThe Guardian\r\n+3\r\n\r\nBattin, who ascended to the Victorian Liberal throne in December 2024 after a Game of Thrones-esque party shuffle, has been busy crafting his \"just a regular bloke\" image. From pub chats to policy talks, he\'s all about connecting with the everyday voter. But when it comes to Dutton\'s nuclear proposal, Battin\'s stance is clear: \"Our focus is gas.\" Translation? \"Nuclear? Not in my backyard, mate.\" ​\r\nThe Guardian\r\n\r\nThe backdrop to this political tango is Dutton\'s bold plan to erect seven nuclear reactors nationwide, with the Loy Yang site in Victoria\'s Latrobe Valley earmarked as a prime spot. However, this vision clashes head-on with Victoria\'s longstanding ban on nuclear activities, enshrined in the Nuclear Activities (Prohibitions) Act of 1983. Overturning this would be akin to convincing a vegan to run a butcher shop. ​\r\nABC\r\n+7\r\nSBS Australia\r\n+7\r\nYahoo News Australia\r\n+7\r\nThe Guardian\r\n\r\nBattin\'s gas-centric focus isn\'t just a random choice. With local gas fields on the decline and energy prices doing their best impression of a rollercoaster, he sees onshore gas exploration as the quick fix to keep Victorians\' lights on and wallets intact. Meanwhile, Dutton\'s nuclear daydreams are viewed by some as the political equivalent of building castles in the air—grand, but lacking a solid foundation. ​\r\ninkl\r\n+6\r\nThe Guardian\r\n+6\r\nThe Guardian\r\n+6\r\n\r\nAs of now, the Victorian Liberals are sticking to their gas guns, leaving Dutton to champion his nuclear crusade solo. Battin\'s message to Dutton? \"Good luck with that, but we\'re good over here with our gas plans.\" It\'s a classic case of political \"agree to disagree,\" with a side of \"please don\'t drag us into this.\" ​\r\nRenewEconomy\r\ninkl\r\n+6\r\nThe Guardian\r\n+6\r\nnews\r\n+6', 0, 'factabot', 'Victorian_Liberal_Leader_Distances_Party_from_Federal_Nuclear_Proposal', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 07:22:11', '2025-04-15 07:22:11', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (386, 'Rory McIlroy Completes Career Grand Slam at The Masters', 'McIlroy finally dons the green jacket, proving that patience (and a killer swing) pays off.', 'It finally happened. Rory “Almost There” McIlroy has actually won The Masters, completing the career Grand Slam after 17 years of Augusta foreplay. Yes, the man who’s been ghosting the green jacket since 2007 finally sealed the deal in 2025, joining the ultra-exclusive club of “Golf Guys Who’ve Won Everything”—alongside legends like Tiger Woods and Jack Nicklaus, and presumably a few golf-course ghosts. +Wikipedia\r\n\r\nMcIlroy’s win wasn’t exactly textbook. The man racked up four double bogeys—setting a Masters record for “most disasters survived en route to victory.” But like any good protagonist in a sports movie, he ignored the bad script and pulled off a sudden-death playoff win over Justin Rose, who now knows what it feels like to be the bridesmaid, again. Rory, meanwhile, cried, hugged his wife Erica, and daughter Poppy like he’d just broken a decade-long curse… which, to be fair, he had. His last major win was in 2014, when TikTok wasn’t even a thing. +PGA Tour\r\n\r\nZoom out, and this is a redemption arc dripping in irony. For years, McIlroy was the guy destined to dominate, until nerves, Nike deals, and swing coach roulette got in the way. Every April, the media would breathlessly ask “Is this Rory’s year?” and then pretend not to look disappointed when he faceplanted on the back nine. But now? Rory’s wearing the jacket, cashing a record-breaking $4.2 million cheque, and proving that if you stall long enough, the plot twist will eventually land. +TalkSport\r\n\r\nAs for the update: McIlroy is basking in green glory while Rose nurses his trauma with polite British resentment. Rory’s caddie Harry Diamond pocketed $420k, which is great because someone needs to carry all that ego. Augusta’s curse is broken. Somewhere, Greg Norman is quietly seething. +NYPost', 0, 'factabot', 'Rory_McIlroy_Completes_Career_Grand_Slam_at_The_Masters', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 07:25:07', '2025-04-15 07:43:29', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (387, 'Dutton Clarifies Housing Plan: \'Don\'t Want Prices to Go Down\'', 'Opposition leader assures homeowners their property values are safe under his watch.', 'Peter Dutton, in a stunning display of saying the quiet part very loud, has clarified his big, bold housing policy: he doesn’t want house prices to go down. That’s right. In a country where half the population is considering swapping avocado toast for sleeping in their cars, Dutton has confirmed he’s not here to fix the housing crisis—just make it a bit more comfortable for people already in the club. +ABC\r\n\r\nHis plan? A thrilling new tax break for first-home buyers, letting them deduct mortgage interest for five years. Sounds nice, until you realise it’s like handing out free petrol during a traffic jam—it doesn’t fix the problem, it just makes everyone slam on the accelerator. Economists, aka the party poopers of election season, have already flagged this as a fast-track to making prices even higher. Because when you throw cash at demand without building more supply, what could possibly go wrong? +News.com.au\r\n\r\nDutton insists he’s just trying to “protect the value of people’s homes.” Translation: Sorry renters, we’re keeping the property ladder just out of reach because falling prices might make Karen from Camberwell feel poor. He even dodged questions about whether he’d help his own kids buy a house—possibly because the answer is “yes, with my MP salary and probably a casual apartment in Canberra.” +The Guardian\r\n\r\nAs for the latest twist, Dutton’s standing by his not-actually-a-solution solution, despite everyone from housing experts to your cousin with a TikTok account pointing out that it’s wildly counterproductive. Meanwhile, Labor’s building promises and the Greens are dreaming of unicorn housing policies—but Dutton? He’s just here to make sure no boomer’s equity ever sheds a dollar. +SBS', 0, 'factabot', 'Dutton_Clarifies_Housing_Plan_Dont_Want_Prices_to_Go_Down', 'draft', '', NULL, '2025-04-15 07:28:08', '2025-04-15 07:34:13', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (388, 'Dutton Clarifies Housing Plan: \'Don\'t Want Prices to Go Down\'', 'Opposition leader assures homeowners their property values are safe under his watch.', 'Peter Dutton, in a stunning display of saying the quiet part very loud, has clarified his big, bold housing policy: he doesn’t want house prices to go down. That’s right. In a country where half the population is considering swapping avocado toast for sleeping in their cars, Dutton has confirmed he’s not here to fix the housing crisis—just make it a bit more comfortable for people already in the club. +ABC\r\n\r\nHis plan? A thrilling new tax break for first-home buyers, letting them deduct mortgage interest for five years. Sounds nice, until you realise it’s like handing out free petrol during a traffic jam—it doesn’t fix the problem, it just makes everyone slam on the accelerator. Economists, aka the party poopers of election season, have already flagged this as a fast-track to making prices even higher. Because when you throw cash at demand without building more supply, what could possibly go wrong? +News.com.au\r\n\r\nDutton insists he’s just trying to “protect the value of people’s homes.” Translation: Sorry renters, we’re keeping the property ladder just out of reach because falling prices might make Karen from Camberwell feel poor. He even dodged questions about whether he’d help his own kids buy a house—possibly because the answer is “yes, with my MP salary and probably a casual apartment in Canberra.” +The Guardian\r\n\r\nAs for the latest twist, Dutton’s standing by his not-actually-a-solution solution, despite everyone from housing experts to your cousin with a TikTok account pointing out that it’s wildly counterproductive. Meanwhile, Labor’s building promises and the Greens are dreaming of unicorn housing policies—but Dutton? He’s just here to make sure no boomer’s equity ever sheds a dollar. +SBS', 0, 'factabot', 'Dutton_Clarifies_Housing_Plan_Dont_Want_Prices_to_Go_Down_1', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-15 07:29:30', '2025-04-15 07:29:30', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (389, 'Leaked Video Reveals Liberal MP\'s Critique of Free TAFE Program', 'Sarah Henderson brands Free TAFE as a $1.5 billion flop. Because who needs affordable education when you can have student debt?', 'In a leaked video that’s basically the political version of “Oops, I said the quiet part out loud,” Liberal MP Sarah Henderson has been caught dragging the Albanese government’s Free TAFE program like it just flunked its own trade course. Speaking to what she thought was a friendly crowd (spoiler: someone had their phone out), Henderson slammed the $1.5 billion policy as “not working” and “just a bit of a dud”—which is rich coming from a party that once thought robo-debt was a solid idea. +News.com.au\r\n\r\nThis wasn’t a polite disagreement; it was a full-blown roast. Henderson, trying to sound “reasonable,” basically implied the program was a waste of taxpayer cash, a jobs mirage dressed up as social good. Her critique? Low completion rates and poor outcomes. Her subtext? “Skilled trades are fine, just not if Labor’s handing out the spanners.” +Sky News\r\n\r\nBut Labor’s not having it. Albanese, clearly sick of the free TAFE slander, clapped back saying the program’s getting Aussies—especially women and regional folk—into real jobs. And honestly, in a country with tradespeople booked out until 2031, maybe giving someone a free go at learning plumbing isn’t the end of civilisation? +The Guardian\r\n\r\nThe fallout: Dutton’s mob now hinting they’ll “reform” the whole thing if elected. Translation: TAFE’s going back on the shelf next to Medicare dental and your dreams of affording rent. Meanwhile, voters are wondering why helping people learn a trade is controversial when half the nation can’t get a bloody electrician. +ABC', 0, 'factabot', 'Leaked_Video_Reveals_Liberal_MPs_Critique_of_Free_TAFE_Program', 'draft', '', NULL, '2025-04-15 07:32:57', '2025-04-15 08:29:18', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (391, 'Dutton Says Australia Needs ‘Nuclear Courage’—Nation Asks for Clarification', 'When your climate plan sounds like a Marvel origin story.', 'Peter Dutton has once again fired up the uranium barbecue, this time declaring that what Australia needs is “nuclear courage.” Which, depending on your interpretation, is either a bold call for energy reform—or the tagline for a Cold War-era propaganda film. +ABC News\n\nStanding in front of a PowerPoint deck that looked suspiciously like it was made in 2007, Dutton unveiled his big, brave, extremely vague plan to go nuclear—because nothing says “forward-thinking policy” like advocating for reactors in a country that still can’t agree on where to put a single wind farm. He’s calling on Labor to be “brave” and back nuclear energy, conveniently forgetting that his own state premiers have said “lol, no thanks” every time the idea gets floated. +Guardian Australia\n\nThe real kicker? Australia literally has laws banning nuclear power. So Dutton\'s pitch amounts to: “Let’s spend billions to repeal decades-old legislation, build power plants no one wants, using tech we don’t have, with tradies we’re already 80,000 short of.” Bold. Reckless. A little delusional. But hey—very courageous. +The Australian\n\nWhen asked how this would be funded or where these mythical nuclear plants would go, Dutton dodged like a man in a political laser tag match, promising “more details later” and muttering something about jobs and China. Meanwhile, energy experts have warned the whole plan could take 15+ years to materialize and might not even reduce emissions any faster than renewables already can—if we, you know, just invested in them. +ABC News', 0, 'factabot', 'dutton-says-australia-needs-nuclear-courage-nation-asks-for-clarification', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 14:08:09', 21);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (392, 'China Tells US to ‘Mind Its Own Business’ Over Taiwan Drills', 'Ah yes, diplomacy via loud military gestures and vague threats.', 'In a recent escalation of tensions, China has launched extensive military drills around Taiwan, prompting a stern warning to the United States to refrain from interference. The exercises, involving aircraft, naval vessels, and live-fire operations, are seen as a direct response to perceived U.S. support for Taiwan\'s pro-independence stance. China\'s Foreign Ministry emphasized that these drills are necessary measures to safeguard national sovereignty and territorial integrity. ​\n\nThe United States, along with allies such as Japan and the European Union, has expressed concern over China\'s military activities, labeling them as provocative and destabilizing. U.S. officials have reiterated their commitment to maintaining peace and stability in the Taiwan Strait, urging Beijing to engage in dialogue rather than coercion. ​\nThe Guardian\n\nTaiwan, for its part, has condemned China\'s actions, with President Lai Ching-te calling for calm and emphasizing the island\'s readiness to defend its sovereignty. The Taiwanese government has also highlighted the importance of international support in deterring aggression and preserving regional security. ​\nthetimes.co.uk\n+7\nNew York Post\n+7\nNew York Post\n+7\nes.wikipedia.org\n+5\nCBS News\n+5\nen.wikipedia.org\n+5', 0, 'factabot', 'china-tells-us-to-mind-its-own-business-over-taiwan-drills', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 10:53:37', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (393, 'Aussie Swimmer Breaks Record, Still Not Impressed with Lane Conditions', 'Because chlorine excellence deserves better tiles.', 'Kyle Chalmers Breaks Record, Still Not Impressed with Lane Conditions\n\nAustralian Olympic champion Kyle Chalmers delivered a standout performance at the 2025 Swim Open Stockholm, clocking a personal best of 22.89 seconds in the men\'s 50m butterfly. This time not only earned him the gold medal but also positioned him as the second-fastest Australian ever in this event, trailing only Matt Targett\'s 2009 supersuit-era record of 22.73 seconds. ​\nSwimSwam\n+1\nSwimSwam\n+1\n\nChalmers\' achievement is particularly noteworthy given his recent challenges, including heart and shoulder surgeries. His performance in Stockholm follows impressive swims at the Bergen Swim Festival, where he recorded a 47.27 in the 100m freestyle and a personal best of 21.78 in the 50m freestyle. ​\nTikTok\n+3\nSwimSwam\n+3\nSwimSwam\n+3\n\nDespite these successes, Chalmers has expressed concerns about lane conditions affecting swimmers\' performances. While specific details about his comments in Stockholm are limited, it\'s not uncommon for elite swimmers to critique factors like water turbulence and lane assignments, which can influence race outcomes.​\n\nAs Chalmers continues his preparation for upcoming competitions, including the Australian Trials for the World Championships, his recent performances underscore his resilience and determination to remain at the top of his sport. ​\nSwimming World', 0, 'factabot', 'aussie-swimmer-breaks-record-still-not-impressed-with-lane-conditions', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 12:52:42', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (394, 'Great Barrier Reef Suffers Another Bleaching Event—Nature Facepalms', 'That white coral chic is back. Too bad it’s from global warming.', 'Great Barrier Reef Suffers Another Bleaching Event—Nature Facepalms\n\nIn a disheartening yet unsurprising development, the Great Barrier Reef has experienced its fifth mass bleaching event in eight years, marking the seventh on record. This latest episode, confirmed in March 2024, is part of a broader global bleaching crisis exacerbated by rising ocean temperatures and climate change. ​\nFinancial Times\nGreat Barrier Reef Foundation\n\nThe extent of the damage is staggering. Aerial surveys revealed that 73% of the reefs within the Great Barrier Reef Marine Park exhibited significant bleaching, with some areas experiencing extreme bleaching levels—over 90% of coral cover affected. Notably, this is the first time such severe bleaching has been observed across all three regions of the reef. ​\ncouriermail\n+4\nAustralian Institute of Marine Science\n+4\nAustralian Institute of Marine Science\n+4\n\nThe southern region, particularly around the Keppel Islands, recorded unprecedented heat stress levels, with Degree Heating Weeks (DHW) reaching between 12 to 15.5°C-weeks. Such prolonged heat exposure has led to extensive coral mortality, with some areas witnessing up to 95% loss in certain coral species like Acropora. ​\nAustralian Institute of Marine Science\n+1\nAustralian Institute of Marine Science\n+1\nAustralian Institute of Marine Science\n+3\nThe University of Sydney\n+3\nOceanographic\n+3\n\nThis event aligns with the fourth global coral bleaching event recognized by NOAA, highlighting the widespread impact of climate-induced heat stress on coral ecosystems worldwide. ​\nNOAA\n\nThe cumulative effects of repeated bleaching events, cyclones, and other stressors have left the reef\'s resilience severely compromised. Scientists warn that without immediate and substantial action to mitigate climate change, the Great Barrier Reef\'s future remains in jeopardy. ​\nThe Verge\n+2\nFinancial Times\n+2\ncouriermail\n+2', 0, 'factabot', 'great-barrier-reef-suffers-another-bleaching-event-nature-facepalms', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 11:17:57', 19);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (395, 'Doctors Warn Against ‘Raw Water’ Trend—Yes, That’s Just Tap Water', 'Filtered? Nah. Safe? Nope. Expensive? Absolutely.', 'Doctors Warn Against ‘Raw Water’ Trend—Yes, That’s Just Tap Water Without the Safety\n\nIn the latest health fad that\'s making experts cringe, some individuals are turning to \"raw water\"—untreated, unfiltered water sourced directly from natural springs or streams—believing it to be a healthier alternative to tap water. Proponents claim that this water retains beneficial minerals and lacks chemicals like fluoride. However, health professionals are sounding the alarm, emphasizing that consuming such water can expose individuals to harmful pathogens, including bacteria, viruses, and parasites. ​\nSELF\nCBS News\n\nThe Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) warns that untreated water can harbor dangerous organisms like E. coli, giardia, and cholera, which can lead to severe gastrointestinal illnesses and other health complications. Despite the natural appeal, experts stress that modern water treatment processes are essential for removing these contaminants and ensuring water safety. ​\nABC News\n\nWhile some believe that raw water offers health benefits due to its natural mineral content, medical professionals argue that these minerals are also present in treated water and that the risks of consuming untreated water far outweigh any perceived advantages. They caution that the trend could lead to a resurgence of waterborne diseases that modern sanitation has largely kept at bay. ​\n\nIn light of these concerns, health authorities recommend sticking to treated water sources and advise against the consumption of raw water. They also suggest that individuals concerned about tap water quality use certified filtration systems rather than resorting to untreated alternatives. ​\nCleveland Clinic', 0, 'factabot', 'doctors-warn-against-raw-water-trend-yes-thats-just-tap-water', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 07:09:15', 19);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (396, 'ASX Opens Flat After Wall Street Whiplash—Investors Shrug', 'The market equivalent of staring into the void and saying, \'meh\'.', 'ASX Opens Flat After Wall Street Whiplash—Investors Shrug\n\nIn a move that surprised absolutely no one, the ASX opened flat today, mirroring Wall Street\'s recent rollercoaster ride. The S&P/ASX 200 index nudged up a mere 0.17% to 7,761.70 points, as investors collectively decided to take a \"wait and see\" approach amid ongoing global economic uncertainties. ​\nThe Australian\n\nWall Street\'s volatility, driven by fluctuating tariff policies and geopolitical tensions, has left investors on edge. Despite a temporary pause in aggressive tariffs by the U.S., markets remain cautious, with analysts warning of potential long-term impacts on global trade dynamics. ​\nYahoo Finance\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+2\nThe Australian\n+2\nThe Guardian\n+1\nThe Guardian\n+1\n\nBack home, Australian investors are keeping a close eye on local developments. Healthcare stocks like CSL and Resmed saw gains, while consumer staples lagged behind. The Australian dollar also experienced a slight uptick, trading at 63.69 US cents. ​\nThe Australian\n+5\nThe Guardian\n+5\nThe Edge Malaysia\n+5\nABC\n+5\nnews\n+5\nThe Australian\n+5\n\nAs the global economic landscape continues to shift, investors are advised to stay informed and exercise caution. With markets reacting to every new development, the only certainty is uncertainty itself.', 0, 'factabot', 'asx-opens-flat-after-wall-street-whiplash-investors-shrug', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-27 01:49:44', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (397, 'Hugh Jackman Confirms Wolverine Return—Gym Memberships Spike', 'He’s back. And so are your unrealistic body expectations.', 'Hugh Jackman Confirms Wolverine Return—Gym Memberships Spike\n\nHugh Jackman is back as Wolverine in Deadpool & Wolverine (2024), and fans are hitting the gym in droves, inspired by the actor\'s impressive transformation. Jackman, at 55, shared his intense workout regimen on social media, showcasing his dedication to reprising the iconic role. His training included deadlifting over 150 pounds and adhering to an 8,600-calorie daily diet, all under the guidance of a dedicated team. This commitment has not only reignited excitement for the character but also motivated many to pursue their own fitness goals. ​\nnews\n+13\nPeople.com\n+13\nWikipedia\n+13\nReddit\nNew York Post\n+2\nnews\n+2\nDailymotion\n+2\n\nThe film\'s release has been a massive success, grossing over $1.3 billion worldwide and becoming the highest-grossing R-rated film in history. Jackman\'s return, alongside Ryan Reynolds, has been praised for its humor and action, further cementing Wolverine\'s place in the Marvel Cinematic Universe. ​\nnews\n+1\nWikipedia\n+1\nVanity Fair', 0, 'factabot', 'hugh-jackman-confirms-wolverine-return-gym-memberships-spike', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-26 05:05:22', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (398, 'Perth Home with Unfinished Roof Listed at $1.2M', 'Privacy? Optional. Rain? Inevitable.', 'Perth Home with Unfinished Roof Listed at $1.2M\n\nIn a move that\'s raising eyebrows and perhaps a few umbrellas, a Perth property has hit the market with a price tag of $1.2 million—despite lacking a completed roof. This listing underscores the intense pressure in Perth\'s housing market, where demand continues to outstrip supply.​\nABC\n+1\nHouse Behind House\n+1\n\nThe city\'s real estate landscape has been described as \"insane,\" with properties selling at lightning speed and buyers often engaging in bidding wars. One prospective buyer recounted losing a property to a higher cash offer made just minutes before the bidding closed, highlighting the fierce competition. ​\nABC\n\nCompounding the issue, several local builders have recently collapsed, leaving numerous homes unfinished and buyers in limbo. Companies like Nicheliving and Start Right Homes have gone into liquidation, contributing to the shortage of completed homes and exacerbating the housing crisis. ​\nntnews\nABC\n+1\nnews\n+1\n\nThis particular property\'s listing, despite its incomplete state, reflects the desperation of buyers willing to consider homes that require significant additional investment. It also highlights the challenges faced by the construction industry, including labor shortages and rising material costs, which have led to delays and increased prices.​\n\nAs Perth\'s housing market continues to sizzle, buyers are advised to exercise caution and conduct thorough due diligence—especially when considering properties that come without a roof.', 0, 'factabot', 'perth-home-with-unfinished-roof-listed-at-12m', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 15:36:16', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (399, 'Aussies Embrace ‘Standing Brunch’ to Save Time and Spines', 'Because who has time to sit and eat toast these days?', 'Aussies Embrace ‘Standing Brunch’ to Save Time and Spines\n\nIn a bold move that combines efficiency with a touch of rebellion, Australians are redefining the traditional brunch by embracing the \'standing brunch\' trend. Gone are the days of leisurely seated meals; now, it\'s all about quick bites on the go, reflecting a shift in dining habits influenced by economic pressures and changing lifestyles.​\n\nThe rise of hybrid work models and the increasing cost of living have led many to forgo the classic sit-down breakfast. Instead, there\'s a noticeable uptick in weekend brunch transactions, as people choose to indulge during their days off. This shift has prompted cafes to adapt, offering more grab-and-go options to cater to the evolving preferences of their clientele. ​\nThe Guardian\n\nMoreover, the demand for unique and memorable dining experiences has never been higher. Australians are seeking out brunch spots that offer not just food, but an experience worth sharing. This has led to the popularity of innovative menu items and creative presentations that cater to the Instagram-savvy crowd. ​\n\nIn this new era of dining, the \'standing brunch\' embodies the balance Australians are striving for: efficient, yet indulgent; quick, yet memorable. It\'s a testament to the nation\'s ability to adapt and find joy in the simple pleasures, even when standing.', 0, 'factabot', 'aussies-embrace-standing-brunch-to-save-time-and-spines', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 17:17:58', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (400, 'Man Arrested After Driving Ride-On Lawn Mower on Highway', 'Who needs horsepower when you’ve got lawn power?', 'In a scene that could have been lifted from a quirky indie film, a 64-year-old Georgia man, Willie Laguines, was arrested after being spotted cruising down Highway 186 on a ride-on lawn mower, beer in hand . When deputies approached, Laguines reportedly admitted he was returning home from a convenience store and had consumed alcohol . He was charged with DUI, open container violations, and operating a low-speed vehicle on a highway .​\n97x.com\n+4\nWRIF Rocks Detroit\n+4\nMarshall Radio\n+4\nDimplify\n+4\nWSB-TV Channel 2 - Atlanta\n+4\nMarshall Radio\n+4', 0, 'factabot', 'man-arrested-after-driving-ride-on-lawn-mower-on-highway', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-05-05 17:59:26', 20);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (401, 'Labor Accused of ‘Housing Maths Gymnastics’ Over Budget Claims', 'Apparently you can solve a housing crisis by rebranding old promises. Ta-da!', 'Labor Accused of ‘Housing Maths Gymnastics’ Over Budget Claims\n\nIn a display of fiscal flexibility that would make an Olympic gymnast proud, Treasurer Jim Chalmers has been accused of performing \"housing maths gymnastics\" to present the government\'s budget in a favorable light. Critics argue that the numbers don\'t quite add up, especially when it comes to addressing Australia\'s housing crisis.​\n\nShadow Treasurer Angus Taylor didn\'t hold back during a recent debate, suggesting that Chalmers\' figures were more about political spin than economic reality. He pointed out that while the government touts its investments in housing, the actual impact on affordability and availability remains questionable.​\nThe Guardian\n+1\nThe Guardian\n+1\n\nThe debate intensified as both parties exchanged barbs over their respective housing policies. Taylor emphasized the Coalition\'s commitment to supporting first-home buyers through tax incentives, while Chalmers defended Labor\'s approach, highlighting investments in social housing and urban development.​\nThe Guardian\n+1\nThe Guardian\n+1\n\nHowever, the core issue remains: Australians are grappling with skyrocketing housing prices and a shortage of affordable homes. While politicians engage in numerical acrobatics, many citizens feel left behind, struggling to secure stable housing in an increasingly competitive market.', 0, 'factabot', 'labor-accused-of-housing-maths-gymnastics-over-budget-claims', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-05-03 19:01:56', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (402, 'NZ PM Criticises Australia Over Climate Foot-Dragging—Again', 'It’s not sibling rivalry until someone says ‘you’re embarrassing us internationally’.', 'New Zealand Prime Minister Christopher Luxon has once again taken aim at Australia\'s climate policies, expressing frustration over what he perceives as a lack of commitment to meaningful climate action. In a recent address, Luxon emphasized the need for countries, especially close neighbors like Australia, to take decisive steps in reducing emissions and transitioning to renewable energy sources.​\nReuters\n\nLuxon\'s comments come amid growing concerns about Australia\'s continued investment in fossil fuel projects and its perceived reluctance to adopt more aggressive climate targets. Environmental groups have echoed these sentiments, pointing out that Australia\'s actions are inconsistent with the urgent need to address climate change.​\n\nThe New Zealand Prime Minister highlighted the importance of regional cooperation in combating climate change, stressing that the Pacific region is particularly vulnerable to its impacts. He urged Australia to align its policies with global efforts to mitigate climate risks, suggesting that failure to do so could strain diplomatic relations and hinder collaborative initiatives.​\n\nIn response, Australian officials have defended their climate strategies, citing recent investments in renewable energy and commitments to net-zero emissions by 2050. However, critics argue that these measures fall short of what\'s needed and that Australia must take more immediate and substantial actions to reduce its carbon footprint.', 0, 'factabot', 'nz-pm-criticises-australia-over-climate-foot-dragging-again', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 15:27:23', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (403, 'NRL Star Suspended for Spraying Ref With Energy Drink', 'Not quite the performance boost he was hoping for.', 'NRL Player Suspended After Spraying Referee with Energy Drink\n\nIn an unusual incident during a recent NRL match, a player was suspended after allegedly spraying an energy drink on the referee. The incident occurred during a heated moment in the game, leading to immediate disciplinary action from the league.​\n\nThe NRL has strict guidelines regarding player conduct, especially towards match officials. This event underscores the importance of maintaining professionalism and respect on the field. The league\'s swift response aims to reinforce these standards and deter similar behavior in the future.​\nnews\n\nWhile the player\'s identity and the specific details of the suspension have not been publicly disclosed, the NRL\'s actions highlight its commitment to upholding the integrity of the sport. Fans and players alike are reminded of the crucial role that referees play in ensuring fair and safe gameplay.​\n\nVisual suggestion: An AI-generated image depicting a rugby league player on the field, holding an energy drink bottle, with a referee nearby reacting to a spray of liquid.', 0, 'factabot', 'nrl-star-suspended-for-spraying-ref-with-energy-drink', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 12:18:22', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (404, 'Koala Habitat Bulldozed After Developer Claims ‘Clerical Error’', 'Oopsie-daisy! Just a tiny forest full of endangered species—our bad!', 'In a development that\'s left conservationists and locals reeling, a significant tract of koala habitat in Queensland has been cleared by mining company Vitrinite, which attributes the action to a \"clerical error.\" The company cleared approximately 47 hectares of land near its Vulcan South project site, an area still under federal environmental assessment. Vitrinite maintains that the clearing was for a \"small-scale resource definition\" activity, not requiring separate approval. ​\nMove Beyond Coal\n+8\nlockthegate.org.au\n+8\nEnvironmental Defenders Office\n+8\nABC\n\nEnvironmental groups, however, argue that this action violates the Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation (EPBC) Act, which mandates federal approval for activities impacting endangered species like koalas. The Queensland Conservation Council and the Environmental Defenders Office have called on Environment Minister Tanya Plibersek to intervene and halt further development. ​\nMove Beyond Coal\n+9\nEnvironmental Defenders Office\n+9\nlockthegate.org.au\n+9\n\nDespite the ongoing federal investigation into the legality of the clearing, Vitrinite continues operations at the site. Critics contend that this situation highlights significant shortcomings in Australia\'s environmental protection laws, allowing developers to proceed with potentially unlawful activities under the guise of administrative oversights. ​\nEnvironmental Defenders Office\n+5\nlockthegate.org.au\n+5\nMove Beyond Coal\n+5\n\nVisual suggestion: An AI-generated image depicting a koala perched on a solitary tree amidst a cleared landscape, with construction equipment in the background and a sign reading \"Clerical Error Zone.\"', 0, 'factabot', 'koala-habitat-bulldozed-after-developer-claims-clerical-error', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 17:12:09', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (405, 'Melbourne Hospital Warns of TikTok ‘Glue Nose Job’ Trend', 'Turns out sniffing glue is bad, even when it’s labelled ‘beauty hack’.', 'Melbourne Hospital Warns of TikTok \'Glue Nose Job\' Trend\n\nA concerning trend has emerged on TikTok, where users are applying glue to their noses in an attempt to mimic the effects of a nose job. This practice, often referred to as the \'glue nose job,\' has garnered significant attention on the platform. Medical professionals are raising alarms about the potential health risks associated with this trend, including skin irritation, allergic reactions, and long-term damage to nasal tissues.​\nInstagram\n\nExperts emphasize that such DIY cosmetic procedures are not only ineffective but also dangerous. The anatomy of the nose is complex, and improper manipulation can lead to complications that may require professional medical intervention. Health authorities urge individuals to consult with qualified medical professionals for any cosmetic concerns and to avoid unverified and potentially harmful beauty hacks circulating on social media.​\nThe Sun', 0, 'factabot', 'melbourne-hospital-warns-of-tiktok-glue-nose-job-trend', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 14:22:26', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (406, 'Woolies CEO Says Cost of Living Crisis ‘Builds Customer Loyalty’', 'Yes, we love loyalty. Especially when it comes with overpriced cheese.', 'In a statement that\'s raised more eyebrows than a surprise price hike, Woolworths CEO Amanda Bardwell has suggested that the ongoing cost-of-living crisis is, in a way, enhancing customer loyalty. As Australians tighten their belts, many are turning to supermarket loyalty programs like Woolworths\' Everyday Rewards in hopes of stretching their dollars further.​\nnews\n+6\nnews\n+6\nThe Australian\n+6\nMi-3\n+2\nnews\n+2\nABC\n+2\n\nThe Australian Competition and Consumer Commission (ACCC) recently highlighted concerns about these loyalty programs. Their report revealed that consumers often need to spend around $2,000 to earn a mere $10 discount, equating to just 0.5 cents saved per dollar spent. The ACCC also pointed out that the \"gamification\" of these programs might be influencing spending habits more than shoppers realize. ​\ntaylorwells.com.au\n+2\nABC\n+2\nnews\n+2\n\nDespite these revelations, Woolworths maintains that its loyalty initiatives are designed to offer value and enhance the shopping experience. However, with the ACCC\'s findings and growing public scrutiny, many are questioning the true benefits of these programs.​\ntaylorwells.com.au\n+1\nnews\n+1\n\nVisual suggestion: An AI-generated image depicting a shopper at a supermarket checkout, holding a loyalty card that\'s comically oversized, with a backdrop of price tags showing minimal discounts.', 0, 'factabot', 'woolies-ceo-says-cost-of-living-crisis-builds-customer-loyalty', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 11:08:48', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (407, 'Margot Robbie’s Outback Thriller Premieres to Screams—and Applause', 'It’s terrifying. It’s brilliant. It’s Australia, just with better lighting.', 'Margot Robbie\'s latest film, A Big Bold Beautiful Journey, premiered on April 15, 2025, in Sydney, Australia, marking her return to the screen post-Barbie. The romantic fantasy, directed by Kogonada, features Robbie alongside Colin Farrell in a tale about two strangers embarking on an unimaginable journey together .​\nWikipedia\n+1\nIMDb\n+1\n\nThe premiere was met with enthusiastic reactions, with audiences praising the film\'s unique storytelling and Robbie\'s compelling performance. The film is scheduled for a wider release in the United States on September 19, 2025 .​\nWikipedia', 0, 'factabot', 'margot-robbies-outback-thriller-premieres-to-screams-and-applause', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-27 13:51:36', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (408, 'Gold Coast Unit With No Kitchen or Bathroom Sells for $495K', 'Minimalist living meets maximum audacity.', 'In a move that underscores the intensity of the Gold Coast property market, a unit lacking both a kitchen and a bathroom has been sold for a staggering $495,000. This sale highlights the region\'s robust demand, where even properties requiring significant renovations are fetching high prices.​\ncouriermail\n\nThe Gold Coast\'s real estate landscape has been marked by a surge in property values, driven by factors such as interstate migration and a persistent supply-demand imbalance. Suburbs like Currumbin, Elanora, and Coolangatta have experienced notable growth, with apartment prices increasing by over six percent quarterly. ​\ncouriermail\n\nThis particular sale reflects a broader trend where buyers are willing to invest in properties needing substantial work, banking on the area\'s continued growth and the potential for significant returns on renovation investments.', 0, 'factabot', 'gold-coast-unit-with-no-kitchen-or-bathroom-sells-for-495k', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 11:06:00', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (409, 'Australians Are Booking ‘Doom Dinners’ to Talk About Death Over Wine', 'Because nothing pairs with rosé like existential dread.', 'In a trend that\'s turning heads and challenging taboos, Australians are gathering for \"Death Over Dinner\" events—intimate meals where the main course is mortality. These gatherings aim to bring the often-avoided topic of death to the dinner table, fostering open conversations about end-of-life wishes and care.​\nABC\n+3\nPalliative Care Australia\n+3\nDeath Over Dinner\n+3\n\nLaunched in the U.S. in 2013 by Michael Hebb, the Death Over Dinner initiative has since made its way to Australia, with the Australian Centre for Health Research adapting it for local audiences. The concept is simple: host a dinner, invite friends or family, and discuss topics related to death and dying. Participants are provided with conversation guides and resources to facilitate meaningful discussions. ​\nL / O / D\n+5\nDeakin\n+5\nLinkedIn\n+5\nPalliative Care Australia\n\nThe goal is to normalize conversations about death, ensuring that individuals\' end-of-life wishes are understood and respected. By discussing these matters in a relaxed setting, attendees often find it easier to express their thoughts and fears, leading to greater clarity and peace of mind.​\nPalliative Care Australia\n\nEvents have been held in various settings, from private homes to public venues like the historic West Terrace Cemetery in Adelaide, which hosted a sold-out dinner focusing on end-of-life themes. ​\nadelaidereview.com.au\n\nFor those interested in hosting their own Death Over Dinner, the official website offers tools and guidance to get started. It\'s an invitation to break bread and break the silence surrounding death. ​\nL / O / D\n+9\nLinkedIn\n+9\nDeakin\n+9\nLinkedIn\n+2\nDeakin\n+2\nDeath Over Dinner\n+2', 0, 'factabot', 'australians-are-booking-doom-dinners-to-talk-about-death-over-wine', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 15:37:19', 16);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (410, 'Man Armed with Sausage Roll Disrupts Brisbane Council Meeting', 'He came hungry, left handcuffed—and full of flaky rage.', 'In an incident that left council members both startled and amused, a man wielding a sausage roll caused a disruption during a Brisbane City Council meeting. The individual entered the chamber mid-session, brandishing the pastry and shouting about local infrastructure issues. Security personnel quickly intervened, escorting the man from the premises without further incident.​\n\nWhile no injuries were reported, the event has sparked discussions about security measures at public meetings. Council officials are reviewing protocols to ensure the safety of attendees and staff. The man\'s motivations remain unclear, but authorities are investigating the matter further.', 0, 'factabot', 'man-armed-with-sausage-roll-disrupts-brisbane-council-meeting', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 13:55:13', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (451, 'Albanese Touts ‘Digital Australia Plan’—Still Can’t Load the Website', 'If your digital revolution starts with a 404 error, maybe slow the parade.', 'Anthony Albanese just unveiled his grand vision for a “Digital Australia”—a shiny tech plan with enough buzzwords to make a startup founder blush. The only problem? The official site promoting it crashed during his own press conference. You’d think “scaling servers” might be part of the vision.\n\nAlbo is positioning this as his big post-COVID innovation strategy: better connectivity, digitised services, smarter infrastructure, and a workforce so tech-savvy it’ll fix your Wi-Fi before morning tea. He smiled earnestly while promising 5G corridors, cyber hubs, and blockchain-based whatever. But while the words flowed, the website didn’t. Journalists couldn’t access the plan live—and social media lit up faster than Telstra’s outage line.\n\nThe backdrop here? The PM’s trying to pitch himself as future-focused and “solutions over slogans” while Dutton bangs on about tax cuts and national security. But digital credibility gets a little murky when your flagship tech rollout kicks off with a 404. To voters, it feels a bit like launching a paperless office by fax.\n\nIn fairness, the plan might have merit—if anyone could read it. As of this morning, the Digital Australia portal was still timing out, and opposition MPs are now calling it the “Offline Australia Roadmap.” Classic.\n\nSources: ABC News, Guardian AU, News.com.au – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'albanese-touts-digital-australia-plan-still-cant-load-the-website', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 05:39:09', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (452, 'Fiji’s PM Warns Australia to Respect Pacific Sovereignty', 'Translation: Stop showing up uninvited with development brochures.', 'Fiji’s Prime Minister Sitiveni Rabuka has thrown shade across the ocean, warning Australia to stop treating the Pacific like its backyard barbecue. After Peter Dutton’s vague mutterings about a potential Russian military base in Indonesia, Rabuka didn’t mince words—reminding everyone that Pacific nations are sovereign, not strategic pawns.\n\nThe warning came via a press statement laced with diplomatic velvet but unmistakable steel. Rabuka didn’t name Dutton directly, but the timing made the subtext clearer than the Pacific’s turquoise waters. His point: Pacific nations don’t appreciate being cast as chess pieces in Australia’s election drama.\n\nThis fits a bigger pattern. Australia’s Pacific step-up has often felt more like a sidestep—offering aid and photo-ops while grumbling when countries engage with China or Russia. But the Pacific isn’t some passive “buffer zone.” These countries have agency, pride, and long memories—especially when outsiders act entitled.\n\nRabuka’s intervention wasn’t just for Canberra’s benefit—it was also a quiet signal to neighbours like PNG, Samoa, and the Solomons. Australia needs to earn trust, not demand it.\n\nAs for Dutton? He’s now dodging questions on whether he overstated foreign threats to look tough during campaign season. Rabuka’s message? Australia should maybe try listening more and lecturing less.\n\nSources: ABC Pacific, SBS News, The Australian – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'fijis-pm-warns-australia-to-respect-pacific-sovereignty', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-17 03:24:05', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (453, 'Australian Gymnast Goes Viral for Mid-Flip Wave to Crowd', 'Who says Olympic sports can’t also be performance art?', 'Move over Simone Biles—Australia’s own acrobatic legend just served Olympic-level sass mid-air. During the national championships in Sydney, 17-year-old gymnast Eliza Trent pulled off a double-twisting layout and threw in a cheeky wave to the crowd. Mid. Flip. The footage exploded online, with fans dubbing her “The Flying Show-Off.”\n\nEliza says the move wasn’t planned. “I just felt in the zone,” she told reporters with the confidence of someone who’s been cartwheeling since kindergarten. The judges were less amused, docking her 0.2 for “unnecessary flair,” which, frankly, sounds like a jealous robot wrote it.\n\nGymnastics Australia was quick to spin it as “a sign of the sport’s evolution,” while Eliza’s coach looked like she aged ten years in one second. But the internet didn’t care. TikTok, Instagram, and even Russian state media (??) picked up the clip. “This is what elite gymnastics needs,” said one viral tweet. “Confidence. Chaos. A little wink.”\n\nContext-wise, it’s a perfect antidote to a week filled with political bickering and climate dread. A teenager soared through the air and reminded us sport isn’t just about precision—it’s about joy, rebellion, and a bit of mischief.\n\nEliza’s now a trending hashtag. Paris 2024 selectors are reportedly taking notes. Just don’t try it in your Pilates class.\n\nSources: ABC Sport, The Guardian AU, Channel 7 – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'australian-gymnast-goes-viral-for-mid-flip-wave-to-crowd', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-27 10:34:57', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (454, 'Tasmania Declares State of Drought Despite ‘Wettest April’ Elsewhere', 'Because why not have fire and flood forecasts in the same bulletin?', 'While the rest of Australia’s east coast is practically swimming through April, Tasmania has officially declared a drought. Yes, really. The Bureau of Meteorology confirmed Hobart’s rainfall is down 35% this year, while Queenslanders are busy building arks.\n\nPremier Jeremy Rockliff didn’t sugarcoat it—declaring parts of northern Tasmania in “prolonged dry stress,” triggering relief measures for farmers watching crops wither faster than political promises. Meanwhile, Melbourne and Sydney just recorded their wettest start to April in over a decade, making this declaration feel like Tasmania’s gone rogue.\n\nThe contrast is more than weather banter—it’s a snapshot of Australia’s growing climate schizophrenia. Drought declarations and flood alerts are being issued in the same breath, often by the same agency. Climate experts say this polarisation of weather patterns is only going to get worse, with La Niña and El Niño basically tag-teaming the continent.\n\nSo while one half of the country debates umbrellas vs. boats, Tassie is rationing water and preparing emergency farm grants. It’s like a climate choose-your-own-adventure—and nobody’s winning.\n\nSources: ABC Tasmania, The Examiner, WeatherZone – April 16, 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'tasmania-declares-state-of-drought-despite-wettest-april-elsewhere', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-29 06:10:04', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (455, 'Experts Say ‘Sick Day Shaming’ is the New Workplace Epidemic', 'You’re not lazy—you’re just not coughing hard enough for HR.', 'Forget the flu—Australia’s latest workplace outbreak is passive-aggressive eyebrow raises whenever someone dares to take a sick day. A new report from HR analytics firm WorkSafeMe found that 67% of employees feel “judged or guilted” for calling in sick, especially in hybrid or remote roles.\n\nLeading the judgmental parade? Middle managers who proudly haven’t taken a day off since Kevin Rudd. Psychologists say this toxic “sick day shaming” culture leads to presenteeism—where people clock in sick just to prove they’re committed, then infect the entire Slack channel with norovirus and resentment.\n\nThe background here is post-COVID exhaustion. After years of “powering through,” workers are burned out but still expected to perform like Olympic sprinters with inboxes. Gen Z isn’t having it, though—they’re reviving the radical idea that “sick” means rest, not reply-all.\n\nThe kicker? The worst offenders are often workplaces with “wellbeing” posters in the break room and mental health webinars scheduled for 6pm on a Friday.\n\nWorkSafeMe is urging companies to overhaul absence policies and start rewarding recovery, not martyrdom. Until then, Australia’s work culture might remain the only place where sneezing is seen as career sabotage.\n\nSources: AFR, Guardian AU, SBS Insight – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'experts-say-sick-day-shaming-is-the-new-workplace-epidemic', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 14:46:59', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (456, 'Qantas Trials Standing Seats on Domestic Flights', 'Because nothing says comfort like a flying mosh pit at 30,000 feet.', 'Because flying wasn’t uncomfortable enough, Qantas has begun trialling “vertical seating” on select domestic routes—a bold experiment in turning economy passengers into literal sardines. Think rollercoaster harness meets Ryanair fever dream.\n\nQantas claims the upright seating model increases cabin capacity by 20% while keeping ticket prices “affordable.” Translation: less legroom, more elbows, and zero dignity. The seats are padded backboards with fold-down perches, allowing passengers to “semi-lean” like cows in a milking stall.\n\nCEO Vanessa Hudson insists it’s about “meeting demand with innovation.” Frequent flyers say it’s a cruel joke. Safety regulators are currently reviewing whether these standing contraptions are even legal for flights over 90 minutes.\n\nContext? Airlines globally are trying to cram more humans into the sky as post-pandemic demand skyrockets. But this might be the most unholy union of capitalism and claustrophobia yet.\n\nTrial flights between Sydney and Melbourne launched yesterday. Reviews are already in: “It’s like doing squats at 35,000 feet.” The next in-flight innovation? Possibly oxygen surcharges and BYO tray tables.\n\nSources: SMH, Crikey, Traveller – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'qantas-trials-standing-seats-on-domestic-flights', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 14:40:23', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (457, 'Bluey’s Dad Bandit Named ‘Australia’s Most Relatable Dad’', 'He’s tired, confused, and trying his best—basically all of us.', 'He’s blue, animated, and entirely fictional—but apparently, Bandit Heeler is now the gold standard for Australian fatherhood. A new YouGov poll has declared Bluey’s dad the “most relatable Aussie dad,” beating out actual humans like Chris Hemsworth, Karl Stefanovic, and every barbecue dad named Gary.\n\nBandit, voiced by David McCormack, has become a cultural phenomenon for juggling work, parenting, and absurd imaginary games with suspiciously limitless patience. He’s been praised for normalising fatherhood that\'s present, playful, and emotionally intelligent—which is a high bar when you’re literally drawn by animators.\n\nThe background? Bluey’s global success has turned the Brisbane-made cartoon into a parenting bible. Bandit has wiped bums, played hospital, and unpacked emotional trauma—all before breakfast. Millennials are quoting him in therapy sessions. Gen X dads are quietly wondering why their kids don’t see them as chill, philosophical cattle dogs.\n\nBut the context is key: in a landscape of toxic masculinity and “old school dads” still high-fiving for changing one nappy a year, Bandit represents a wholesome, modern archetype. He’s fun without being flaky, vulnerable without losing the plot.\n\nThe award, though fake, came with real media coverage, a thousand memes, and even a tribute mural in inner Melbourne. Bandit didn’t comment—probably busy playing ‘Statues’ with Bluey and Bingo.\n\nSources: ABC News, Guardian AU, Pedestrian.TV – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'blueys-dad-bandit-named-australias-most-relatable-dad', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-05-01 13:34:26', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (458, 'Tiny Shed in Hobart Marketed as ‘Cosy Studio’—No Plumbing Included', 'Live the minimalist dream, just don’t flush it.', 'A 3x3m timber shed in suburban Hobart has hit the market this week, rebranded as a “cosy micro-studio retreat.” The catch? It has no plumbing, no insulation, and no shame. Asking price? A cheeky $195,000.\n\nThe so-called “studio” features a single power outlet, questionable flooring, and enough space for a mattress and, maybe, a kettle—if you sleep diagonally. The listing describes it as “perfect for creatives or minimalists seeking a no-fuss lifestyle.” Translation: ideal for masochists with money.\n\nBackground: Hobart’s property market has surged 25% in the past two years, fuelled by mainlanders fleeing Melbourne in search of mountain views and mortgage misery. Locals now face a brutal rental squeeze, with stories of people sleeping in vans, storage units, and yes, glorified sheds.\n\nThe broader issue? This listing isn’t a joke—it’s the housing crisis laid bare. Young people can’t buy, renters can’t rent, and now sheds are apparently “innovative housing solutions.”\n\nThe shed\'s gone viral, sparking outrage and memes. One tweet read, “Australia 2025: pay $200K for a roof and the privilege of pooping elsewhere.”\n\nNo sale yet—but given the market, someone will bite. Probably an influencer looking for content.\n\nSources: Domain, Mercury, The Guardian AU – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'tiny-shed-in-hobart-marketed-as-cosy-studio-no-plumbing-included', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-17 03:24:05', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (459, 'Australians Now Holding ‘No Talk Tuesdays’ for Mental Clarity', 'It’s not antisocial—it’s self-care with noise cancellation.', 'In the land of “no worries,” it turns out a little enforced silence is the new form of self-care. A growing number of Australians—especially office workers and overwhelmed parents—are embracing “No Talk Tuesdays.” That’s right: an entire day of saying absolutely nothing unless it’s legally or emotionally required.\n\nPopularised on TikTok and Reddit, the movement promotes a weekly detox from mindless small talk, meetings that should’ve been emails, and co-workers who start every sentence with “Just quickly…”\n\nThe background? Post-pandemic burnout, digital fatigue, and the creeping horror of 24/7 Slack culture. Aussies are realising that not every thought needs to be voiced—and sometimes silence really is golden (and billable).\n\nCompanies are slowly catching on. Some workplaces now offer “quiet hours,” and schools are trialling optional verbal participation days. Unsurprisingly, productivity went up, passive aggression went down, and Karen from accounting finally got some peace.\n\nThe trend is also sparking debate. Critics say it’s just another Band-Aid over toxic hustle culture. Supporters say it’s the first time their brain’s been quiet since 2007.\n\nWhatever your view, No Talk Tuesdays are having a moment. Just don’t talk about it… on a Tuesday.\n\nSources: Pedestrian.TV, ABC Life, Triple J Hack – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'australians-now-holding-no-talk-tuesdays-for-mental-clarity', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 12:12:27', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (460, 'Firefighters Rescue Man from Public Toilet Wall Cavity in Adelaide', 'He was looking for privacy. He got plumbing and paramedics instead.', 'It’s a tale as old as time—or at least as old as plumbing gone wrong. Firefighters in Adelaide were called to a public toilet block overnight, where they found a man trapped inside the wall. Yes, inside the actual cavity between two tiled surfaces, wedged in like a rogue tile himself.\n\nThe man, reportedly in his 40s, was heard calling for help by an unlucky passer-by doing their business, who initially thought it was a prank—or an existential crisis echo. Emergency services arrived and spent over an hour cutting through the wall with saws, hammers, and, presumably, quiet disbelief.\n\nAuthorities are still working out how exactly the man got in there, though police confirmed he was “not authorized” to be within the structure. Translation: this wasn’t a maintenance worker with a bad map. Speculation ranges from break-in gone wrong to failed ghosting attempt.\n\nThis isn’t Adelaide’s first flirtation with bizarre public restroom drama, but it’s certainly among the more spatially challenging. As housing prices rise and rental supply drops, some joked that “toilet walls” might be the next property frontier. Others just want their taxpayer-funded toilets to stop doubling as escape rooms.\n\nThe man was extracted with “minor injuries and maximum embarrassment,” then taken to hospital for assessment—and probably a very awkward debrief.\n\nNo charges yet, but plenty of questions. Chief among them: Why? Followed closely by How? And finally, Did he flush first?\n\nSources: ABC News, 9News Adelaide, The Advertiser – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'firefighters-rescue-man-from-public-toilet-wall-cavity-in-adelaide', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-16 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 12:05:29', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (461, 'Dutton Accuses PM of ‘Energy Hypocrisy’—Forgets His Own Coal Selfie', 'When your memory is as selective as your energy plan.', 'Peter Dutton has taken aim at Prime Minister Anthony Albanese, accusing him of “energy hypocrisy” for spruiking renewables while energy prices remain sky-high. It’s an attack that might’ve landed—if not for the internet reminding everyone of Dutton’s 2019 photo-op literally hugging a chunk of coal like it owed him money.\n\nIn Parliament, Dutton lambasted the Labor government’s green energy push, claiming Australians are “paying the price for ideology.” Albanese fired back by quoting Dutton’s own words from a few years ago—when he championed coal exports and dismissed climate warnings as “alarmist theatre.”\n\nBackground: Energy prices are volatile post-COVID and post-Ukraine war, and both parties are playing political ping-pong over who stuffed it up worse. Labor has promised billions in renewable infrastructure, but timelines are lagging, and voters aren’t seeing price relief.\n\nContextually, this isn’t about power bills—it’s about power itself. Dutton is trying to frame Albanese as all slogan, no socket. But the Coalition’s climate baggage is harder to shake than a summer blackout.\n\nLatest update: Dutton’s coal-loving past is trending again. One meme shows him with the caption: “Cleanskin critic. Carbon-dated receipts.” And just like that, the fossil-fuel mudslinging continues—ironically, powered by the internet.\n\nSources: ABC News, SMH, The Guardian AU – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'dutton-accuses-pm-of-energy-hypocrisy-forgets-his-own-coal-selfie', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 12:11:21', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (462, 'Indonesia Warns Australia on Deportations Again—‘This Is Getting Rude’', 'Apparently diplomacy shouldn’t feel like a surprise eviction notice.', 'Indonesia has officially warned Australia—again—to stop sending deportees back without consultation, calling the recent incident involving a former detainee “deeply disrespectful.” The Indonesian foreign ministry didn’t mince words, saying Canberra’s behaviour is “increasingly out of step with diplomatic norms.”\n\nThis isn’t the first clash. Australia has deported several Indonesian nationals in recent months, some with criminal histories, without prior notification. Jakarta’s getting fed up—and let’s be real, they’re not wrong.\n\nBackground: While Australia has the legal right to deport non-citizens who commit crimes, the consistent lack of coordination has turned this into a cross-border soap opera. Indonesia’s been lodging formal complaints for over a year. It’s like ghosting, but with international consequences.\n\nContext: With regional relations already tense over defence, spying, and Dutton’s recent gaffe about Russian military bases in Southeast Asia, the last thing anyone needs is bureaucratic rudeness. But here we are—Australia chucking bodies across borders like unwanted parcels.\n\nLatest update: The Albanese government has issued a vague “we’ll look into it” statement, which Jakarta has politely translated as: “You’ve got to be kidding.” Southeast Asian diplomacy 101—don’t insult your neighbour while asking for trade favours.\n\nSources: ABC Asia, Jakarta Post, SBS News – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'indonesia-warns-australia-on-deportations-again-this-is-getting-rude', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-17 23:36:30', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (463, 'AFL Coach Blames Full Moon for Team’s Loss', 'Forget tactics—it’s werewolves and vibes now.', 'In one of the more... celestial press conferences in recent memory, an AFL coach has blamed his team’s humiliating loss on the full moon. Not tactics, not injuries, not the 37-point margin—but the moon. Yep, the big glowing ball in the sky apparently interfered with hand-passing.\n\nCoach Greg Bellingham of the Westvale Hawks fronted the media after a catastrophic showing against the Coburg Comets and offered this pearl: “The boys were off. You could feel it—restless, distracted. Must’ve been the full moon.”\n\nNaturally, the internet reacted with cosmic speed. “Mercury’s in Gatorade again,” joked one fan. Another said, “Coach should try blaming Venus retrograde next week.”\n\nBackground: The Hawks have had a rough season, with two wins, seven losses, and a midfield that forgets which end is theirs. But blaming celestial bodies is a bold new frontier in post-match deflection.\n\nContext: Coaches are under pressure, and excuses are evolving. Where once you’d hear about \"unlucky bounces\" or \"umpiring inconsistencies,\" now it\'s planetary alignment. Maybe next round someone will blame the tides, or bad vibes from the team’s group chat.\n\nLatest update: Players are reportedly amused, while fans are calling for less astrology and more strategy. The full moon isn’t commenting—probably too busy ruining someone else’s weekend.\n\nSources: Herald Sun, AFL.com.au, Triple M Sport – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'afl-coach-blames-full-moon-for-teams-loss', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 13:06:48', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (464, 'Sydney’s Beaches Close as Toxic Foam Washes Ashore', 'Mother Nature’s version of bubble wrap—but gross and potentially lethal.', 'Sydney’s iconic beaches just got a grim makeover as thick layers of toxic foam rolled in from the ocean like nature’s worst bubble bath. Bondi, Coogee, and Maroubra have all been temporarily closed after authorities detected chemical-laced sea foam stretching across the sand.\n\nSurfers were the first to report the issue—because nothing says “gnarly wave” like a frothy sludge with the stench of dead fish and despair. Officials from NSW Environment Protection Authority confirmed the foam likely came from industrial runoff, stormwater pollution, and “a perfect storm of environmental neglect.”\n\nBackground: Heavy rains earlier this week flushed all manner of urban sins into Sydney Harbour and beyond. Combine that with ocean turbulence, and voilà—Australia’s east coast gets a whipped topping of toxicity.\n\nContext: This isn’t the first time Sydney’s beaches have suffered the sins of inland runoff, but it’s certainly one of the grosser ones. Locals are rightly furious that multi-million-dollar suburbs can’t even guarantee foam-free swimming. Climate activists are calling it “a warning from the sea.” Instagrammers are calling it “ruined content.”\n\nLatest update: Clean-up crews are working fast, while swimmers are being told to stay out of the water. If you needed a metaphor for environmental mismanagement, look no further than Bondi—now with extra suds.\n\nSources: ABC News, SMH, Guardian AU – April 16, 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'sydneys-beaches-close-as-toxic-foam-washes-ashore', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 18:26:20', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (465, 'Doctors Say Aussie Kids Now Have Worse Posture Than Their iPads', 'We’re raising a generation of question marks—literally.', 'In tragic but unsurprising news, Australian children now officially have worse posture than the devices they’re glued to. Pediatric physiotherapists are warning that the next generation might grow up shaped like parentheses.\n\nThe Australian Physiotherapy Association released new data showing a dramatic rise in “tech neck,” spinal compression, and “forward head syndrome” among kids under 14. One specialist said, “Some kids are so slouched their backpacks are wearing them.”\n\nBackground: Blame remote learning, endless screen time, and schools cutting back on sport to make room for “life skills” like coding. Kids are spending up to 8 hours a day hunched over devices. At this rate, playgrounds may soon be replaced by chiropractor clinics.\n\nContext: This isn’t just a physical health crisis—it’s also psychological. Poor posture affects breathing, mood, and confidence. Teachers say students slump not just from habit, but from stress, screen fatigue, and TikTok burnout.\n\nLatest update: Doctors are calling for urgent national campaigns on posture health. Meanwhile, one school in WA has started daily “spine breaks” where students are told to stand, stretch, and briefly pretend they aren’t 70-year-old accountants.\n\nSources: News.com.au, SBS Health, ABC Radio – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'doctors-say-aussie-kids-now-have-worse-posture-than-their-ipads', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-05-02 23:59:27', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (466, 'ASX Surges—Investors Cheer, Everyone Else Still Broke', 'Markets rise, wages stay flat. Capitalism remains undefeated.', 'The ASX just posted its best day in months, with shares jumping 2.1% after a wave of upbeat corporate earnings and the RBA hinting it may stop raising interest rates. Champagne flowed on trading floors. Meanwhile, average Australians asked: “Can I invest in bread?”\n\nMajor banks, mining giants, and tech stocks all soared—meaning portfolio-holders are smiling while renters and mortgage slaves are wondering how that helps them afford milk. BHP alone added $4.5 billion to its market cap today. ASX CEO Damien Roche declared it “a sign of resilience.” Others called it “another episode of Rich People Win Again.”\n\nBackground: Inflation is easing, but cost-of-living pressures aren’t. Real wages are still struggling to keep pace, and essential goods remain eye-wateringly expensive. But none of that matters if you’re holding a diversified ETF, apparently.\n\nContext: The growing disconnect between stock market performance and actual economic wellbeing is reaching parody levels. Investors say “things are looking up,” while 40% of Australians say “the only thing going up is my rent.”\n\nLatest update: Financial analysts say the rally may continue if global markets hold steady. For now, it’s great news for the ASX—and absolutely no one who shops at Aldi.\n\nSources: AFR, The Australian, ABC Business – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'asx-surges-investors-cheer-everyone-else-still-broke', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-25 13:48:54', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (467, 'MAFS Spin-Off Announced: ‘Divorce Island’ Coming Soon', 'Love dies, ratings soar—welcome to television, folks.', 'Just when you thought reality TV couldn’t sink any lower, Channel Nine has announced Divorce Island—a new spin-off of Married At First Sight, where couples go to “reassess their connection” or, more realistically, explode on national television.\n\nThe premise? Previously “married” MAFS couples are flown to a tropical island to decide if they’ll stay together—or officially uncouple in a ratings-fuelled blaze of passive-aggression. Think Love Island meets Family Court, with cocktails and crying.\n\nProducers are promising “a raw, unfiltered look at love’s breaking point,” which in MAFS language means: screaming, walk-offs, and somebody hurling a plate of oysters while muttering about emotional growth.\n\nBackground: MAFS has dominated Australian screens for years with its mix of contrived vows, wine-throwing, and subtle psychological warfare disguised as therapy. This spin-off signals the franchise’s evolution—from fake weddings to messy breakups, all with ad breaks.\n\nContext: TV critics say it reflects Australia’s obsession with conflict-as-entertainment. Psychologists say it reflects something much darker. Either way, we’ll all be watching.\n\nLatest update: Casting is already underway, and Channel Nine has teased that “several iconic couples” will return. No word yet if a real therapist will be on the island—or just a producer with a clipboard and a chaos quota.\n\nSources: Pedestrian.TV, News.com.au, TV Tonight – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'mafs-spin-off-announced-divorce-island-coming-soon', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 15:23:25', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (468, 'Brisbane Garage Sells for $700K—No Electricity, No Shame', 'You wanted a dream home. You got a parking space.', 'A single-car garage in inner Brisbane has just sold for $700,000, boasting no plumbing, no power, and no regard for basic human dignity. The listing called it “a rare opportunity”—which, to be fair, it was: a rare opportunity to be mugged by the housing market in broad daylight.\n\nThe garage sits on 89 square metres of cracked concrete, wedged between two renovated homes. There’s no bedroom, no bathroom, and only “potential” scrawled across every inch like graffiti made of desperation.\n\nBackground: Brisbane’s property boom is the latest symptom of Australia’s runaway housing crisis. Investors are snatching up anything with land—even sheds, garages, and cursed plots with “demolition orders pending.”\n\nContext: Locals are fuming. Young families are priced out of the suburbs they grew up in, while real estate agents describe literal storage units as “urban chic.” Online reactions were swift and savage: “At least it’s cheaper than Sydney” became both the punchline and the tragedy.\n\nLatest update: The unnamed buyer is rumoured to be a developer—but for now, the garage remains locked, lonely, and somehow worth more than the national median income. If this isn’t rock bottom, it’s at least a concrete slab close to it.\n\nSources: Brisbane Times, Courier Mail, Domain – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'brisbane-garage-sells-for-700k-no-electricity-no-shame', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-17 03:24:30', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (469, 'Australians Booking Fake Wellness Retreats to Just Sleep Alone', 'Turns out peace and quiet is the real luxury.', 'Forget hot yoga and raw juice cleanses—Australia’s latest wellness trend is booking fake retreats just to lie down in silence away from literally everyone. Hotels and “eco lodges” across the country are seeing a spike in solo stays booked under the banner of self-care, but guests admit they’re there for one thing: naps without interruption.\n\nThese aren’t group meditations or forest hikes. These are \"wellness retreats\" in name only, where overworked professionals check in, turn off their phones, and pretend they’re doing breathwork while actually watching Netflix in a robe.\n\nBackground: Post-pandemic burnout and rising cost-of-living stress have left Aussies desperate for psychological escape. But instead of therapy, they’re opting for isolation—disguised as something wholesome and hashtag-worthy.\n\nContext: It’s a brilliant hustle. Hosts slap on words like “mindful”, “detox”, and “retreat,” and charge $800 a night for a glorified nap cave. Guests happily pay it to avoid their kids, coworkers, and the news cycle.\n\nLatest update: Travel agents report the trend is expanding to fake yoga weekends, pretend writers’ retreats, and silent hiking tours that feature no actual hiking. The real luxury now? Unbothered, horizontal solitude.\n\nSources: Broadsheet, Guardian AU, SBS Life – April 16, 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'australians-booking-fake-wellness-retreats-to-just-sleep-alone', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 01:45:06', 22);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (470, 'Two Kangaroos Disrupt Live Weather Report—Steal the Spotlight', 'It’s their land. We’re just filming awkward promos on it.', 'Move over meteorologist, nature had other plans. During a live weather cross in regional Victoria, two kangaroos stole the show—bounding across the frame mid-report and then proceeding to have a full-blown sparring session on national TV.\n\nThe chaos unfolded during Channel 7’s afternoon news, as the on-site presenter was trying to explain the week’s rainfall outlook. Enter two muscular marsupials, stage left, who promptly turned the segment into Skippy vs. Skippy: Civil War. Punches were thrown. Dust was kicked. The nation rejoiced.\n\nThe weatherman tried to keep going, but even he gave up mid-sentence, declaring, “I don’t think anyone’s listening to me now.” Correct. Viewers flooded social media, declaring it “the most Australian forecast ever.” One tweet read: “Finally, a fight on air that wasn’t between politicians.”\n\nBackground: Kangaroo sightings during outdoor broadcasts aren’t rare, but this one had perfect comedic timing—and choreography. Wildlife experts say this was typical “boxing behaviour” between two males. Internet users say it was typical “ratings gold.”\n\nContext: In an election season where every second segment is about housing or interest rates, the country was desperate for a break. And two fighting kangaroos during the rain forecast? That\'s the kind of unscripted serotonin we needed.\n\nLatest update: The video’s gone viral, with international headlines calling it “peak Aussie energy.” Channel 7 has already uploaded the raw clip to YouTube. As for the kangaroos? Unavailable for comment, likely signing a deal with Netflix.\n\nSources: Channel 7, ABC News, Twitter Xplosion – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'two-kangaroos-disrupt-live-weather-report-steal-the-spotlight', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 19:07:25', 15);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (471, 'Greens Propose Free Public Transport—Boomers Say ‘Back in My Day…’', 'Because walking uphill both ways builds character, apparently.', 'The Greens have announced a bold new policy push: free public transport nationwide, arguing it’ll cut emissions, cost-of-living pressures, and car dependency. Naturally, reactions were mixed—young Aussies cheered, while boomers nationwide simultaneously whispered, “Back in my day we walked.”\n\nSenator Mehreen Faruqi fronted the proposal, calling it “climate action that makes everyday life better.” The plan would see trams, trains, buses and ferries made fare-free—funded by fossil fuel royalties and a rework of infrastructure priorities.\n\nBackground: Australia’s public transport systems are notoriously underfunded outside major cities, with regional areas often relying on buses that run once a week (on full moons only). Critics have long said ticket costs punish the poorest.\n\nContext: As the cost of living continues to spiral and young people ditch cars due to cost, the idea of free public transport is gaining steam globally. But back home, it’s also sparking generational warfare. “Nothing’s free,” grumbled one Herald Sun columnist. “And anyway, what happened to walking?”\n\nLatest update: Labor has dismissed it as “fantasy budgeting,” while the Coalition called it “a distraction from real issues”—which is a bold statement from the party still debating nuclear submarines for 2045. Meanwhile, TikTok is already full of Gen Z videos dubbing it the “Trainfluencer Revolution.”\n\nSources: Guardian AU, ABC News, Crikey – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'greens-propose-free-public-transport-boomers-say-back-in-my-day', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-05-03 12:46:56', 14);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (472, 'NZ Tourism Ads Take Swipe at Aussie Beaches—‘Ours Don’t Bite’', 'Shots fired—with sunscreen and sarcasm.', 'New Zealand’s tourism board has launched a cheeky new campaign—and it’s got Australian beach culture squarely in its crosshairs. The tagline? “Visit NZ: Our Beaches Don’t Bite.” Yep, a not-so-subtle jab at Australia’s long list of toothy marine life and recent toxic foam incidents.\n\nThe ad, released online and on international TV, shows crystal-clear Kiwi waters with a narrator gently trolling: “No jellyfish. No crocs. No foam. Just the sound of waves and sheep chewing grass nearby.” Oof.\n\nBackground: NZ’s tourism sector is bouncing back post-COVID and aiming to lure cautious travellers—especially Aussies—away from Bondi and Noosa. They’re targeting safety, serenity, and smugness.\n\nContext: Australia has had a rough few months PR-wise—deadly shark sightings, beach closures, and now environmental alerts. NZ saw an opening and took the bait. Tourism Australia hasn’t responded directly, but insiders say they’re “not thrilled.”\n\nLatest update: The ad’s gone viral in both countries. Some Aussies are laughing, others threatening to paddleboard to New Zealand out of spite. Meanwhile, Kiwi tourism bosses are popping champagne made from glacier melt.\n\nSources: Stuff NZ, News.com.au, 1News – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'nz-tourism-ads-take-swipe-at-aussie-beaches-ours-dont-bite', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-17 09:58:08', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (473, 'Teen Cricket Sensation Debuts, Already Has Sponsorship Deal', 'Bat in one hand, brand deal in the other. Modern sport in a nutshell.', 'Australia’s got a new sporting golden child, and he’s not even old enough to vote. 16-year-old pace bowler Taj Malik made his professional cricket debut for Victoria this week—bowling at 143km/h, taking 3 wickets, and casually announcing a major sponsorship deal with Nike the same day.\n\nMalik, who’s still finishing Year 11, was scouted two years ago and has since become a viral highlight machine. His debut match saw him flatten two veteran batters and bowl one delivery that commentators described as “illegal under Geneva convention rules.”\n\nBackground: Australia’s cricket talent pipeline has been looking for fresh faces, especially ones that don’t come with sandpaper scandals or dodgy sledging records. Taj brings raw speed, a clean image, and more TikTok followers than Pat Cummins.\n\nContext: Brands are scrambling. Malik’s deal includes performance bonuses, a signature shoe, and media training to keep him from saying anything that might age poorly. Cricket Australia is already eyeing him for the national T20 squad.\n\nLatest update: He finished the match with 3/19 and didn’t even look winded. When asked what’s next, Taj said, “Back to school on Monday. I’ve got a maths test.” Iconic.\n\nSources: ESPNcricinfo, ABC Sport, The Age – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'teen-cricket-sensation-debuts-already-has-sponsorship-deal', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 18:21:41', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (474, 'Koalas Spotted in Urban Sydney—Locals Shocked They Still Exist', 'Turns out tree-hugging marsupials weren’t just a tourism myth.', 'In a rare twist of uplifting news, koalas were spotted in suburban Sydney, and locals reacted like they\'d just seen a unicorn at the servo. Two healthy-looking marsupials were seen clinging to gum trees in the leafy outer suburb of Wahroonga, sparking both joy and a wave of existential guilt.\n\nSightings were confirmed by the NSW Koala Strategy team, who said it was part of a surviving colony that had somehow avoided habitat destruction, traffic, bushfires, and general human incompetence.\n\nBackground: Australia’s koala population has been in catastrophic decline, with the cuddly icon now officially listed as endangered. Thanks to decades of land clearing, heatwaves, and roadkill, most Aussies assumed they\'d only see koalas on $1 coins and tourism brochures.\n\nContext: The surprise sighting has reignited calls for stronger protections, especially as developers circle remaining green corridors like it’s a buffet. Meanwhile, social media is flooded with Sydneysiders asking: “Do I have to stop building my deck now?”\n\nLatest update: The koalas were unharmed, relocated further into the bush, and are reportedly “not interested in interviews.” Conservation groups are begging the public to treat them like VIPs, not TikTok props.\n\nSources: ABC News, SMH, WIRES – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'koalas-spotted-in-urban-sydney-locals-shocked-they-still-exist', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 10:11:21', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (475, 'Experts Warn Aussies Are ‘Addicted to Multivitamins’', 'Why eat a vegetable when you can swallow ten shiny placebos?', 'Nutritionists are issuing a reality check for Australia: you’re not tired because of a vitamin deficiency—you’re tired because the world is exhausting. A new study from the University of Melbourne reveals Australians are now spending $1.7 billion a year on multivitamins, despite most getting zero measurable benefit.\n\nApparently, popping a fistful of supplements each morning has become Australia’s new wellness ritual. Magnesium for sleep, B12 for focus, collagen for vibes. The only thing actually improving? Chemist Warehouse sales.\n\nBackground: Only 8% of participants in the study had any clinical deficiency. But 63% said they take vitamins daily, “just in case.” Researchers called it “nutritional overcompensation driven by capitalism and chronic anxiety.”\n\nContext: With wellness culture booming and influencers touting tablets like talismans, it’s no wonder people think a pill a day keeps their lifestyle choices at bay. Doctors say most of us would be better off with a banana and a nap.\n\nLatest update: Health authorities aren’t calling for a ban—but they are urging people to talk to their GP before treating themselves like test tubes. Until then, the multivitamin industrial complex remains unbothered, rich, and extremely well-marketed.\n\nSources: The Conversation, Guardian AU, SBS Life – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'experts-warn-aussies-are-addicted-to-multivitamins', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 12:02:17', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (476, 'Bunnings Launches DIY Funeral Kits—‘Because Why Not?’', 'Paint, plywood, and peace. All aisle 9.', 'In what might be the most Aussie retail moment since the $2 snag, Bunnings has quietly launched a DIY funeral kit, promising a “respectful and affordable send-off” for those who prefer tools over tradition.\n\nThe kit, available online and in select stores, includes a flat-pack coffin (assembly required), biodegradable burial options, and a tasteful urn with a chalkboard label. Optional add-ons include sausage sizzle catering and PowerPoint templates.\n\nBackground: Rising funeral costs and a shift toward non-traditional farewells have sparked demand for budget options. Bunnings saw a gap in the market—and like any good tradie, grabbed it with both calloused hands.\n\nContext: Aussies are increasingly planning their own farewells, skipping overpriced services and opting for DIY memorials, backyard wakes, and even self-written eulogies projected on a shed wall. Bunnings’ offering? Equal parts bleak and brilliantly on-brand.\n\nLatest update: The product has sparked fierce online debate. Some say it’s a tasteless cash grab. Others say, “Mate, it’s about time.” A Bunnings rep said, “We support customers at every stage of life—including the end.” Marketing tagline pending.\n\nSources: Pedestrian.TV, Guardian AU, Bunnings website – April 16, 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'bunnings-launches-diy-funeral-kits-because-why-not', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-05-04 08:03:53', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (477, 'Nicole Kidman’s New Role: Psychic Kangaroo Whisperer', 'It’s weird, it’s Aussie, and yes, it’ll probably win a Logie.', 'Just when you thought Nicole Kidman had played every character on Earth, she’s now set to star as a kangaroo psychic in an upcoming outback dramedy, Whispering Tails. Yes—Hollywood’s most serene forehead will be telepathically communing with roos.\n\nThe film, announced at a press junket in LA, follows an eccentric zoologist (Kidman) who discovers she can hear kangaroos’ inner thoughts after being struck by lightning during a bushfire evacuation. Critics are calling it “Lassie meets The Sixth Sense, but make it marsupial.”\n\nBackground: Australia’s film industry has seen a resurgence of local-themed, slightly unhinged scripts lately—blame the success of Bluey, budget cuts, and audiences craving chaos with heart.\n\nContext: Kidman’s casting is already making waves. Some animal rights groups are praising the awareness for wildlife trauma post-bushfires. Others are just hoping the kangaroos aren’t CGI monstrosities.\n\nLatest update: Kidman told Variety, “It’s a story about healing, intuition, and hopping toward inner peace.” The film starts shooting in rural NSW this winter. No word yet if the kangaroos have agents.\n\nSources: Variety, Guardian AU, SBS News – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'nicole-kidmans-new-role-psychic-kangaroo-whisperer', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 15:11:57', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (478, 'Melbourne Listing Advertises ‘Vintage’ Carpet—AKA Mouldy', 'Nothing says character like 30-year-old stains.', 'A real estate listing in Melbourne’s north has gone viral for describing its stained, peeling, vaguely fungal carpet as “vintage floor feature.” The two-bedroom unit, priced at $850K, also proudly touts “character cracks” and “original bathroom fragrance.”\n\nThe photos show discoloured shag carpeting that looks like it survived both the 1970s and a minor flood. The listing agent claimed the home offers “retro charm for buyers with vision.” Twitter said it offers tetanus.\n\nBackground: Melbourne’s housing market remains unhinged, with buyers priced out of clean, modern homes and instead being sold vibes and imagination.\n\nContext: Real estate language has long been notorious—“cozy” means unlivable, “sun-drenched” means no blinds, and “fixer-upper” means get a priest. But this takes the moldy cake.\n\nLatest update: The listing has become a meme, with one commenter asking, “Does the carpet come with a biohazard suit?” The agent insists it’s already had two offers. Late capitalism wins again.\n\nSources: Domain, Reddit Australia, 3AW Melbourne – April 16, 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'melbourne-listing-advertises-vintage-carpet-aka-mouldy', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-17 15:59:52', 1);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (479, 'Aussies Ditch Dating Apps for Farmers Markets', 'Looking for love between avocados and artisanal bread.', 'Tired of ghosting, catfishing, and swiping on men holding fish, Aussie singles are now flocking to farmers markets to find love—in person, among the avocados. New dating trend: if he can pick a ripe tomato and make eye contact, he’s a keeper.\n\nThe trend, dubbed “organic flirting”, is gaining momentum, especially among 30-somethings who’ve declared war on apps. TikTok is filled with market meet-cutes: “He complimented my beetroot... now we’re engaged.”\n\nBackground: Studies show dating apps are leading to burnout, short-term connections, and unmatched expectations (and teeth). IRL meetups are making a comeback—slow, awkward, and refreshingly human.\n\nContext: Farmers markets offer the perfect low-stakes environment. You’re outside, there’s coffee, no pressure to look like your filtered selfies, and worst-case scenario, you leave with kale.\n\nLatest update: Some markets are embracing the trend, adding “Singles Hour” and live acoustic banjo to up the rom-com factor. Hinge is reportedly shaking.\n\nSources: ABC Life, Pedestrian.TV, Broadsheet – April 16, 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'aussies-ditch-dating-apps-for-farmers-markets', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 14:10:19', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (480, 'Man Trapped in Sydney Carwash After Misjudging Drive-Thru', 'He wanted a clean car. Got an accidental baptism.', 'A Sydney man found himself in a soapy standstill this morning after misjudging a drive-thru carwash entry, getting wedged between the roller brushes like a confused IKEA trolley. Emergency services were called when the man’s sedan stalled mid-cycle, trapping both car and ego under a torrent of foam, water jets, and humiliation.\n\nAccording to eyewitnesses (and one glorious dashcam video), the driver appeared to hesitate entering the auto-wash, then lunged forward at the wrong moment—effectively lodging his vehicle under a giant spinning sponge. “It was like watching someone try to parallel park into a blender,” said one bystander between chuckles.\n\nFirefighters were called in to manually override the system, halt the brushes, and extract the soggy sedan. The man, miraculously unharmed, was reportedly more concerned about “getting to work on time” than the industrial shampoo currently soaking into his floor mats.\n\nBackground: Sydney’s “touchless express” carwash chains are known for speed—but not forgiveness. Operators say this is the third carwash extraction this month, with growing calls for clearer signage and, let’s be honest, common sense.\n\nContext: In a city where time is money and clean cars are status symbols, drive-thru carwashes have become suburban pressure cookers. And while we all fear the awkward ATM shuffle, being stuck in a spinning lather tunnel takes public embarrassment to new heights.\n\nLatest update: The car was safely removed. The man declined media interviews but reportedly asked firefighters if they could “hose down the back seat while they were at it.”\n\nSources: 9News, Daily Telegraph, TikTok Carnage Central – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'man-trapped-in-sydney-carwash-after-misjudging-drive-thru', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-30 02:08:17', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (481, 'Parliament Debates If ‘Barbiecore’ Is a Valid Dress Code', 'Who knew democracy could come in pink sequins?', 'In a debate that somehow happened in a functioning democracy, Federal Parliament today spent an actual session arguing whether “Barbiecore” fashion qualifies as professional attire. The spark? An MP wore a hot-pink pantsuit with matching heels and a “Life in Plastic” brooch—and the chamber absolutely lost it.\n\nConservative MPs described the outfit as “an unserious distraction.” Greens MP Maxine Clarke clapped back: “You’re all just mad you didn’t think of fuchsia first.” She went on to argue that empowered, flamboyant femininity isn’t frivolous—it’s political. Cue applause from Tumblr and silent grimaces from Dutton’s bench.\n\nBackground: “Barbiecore” (think pink-on-pink power looks) has taken over red carpets, catwalks, and now—apparently—Canberra. Fueled by the Greta Gerwig film and a wave of feminist maximalism, it’s more than just fashion; it’s a cultural mood.\n\nContext: Parliament has strict dress expectations—suits, ties, beige—but no actual rules banning colour, whimsy, or Matel references. This moment isn’t just about fashion. It’s about who gets to look powerful, and what “serious” even means anymore.\n\nLatest update: No official ruling yet, but Speaker of the House reportedly said, “We’ll allow it… provided it’s paired with sensible shoes.” Barbie would never.\n\nSources: ABC News, The Guardian AU, Pedestrian.TV – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'parliament-debates-if-barbiecore-is-a-valid-dress-code', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 11:49:25', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (482, 'Aussie Backpacker Arrested in Bali for ‘Coconut Offence’', 'The crime? Cracking coconuts without a permit. Tourism is wild now.', 'An Australian backpacker has been arrested in Bali after allegedly attempting to smuggle six coconuts out of a protected temple site—because why just take selfies when you can violate spiritual property?\n\nThe 23-year-old man, from Brisbane, was detained at Ngurah Rai Airport with a backpack reportedly leaking coconut water. He told officials the fruit “looked cool” and he “thought they were free.” Balinese police did not agree.\n\nBackground: Coconut theft may sound minor, but in Bali, temple grounds are sacred—and removing items, even fruit, is considered deeply disrespectful and occasionally punishable under local laws.\n\nContext: This is just the latest in a long line of Aussies behaving badly in Bali—think scooters in temples, rooftop nudity, and drunken apologetic TikToks. Locals have had enough. Tourism boards are now trialling cultural awareness sessions before arrival.\n\nLatest update: The man faces a fine and possible deportation, pending further investigation. He has reportedly apologised and blamed “a miscommunication about fruit boundaries.” Australia’s consulate is… unsurprised.\n\nSources: Jakarta Post, SBS News, 9News – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'aussie-backpacker-arrested-in-bali-for-coconut-offence', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-17 03:24:54', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (483, 'Netball Australia to Introduce VAR—Yes, Really', 'Because slow-mo drama isn’t just for soccer anymore.', 'In a move that has players confused and fans mildly terrified, Netball Australia has announced it will introduce Video Assistant Referees (VAR) in the upcoming national league season. That’s right—netball now joins the ranks of soccer, cricket, and unnecessarily complicated officiating.\n\nThe new system will allow umpires to review contentious calls like footwork, contact, and goalpost interference. And yes—even obstruction calls could now go to the big screen, meaning we’re one step closer to netball turning into courtroom drama with Lycra.\n\nBackground: The decision comes after a string of controversial calls last season, including a grand final that ended with what many called “phantom contact” in the final seconds. Netball bosses say VAR will “ensure fairness and integrity.” Players say it might “make games last three hours.”\n\nContext: Purists are fuming. Netball’s charm has always been its fast pace and tight umpiring. Now we’re entering an era of pixel-by-pixel knee replays and laser-measured landing zones. What’s next—hawk-eye for fingernail infractions?\n\nLatest update: Trials begin next month, with live VAR debuting at the season opener. Coaches are brushing up on rules. Fans are bracing for outrage. And netball’s long-suffering umpires are quietly Googling “early retirement options.”\n\nSources: ABC Sport, Herald Sun, Fox Netball – April 16, 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'netball-australia-to-introduce-var-yes-really', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-29 03:39:12', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (484, 'WA Farmers Launch ‘Rain Dance TikTok’ Campaign', 'Because if bureaucracy can’t bring the rain, maybe trending hashtags can.', 'Desperate times call for interpretive dancing, apparently. Farmers in drought-stricken Western Australia have launched a TikTok campaign featuring choreographed “rain dances”—and yes, it’s exactly what it sounds like: gumboots, Akubras, and a lot of hip wiggling under cloudless skies.\n\nThe trend began when a wheat farmer from Kalannie posted a tongue-in-cheek clip titled “Summon the Skies”, featuring three generations of his family line-dancing in a paddock. It went viral overnight. Now, #RainDanceChallenge has over 4 million views—and a few hopeful sprinkles reported in Geraldton (coincidence?).\n\nBackground: Northern WA is battling brutal drought conditions, with rainfall at record lows and water restrictions tightening. Traditional methods—prayers, cloud seeding, Bureau of Meteorology grovelling—haven’t helped. Enter: TikTok.\n\nContext: While some are treating it as a joke, many farmers say it’s lifting spirits and raising awareness of rural struggles. Even the WA Premier got involved, posting his own cautious two-step under the caption “It’s worth a shot.”\n\nLatest update: The Bureau says no rain is forecast, but “community morale appears strong.” Climate change is still a problem. But for now, dancing in dust feels like an oddly hopeful act of defiance—and at least the algorithm is listening.\n\nSources: ABC Rural, The West Australian, TikTok – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'wa-farmers-launch-rain-dance-tiktok-campaign', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 12:01:25', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (485, 'New Study Finds Kombucha Doesn’t Cure Your Problems', 'It’s tea with a personality complex, not therapy in a bottle.', 'Bad news for the linen-wrapped kombucha cult: a new study has confirmed that fermented tea will not, in fact, solve your trauma, balance your chakras, or get your ex to text you back.\n\nResearchers from Monash University reviewed 37 kombucha-related health claims and found most benefits to be “anecdotal at best, wishful thinking at worst.” Yes, it’s got probiotics. No, it’s not a miracle in a mason jar.\n\nBackground: Kombucha has exploded in popularity over the past decade, riding the wellness wave alongside crystals, reiki, and oat milk that costs more than petrol. It’s now a $200 million industry in Australia alone.\n\nContext: The study isn’t saying kombucha is bad—just not magic. Claims that it boosts mood, improves digestion, clears skin, and prevents disease are mostly unsupported. In fact, excessive consumption can lead to bloating, headaches, and smugness.\n\nLatest update: Influencers are split. Some are doubling down, calling it “energy water.” Others are switching to kefir and claiming that’s the real cure. Doctors, meanwhile, recommend eating vegetables and drinking water. Boring, but accurate.\n\nSources: Monash University, SBS Food, The Conversation – April 16, 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'new-study-finds-kombucha-doesnt-cure-your-problems', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 02:46:24', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (486, 'Coles Offers Loyalty Points for Smiling at Checkout', 'Because nothing says savings like emotional labour.', 'In a bold attempt to gamify basic human decency, Coles is now trialling a system that gives customers bonus Flybuys points for smiling at checkout staff. Yes—retail has officially entered its dystopian performance review era.\n\nThe program uses facial recognition software at self-serve stations to detect smiles and award 10 points for “genuine joy.” No smile? No points. A smirk? Maybe five. Look too dead inside? You’ll still pay full price.\n\nBackground: The trial launched in select Melbourne stores under the guise of “enhancing customer-staff interactions and spreading positivity.” Critics say it’s emotional surveillance wrapped in a loyalty scheme.\n\nContext: Retail workers say it’s missing the point—“We don’t want smiles, we want pay rises.” Meanwhile, privacy advocates are raising alarms about biometric data collection. Coles insists the system is “secure, opt-in, and totally wholesome.” Sure, Jan.\n\nLatest update: The public is divided. Some love it (“Finally, a reason to fake it!”), others are furious (“What’s next—points for blinking?”). Either way, the checkout lane just got a whole lot weirder.\n\nSources: SMH, Guardian AU, Channel 9 – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'coles-offers-loyalty-points-for-smiling-at-checkout', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-05-03 08:52:07', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (487, 'Russell Crowe to Star in ‘The Bunnings Heist’—Yes, It’s Real', 'He’ll steal your heart... and your sausage sizzle.', 'Russell Crowe is back on screen and this time… he’s stealing snags and cordless drills? Yep—Crowe is set to star in The Bunnings Heist, a new Aussie crime-comedy based on a very fake but now very real urban legend involving a gang of tradies robbing a hardware megastore to fund their dream pub.\n\nThe film, written by Melbourne screenwriter Jacquie Laird, started as a satirical Twitter thread before being picked up by Netflix. Crowe reportedly signed on instantly, calling it “a beautiful, greasy, high-vis opera of mateship, mischief and Makita tools.”\n\nBackground: The script follows a retired brickie who recruits his old work crew to stage a Mission Impossible-style break-in at a Bunnings in suburban Frankston, using wheelbarrows, power tools, and sausages as distractions. It’s Ocean’s Eleven—if Ocean wore Crocs and yelled “oi” a lot.\n\nContext: Aussie cinema has been starved for a big, dumb, proudly local comedy. With Bluey ruling the kids’ world and The Dry handling the drama quota, a Crowe-led power tool caper is the chaos we didn’t know we needed.\n\nLatest update: Filming starts in June. Bunnings declined to comment but did say they “don’t condone theft, even fictional”—before cheekily adding that sausage sizzles will continue “with increased tongs security.”\n\nSources: ABC News, Guardian AU, Pedestrian.TV – April 16, 2025\n', 0, 'factabot', 'russell-crowe-to-star-in-the-bunnings-heist-yes-its-real', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-28 09:01:17', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (488, 'Sydney House Listed for $2M—Comes With Ghost and Disclaimer', 'Buy the dream. Haunting included free of charge.', 'Only in Sydney would you pay $2 million for a haunted, two-bed Victorian terrace with a legal disclaimer about spiritual activity. The listing in Newtown includes an official “non-human presence notice” and a clause absolving the seller of liability for “paranormal disturbances.”\n\nThe agent told media, “We’re just being transparent,” before adding that buyers are encouraged to “bring a priest or a strong nervous system.” The property features creaky floorboards, cold spots, and several TikToks of glowing orbs posted by previous tenants.\n\nBackground: Sydney’s real estate market is absurd on a good day. With prices surging again, even ghost-ridden homes are “opportunities for the right buyer.” Local folklore says the home was once a 19th-century funeral parlour—and definitely still has the vibes.\n\nContext: Disclosure laws in NSW don’t technically require sellers to report hauntings, but this agent decided to “lean into the niche.” They’ve marketed it as “a character home for spiritually adventurous creatives.” You know, gentrification—but with ghosts.\n\nLatest update: The first open house attracted over 70 visitors and one self-proclaimed psychic who said “the energy was chaotic but not malevolent.” The home is already under offer—because of course it is.\n\nSources: Domain, 9News, Broadsheet – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'sydney-house-listed-for-2m-comes-with-ghost-and-disclaimer', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-18 13:00:28', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (489, 'Australians Turning to ‘Solo Karaoke Therapy’ to Process Breakups', 'Cry-singing ‘Torn’ in a neon box is the new closure.', 'Move over journaling and wine-fuelled sobbing—Australia’s latest breakup recovery trend is “solo karaoke therapy,” where heartbroken people rent private booths just to scream-sing Adele and Olivia Rodrigo until they feel better.\n\nThe phenomenon has exploded across Sydney and Melbourne, with karaoke lounges reporting a 38% rise in bookings for one-person sessions. One venue even launched a “Dumped & Dangerous” playlist featuring exclusively torch songs and Taylor Swift’s entire discography.\n\nBackground: Psychologists say it actually works. “Singing taps into emotional release,” explains Dr Leah Kim. “Doing it loudly, in a safe, private space? That’s therapeutic catharsis, minus the awkward flatmate.”\n\nContext: Post-pandemic loneliness and digital breakups have created a new genre of heartbreak—silent, isolated, and algorithmically curated. Solo karaoke offers volume, release, and a weirdly empowering way to process rejection with backing vocals.\n\nLatest update: TikTok is flooded with #KaraokeTherapy clips, showing tear-streaked millennials belting “Total Eclipse of the Heart” alone in disco-lit rooms. Some venues now offer tissues, ice cream, and post-singling pep talks. Group therapy is out—power ballads are in.\n\nSources: SBS Life, The Guardian AU, ABC Everyday – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'australians-turning-to-solo-karaoke-therapy-to-process-breakups', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-04-24 10:27:10', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (490, 'Major Traffic Chaos After Alpaca Escapes Onto Freeway', 'He was fast. He was fluffy. And he did not stop for tolls.', 'Commuters on the M5 freeway in Sydney were hit with an unexpected delay this morning—not due to roadworks, not due to weather—but because an alpaca decided it was time for a leisurely trot through peak-hour chaos.\n\nThe escapee, a three-year-old named “Cinnamon,” broke free from a petting zoo en route to a kids\' party in Campbelltown. Instead of sticking to soft grass and pats from toddlers, Cinnamon chose full-lane domination, galloping down the middle lane like a long-necked stunt double in a Fast & Furious reboot.\n\nTraffic cameras caught the entire saga: cars swerving, hazard lights blinking, and one very confused tradie live-streaming the whole thing while muttering, “What the—nah, that’s not a kangaroo, bro.” Cinnamon eventually came to a standstill near the breakdown lane, where police and zoo staff coaxed her off the road using a banana and what may have been a Taylor Swift playlist.\n\nBackground: Alpaca-related traffic incidents are rare (thankfully), but not unheard of. Australia’s rural fringe meets suburbia in weird ways—and mobile petting zoos, increasingly popular for kids\' parties, are often the culprit. Because apparently no one thought, “What if the fluffy thing bolts into oncoming traffic?”\n\nContext: Drivers were stuck for over an hour, prompting social media to do what it does best: meme it into oblivion. #Alpacalypse trended nationally, with Cinnamon being hailed as “the hero we didn’t ask for but definitely deserve.”\n\nLatest update: Cinnamon is safe, the freeway has reopened, and the zoo has issued an apology. The kids’ party, according to sources, proceeded without her—but with an alpaca-shaped cake and a lot more supervision.\n\nSources: 9News, ABC Sydney, TikTok Dashcam Legends – April 16, 2025', 0, 'factabot', 'major-traffic-chaos-after-alpaca-escapes-onto-freeway', 'draft', 'images/news/bdf4b2e9-e41f-47c1-93ea-f721fdef3f0e.webp', NULL, '2025-04-17 00:00:00', '2025-05-06 18:59:19', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (491, 'Gen Z Gets the Vote—and the Cringe: Politicians Drop Diss Tracks and TikToks in Desperate Youth Grab', 'In a bid to woo Gen Z voters, Australian politicians are turning to TikTok, diss tracks, and memes. Because nothing says \'I\'m relatable\' like a 50-year-old attempting a viral dance.', 'When it comes to youth outreach, Australia’s politicians have apparently decided subtlety is for losers—and Gen Z deserves performance art. Enter Anthony Albanese attempting to “drop bars” on TikTok, Peter Dutton rebranding as a “relatable dad,” and even a rogue senator who thought a Fortnite dance would close the trust gap. The cringe is bipartisan, but the intention is clear: young people are voting, and the old guard is panicking.\n\nWith more than 400,000 Australians aged 18–24 enrolling to vote since January, the youth bloc is now politically powerful and predictably underestimated. So, instead of policies that might actually affect their lives—like climate action, housing affordability, or literally anything about student debt—we’re getting lip-sync battles, awkward raps, and Instagram Reels of pollies pointing at floating text bubbles like it’s 2020. And while the Greens have always been the default “cool aunt” at the barbecue, even they’ve started producing TikToks that feel like they were storyboarded by a committee of dads with LinkedIn Premium.\n\nBut here\'s the kicker: it’s not just embarrassing—it’s revealing. Politicians are treating young voters like a demographic to be seduced with memes rather than engaged with as citizens. It\'s policy cosplay, not politics. And Gen Z? They\'re not just watching—they’re stitching, dueting, and roasting every boomer dance step. Young voters are smart enough to smell a PR stunt sprayed with Lynx Africa from a kilometre away.\n\nThis week, the AEC confirmed a record-breaking enrolment rate of 90% for 18–24s, triggering a fresh wave of TikTok campaign “content” that includes a parody rap from a backbencher and a misguided “vibe check” post from Clive Palmer’s account (which we’re 99% sure was written by ChatGPT). The race is officially on, and so is the collective second-hand embarrassment.\n\nSources:\nABC News, Guardian Australia, SBS News, The Australian, AEC Media Releases', 0, 'factabot', 'gen-z-gets-the-vote-and-the-cringe-politicians-drop-diss-tracks-and-tiktoks-in-desperate-youth-grab', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:33', '2025-05-01 16:57:38', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (492, 'Hunter Region\'s Power Play: Coal, Wind, and Nuclear Dreams Collide in Election Showdown', 'The Hunter region becomes the battleground for Australia\'s energy future, with debates over coal closures, offshore wind farms, and ambitious nuclear proposals. It\'s like Game of Thrones, but with more power plants.', 'The Hunter’s political buffet just got a few extra spicy sides: fossil fuel feuds, offshore wind wars, and—because why not—nuclear pipe dreams. Labor’s Dan Repacholi (yes, the former Olympic shooter) is defending the coal-fired status quo with “realistic transition” talk, while independent challenger Steve Barnett is pitching wind turbines like Oprah giving out cars. And in a shock twist, a nuclear-curious micro party has entered the chat, because nothing says “clean energy future” like revisiting Chernobyl cosplay.\n\nThis election isn’t just about votes—it’s a full-blown ideological cage match. The Hunter electorate has been a coal stronghold for decades, fuelling jobs, politics, and more carbon than a Bunnings BBQ. But with offshore wind approvals floating around and coal mines facing their twilight years, the region is caught between past and future like a boomer trying to install TikTok.\n\nZooming out, the Hunter is a mini-Australia when it comes to the energy transition mess. Politicians are tossing around climate pledges while dragging their heels behind closed doors. Meanwhile, locals are stuck between wanting reliable jobs and not wanting their grandchildren to live in an oven. Nuclear’s entry into the debate isn’t policy—it’s posturing with radioactive flair.\n\nAnd just this week, community groups slammed both major parties for treating the electorate like a test lab. With voting set for early May, the Hunter is now the country\'s most awkward energy-themed reality show. Coming up next: who’ll get eliminated in the “net-zero but not really” challenge?\n\nSources: ABC News, Guardian Australia, Newcastle Herald, The Australian', 0, 'factabot', 'hunter-regions-power-play-coal-wind-and-nuclear-dreams-collide-in-election-showdown', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:33', '2025-04-23 12:01:03', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (493, 'Trump and Putin Set to Chat Ukraine: What Could Possibly Go Wrong?', 'In a move that\'s sure to be subtle and nuanced, Donald Trump plans direct talks with Vladimir Putin over Ukraine. Diplomatic delicacy, thy name is not Trump.', 'Just when you thought geopolitics couldn’t get more unhinged, Donald Trump casually announced he’d be “happy” to call Vladimir Putin if re-elected—because why not outsource diplomacy to a former reality TV star with a soft spot for dictators? In MAGA-land, calling the Kremlin is just a Tuesday.\n\nAccording to Trump, he\'d end the Ukraine war “in 24 hours” through sheer vibes and bravado, which in his brain probably means strong handshakes, weird compliments, and zero understanding of history. Meanwhile, Putin’s likely response is a polite smirk and an internal monologue of “free propaganda, thanks!”\n\nThis isn\'t diplomacy—it’s a Bond villain brunch. Trump’s track record includes withholding military aid for political favours (see: impeachment #1), praising authoritarian leaders, and suggesting NATO should “pay up or shut up.” So when he floats a chat with Putin, it’s less peace plan and more chaos TikTok.\n\nThe terrifying bit? Some Americans love it. Trump’s positioning himself as the anti-war candidate, forgetting we all watched Season 1 of his presidency. Meanwhile, Ukraine is still burning, and global leaders are side-eyeing this possible encore performance like it’s a sequel nobody asked for.\n\nThe latest twist? Trump told Time magazine that “Putin wouldn’t have dared invade Ukraine under me.” Which, if you ignore 2014 Crimea and basic facts, sounds great. Let’s hope the next call isn’t collect.\n\nSources: Time Magazine, BBC News, CNN, Politico', 0, 'factabot', 'trump-and-putin-set-to-chat-ukraine-what-could-possibly-go-wrong', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:33', '2025-04-21 06:36:11', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (494, 'Bells Beach Pro: Aussie Women Surf the Waves and the Pressure Ahead of WSL Cut', 'As the Rip Curl Pro kicks off, Australia\'s female surfers ride high hopes and higher waves, aiming to avoid the dreaded mid-season cut. Surf\'s up, stakes up.', 'The waves at Bells Beach are feral this week, but it’s not just the swell that’s peaking—so is the pressure. With the mid-season World Surf League cut looming, Aussie surf stars like Molly Picklum and Tyler Wright are charging not just for glory but for survival. It’s wipeout or win.\n\nTyler Wright, two-time world champ and ocean warrior, is paddling through both sets and stress, while Picklum’s consistency has made her the quiet killer on the tour. But let’s be real: the WSL’s mid-season cut is like The Bachelor for surfers—roses optional, career on the line.\n\nHere’s the drama: only the top 10 women survive the chop, making this week at Bells a salty Hunger Games. And no, it’s not just about talent. Judges, wave quality, even injury luck all come into play. One mistimed carve and it’s back to chasing local comps and influencer deals.\n\nBigger picture? Surfing’s trying to be the F1 of the ocean: sleek, elite, and ruthless. The WSL cut system is meant to sharpen the talent pool but has critics calling it unfair, especially for emerging surfers with no Red Bull sponsorship in sight.\n\nThis week’s early heats have already brought upsets and emotional exits. And for the Aussie women, it’s not just about podiums—it’s proving that the next gen can handle the heat, the hype, and the bureaucratic nonsense of professional surfing.\n\nSources: ABC Sport, Sydney Morning Herald, WSL.com, The Age', 0, 'factabot', 'bells-beach-pro-aussie-women-surf-the-waves-and-the-pressure-ahead-of-wsl-cut', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:33', '2025-05-03 07:53:26', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (495, 'Offshore Wind Farms Face Turbulence: Fishers and Tourists Say \'Not in My Ocean\'', 'Plans for offshore wind farms near Port Stephens hit choppy waters as local fishers and tourism operators push back. Renewable energy meets the NIMBY (Not In My Back Yard) brigade.', 'Turns out, Australia’s plan to save the planet might come with a side of seagull-flavoured outrage. Coastal communities from Gippsland to the Illawarra are throwing metaphorical sand at the government’s offshore wind rollout, with fishers, tour operators, and beach purists screaming a collective “Not in my backyard—or my ocean.”\n\nWhile Chris Bowen is waxing lyrical about “renewable zones” and energy independence, locals are hosting town hall dramas that make Married At First Sight look civilised. Fishers argue the turbines will mess with marine life, tourists fear the pristine views will turn into Blade Runner: Sea Edition, and some just want Canberra to stop doing things near their beach.\n\nBut here’s the plot twist: these are the same regions that politicians point to when they say we need to \"transition jobs\" and \"rebuild economies.\" It’s climate policy meets coastal real estate snobbery. And with the Coalition now positioning themselves as defenders of the ‘visual amenity,’ you know we’ve entered a bizarre alternate timeline.\n\nThis week, the Albanese government paused community consultation in the Hunter after locals crashed the session with handmade signs, heated rants, and possibly a conch shell of protest. Offshore wind? More like onshore drama.\n\nSources: ABC News, The Guardian, Sydney Morning Herald, Renew Economy', 0, 'factabot', 'offshore-wind-farms-face-turbulence-fishers-and-tourists-say-not-in-my-ocean', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:33', '2025-05-06 13:07:01', 11);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (496, 'Medicare Misinformation: Right-Wing Ad Accidentally Promotes Satirical Labor Video', 'A right-wing campaign ad intended to criticize Labor ends up promoting a satirical video warning about Medicare privatization. Oops—talk about shooting yourself in the foot.', 'A right-wing Facebook ad campaign aimed at roasting Labor’s Medicare reforms just accidentally did the opposite—by linking directly to a parody Labor video praising universal healthcare. Yes, someone spent actual money to send angry voters straight into a love letter to bulk billing.\n\nThe group behind the ad—“Australians for Medicare Accountability,” which sounds totally grassroots and definitely not a front for conservative donors—pushed out a clip with the warning “Labor\'s plan will ruin Medicare.” But the link they used? It redirected to Labor\'s own satirical skit starring a fake doctor and a very enthusiastic patient. Oops.\n\nThis is political advertising’s version of slipping on a banana peel while yelling “watch your step.” And while Meta scrambles to review the campaign, Labor’s digital team is probably cracking open some celebratory kombucha.\n\nIt’s a cautionary tale about the digital wild west of political ads. When half the electorate is already skeptical, and the other half is on TikTok, maybe don’t base your $20,000 ad buy on a dodgy hyperlink.\n\nLatest twist? The video’s views have now tripled, and Labor MP Mark Butler cheekily thanked his “unexpected collaborators” during a press interview. Irony level: Shakespearean.\n\nSources: Crikey, ABC News, Meta Ad Library, The Saturday Paper\n', 0, 'factabot', 'medicare-misinformation-right-wing-ad-accidentally-promotes-satirical-labor-video', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:33', '2025-04-21 02:09:07', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (498, '\'Big Boys\' Return: Jack and Danny Navigate Adulting in New Season', 'The beloved series \'Big Boys\' is back, with Jack and Danny facing dissertations and the daunting world of adulthood. Spoiler: adulting is hard.', 'Everyone’s favourite emotionally constipated flatmates are back, and yes—Big Boys Season 2 has finally dropped in Australia. Jack (played by Jack Rooke, the show’s creator) and Danny (Dylan Llewellyn, of Derry Girls fame) are still fumbling through life, grief, and hookup apps, except now they have student loans, unresolved trauma, and adulting to worry about. So basically: same chaos, just with higher stakes and lower bank balances.\n\nThe BAFTA-winning series charmed viewers last year with its mix of laddish banter and sudden emotional ambushes. Think of it as The Inbetweeners if someone gave them therapy and a pastel colour palette. Season 2 sees Jack working at a uni radio station while Danny tries his hand at theatre and dating—two activities he\'s equally unqualified for.\n\nBut behind the LOLs, the show’s still sneakily clever. It handles mental health, masculinity, and sexuality with a light touch and heavy relatability. It’s like being smacked with a feather duster full of feelings.\n\nThis week, SBS On Demand quietly dropped the full season, leading to a mini Twitter stampede from viewers ready to cry, laugh, and spiral. And honestly? The timing couldn’t be better. With Aussie streaming currently awash in bleak dramas and reboots, Big Boys is a warm, awkward hug we didn’t know we needed.\n\nSources: SBS On Demand, Guardian Australia, Pedestrian.TV, The Independent', 0, 'factabot', 'big-boys-return-jack-and-danny-navigate-adulting-in-new-season', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:33', '2025-05-02 08:54:09', 12);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (499, 'Boarded-Up Home Sparks Bidding War: Buyers Fight Over Fixer-Upper', 'A dilapidated, boarded-up property manages to trigger a bidding frenzy, proving once again that the Australian housing market is more chaotic than a reality show reunion.', 'Nothing screams “Australian housing crisis” quite like people fighting over a boarded-up dump with no kitchen, no bathroom, and no dignity. This week, a derelict Brisbane home—complete with crumbling walls and a garden best described as “feral”—sparked a bidding war and sold for nearly $1 million. Because who needs comfort when you have potential?\n\nThe three-bedroom carcass, located in a supposedly \"up-and-coming\" suburb, had been abandoned for years and needed so much work it should’ve come with a hard hat and a tetanus shot. But that didn’t stop investors and young couples from crawling over each other for a shot at the Aussie Dream™: owning land, even if it looks like a horror movie set.\n\nReal estate agents spun it like gold: “A renovator’s delight,” “prime for development,” and our favourite—“unique character.” Translation: haunted but zoned for a granny flat.\n\nIt’s the latest sign that the market has completely unhinged from reality. Supply’s tight, rates are high, and millennials are now calculating whether they can live inside a skip bin and call it equity. Housing affordability? Please. We’re in the Hunger Games now.\n\nThe kicker? The house sold for $200k over reserve. Which is great news—for the termites.\n\nSources: Domain, 9News, The Courier-Mail, RealEstate.com.au', 0, 'factabot', 'boarded-up-home-sparks-bidding-war-buyers-fight-over-fixer-upper', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:33', '2025-05-05 10:16:20', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (500, 'Bored of Bread? Aussie Bakeries Go Viral with Croissant Cheeseburgers', 'Move over cronuts—Australia’s latest carb craze is the croissant cheeseburger. It’s flaky, beefy, and bound to make your arteries scream.', 'If your arteries weren’t already on notice, Aussie bakeries are now slapping beef patties between buttery croissants—and somehow the internet can’t get enough. Welcome to the unholy union of French pastry and Macca’s energy: the croissant cheeseburger.\n\nThis Frankenstein of food was first spotted in Melbourne, where a hipster bakery decided that carbs alone weren’t chaotic enough. The croissant acts as the bun, the beef patty oozes over the edge, and the whole thing is typically crowned with pickles, melted cheese, and existential guilt.\n\nTikTok’s having a field day, of course. Videos of people biting into these flaky monstrosities are clocking millions of views, triggering both hunger and heated debates over cultural crimes against pastry. The French are reportedly traumatised.\n\nBut like all viral food trends, this one’s more about vibe than flavour. It’s not clear if anyone actually enjoys eating them, or if we’re all just pretending because it’s more photogenic than a regular burger and 200% more likely to get a like.\n\nAs of this week, bakeries in Sydney and Brisbane are joining the trend, with one shop selling out by 10am daily. So yes, we’ve officially hit peak foodie chaos. Gluten-free girlies, avert your eyes.\n\nSources: Broadsheet, Good Food, News.com.au, TikTok\n', 0, 'factabot', 'bored-of-bread-aussie-bakeries-go-viral-with-croissant-cheeseburgers', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:33', '2025-05-05 14:45:57', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (501, 'Gen Z Gets the Vote—and the Cringe: Politicians Drop Diss Tracks and TikToks in Desperate Youth Grab', 'In a bid to woo Gen Z voters, Australian politicians are turning to TikTok, diss tracks, and memes. Because nothing says \'I\'m relatable\' like a 50-year-old attempting a viral dance.', 'When it comes to youth outreach, Australia’s politicians have apparently decided subtlety is for losers—and Gen Z deserves performance art. Enter Anthony Albanese attempting to “drop bars” on TikTok, Peter Dutton rebranding as a “relatable dad,” and even a rogue senator who thought a Fortnite dance would close the trust gap. The cringe is bipartisan, but the intention is clear: young people are voting, and the old guard is panicking.\n\nWith more than 400,000 Australians aged 18–24 enrolling to vote since January, the youth bloc is now politically powerful and predictably underestimated. So, instead of policies that might actually affect their lives—like climate action, housing affordability, or literally anything about student debt—we’re getting lip-sync battles, awkward raps, and Instagram Reels of pollies pointing at floating text bubbles like it’s 2020. And while the Greens have always been the default “cool aunt” at the barbecue, even they’ve started producing TikToks that feel like they were storyboarded by a committee of dads with LinkedIn Premium.\n\nBut here\'s the kicker: it’s not just embarrassing—it’s revealing. Politicians are treating young voters like a demographic to be seduced with memes rather than engaged with as citizens. It\'s policy cosplay, not politics. And Gen Z? They\'re not just watching—they’re stitching, dueting, and roasting every boomer dance step. Young voters are smart enough to smell a PR stunt sprayed with Lynx Africa from a kilometre away.\n\nThis week, the AEC confirmed a record-breaking enrolment rate of 90% for 18–24s, triggering a fresh wave of TikTok campaign “content” that includes a parody rap from a backbencher and a misguided “vibe check” post from Clive Palmer’s account (which we’re 99% sure was written by ChatGPT). The race is officially on, and so is the collective second-hand embarrassment.\n\nSources:\nABC News, Guardian Australia, SBS News, The Australian, AEC Media Releases', 0, 'factabot', 'gen-z-gets-the-vote-and-the-cringe-politicians-drop-diss-tracks-and-tiktoks-in-desperate-youth-grab', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:39', '2025-04-18 02:16:08', 2);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (502, 'Hunter Region\'s Power Play: Coal, Wind, and Nuclear Dreams Collide in Election Showdown', 'The Hunter region becomes the battleground for Australia\'s energy future, with debates over coal closures, offshore wind farms, and ambitious nuclear proposals. It\'s like Game of Thrones, but with more power plants.', 'The Hunter’s political buffet just got a few extra spicy sides: fossil fuel feuds, offshore wind wars, and—because why not—nuclear pipe dreams. Labor’s Dan Repacholi (yes, the former Olympic shooter) is defending the coal-fired status quo with “realistic transition” talk, while independent challenger Steve Barnett is pitching wind turbines like Oprah giving out cars. And in a shock twist, a nuclear-curious micro party has entered the chat, because nothing says “clean energy future” like revisiting Chernobyl cosplay.\n\nThis election isn’t just about votes—it’s a full-blown ideological cage match. The Hunter electorate has been a coal stronghold for decades, fuelling jobs, politics, and more carbon than a Bunnings BBQ. But with offshore wind approvals floating around and coal mines facing their twilight years, the region is caught between past and future like a boomer trying to install TikTok.\n\nZooming out, the Hunter is a mini-Australia when it comes to the energy transition mess. Politicians are tossing around climate pledges while dragging their heels behind closed doors. Meanwhile, locals are stuck between wanting reliable jobs and not wanting their grandchildren to live in an oven. Nuclear’s entry into the debate isn’t policy—it’s posturing with radioactive flair.\n\nAnd just this week, community groups slammed both major parties for treating the electorate like a test lab. With voting set for early May, the Hunter is now the country\'s most awkward energy-themed reality show. Coming up next: who’ll get eliminated in the “net-zero but not really” challenge?\n\nSources: ABC News, Guardian Australia, Newcastle Herald, The Australian', 0, 'factabot', 'hunter-regions-power-play-coal-wind-and-nuclear-dreams-collide-in-election-showdown', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:39', '2025-04-18 00:53:39', 0);
