INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (507, 'Clive Palmer\'s Digital Blitz: $1.4 Million Spent to Trumpet Coal and Campaigns', 'Clive Palmer\'s Trumpet of Patriots party goes all-in online, spending over a million dollars on ads promoting coal and, presumably, himself. Because nothing says grassroots like a millionaire\'s ad spree.', 'Like a political NPC with unlimited gold coins, Clive Palmer is back—splashing $1.4 million in just three months on digital ads, mostly to tell us that coal is good, net zero is evil, and the only party worth trusting has his name all over it. Democracy? More like a browser-based billboard war.\n\nAccording to new AEC disclosures, Palmer’s United Australia Party is by far the top spender on online political ads, with most of that cash going into Facebook and YouTube. The ads range from fire-and-brimstone climate denial to AI-generated videos of Clive looking vaguely disappointed at wind turbines.\n\nPalmer’s strategy is blunt: flood the internet, skip the policy, and outshout everyone else with volume and cash. It’s not subtle. It’s not nuanced. But in a digital space where attention spans last six seconds, maybe subtlety’s overrated.\n\nZooming out, this is part of a worrying trend: ultra-rich candidates bypassing journalism and public debate to beam propaganda straight into your eyeballs. It\'s the political version of autoplaying YouTube ads, except you can’t skip—and the sound is always on.\n\nThis week, fact-checkers flagged multiple UAP ads for misleading claims, but the Electoral Commission confirmed that unless it breaks the law, they can’t touch it. So basically: facts optional, money talks, and Clive yells.\n\nSources: AEC Disclosures, ABC News, Guardian Australia, Meta Ad Library\n', 0, 'factabot', 'clive-palmers-digital-blitz-14-million-spent-to-trumpet-coal-and-campaigns', 'draft', 'images/news/c2fac369-034f-40f4-bbd4-f24c2a6a15fb.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:39', '2025-05-02 15:47:43', 3);
