INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (510, 'Bored of Bread? Aussie Bakeries Go Viral with Croissant Cheeseburgers', 'Move over cronuts—Australia’s latest carb craze is the croissant cheeseburger. It’s flaky, beefy, and bound to make your arteries scream.', 'If your arteries weren’t already on notice, Aussie bakeries are now slapping beef patties between buttery croissants—and somehow the internet can’t get enough. Welcome to the unholy union of French pastry and Macca’s energy: the croissant cheeseburger.\n\nThis Frankenstein of food was first spotted in Melbourne, where a hipster bakery decided that carbs alone weren’t chaotic enough. The croissant acts as the bun, the beef patty oozes over the edge, and the whole thing is typically crowned with pickles, melted cheese, and existential guilt.\n\nTikTok’s having a field day, of course. Videos of people biting into these flaky monstrosities are clocking millions of views, triggering both hunger and heated debates over cultural crimes against pastry. The French are reportedly traumatised.\n\nBut like all viral food trends, this one’s more about vibe than flavour. It’s not clear if anyone actually enjoys eating them, or if we’re all just pretending because it’s more photogenic than a regular burger and 200% more likely to get a like.\n\nAs of this week, bakeries in Sydney and Brisbane are joining the trend, with one shop selling out by 10am daily. So yes, we’ve officially hit peak foodie chaos. Gluten-free girlies, avert your eyes.\n\nSources: Broadsheet, Good Food, News.com.au, TikTok\n', 0, 'factabot', 'bored-of-bread-aussie-bakeries-go-viral-with-croissant-cheeseburgers', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 00:53:39', '2025-04-18 00:53:39', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (511, 'Pilot\'s Fatal Plot: Lawn Mower Death Scene \'Manipulated\' in Murder Case', 'An air force pilot is accused of turning a tragic lawn mower accident into a murder scene. CSI: Backyard Edition.', 'Buckle up for the most unhinged true-crime plot this side of Midsomer Murders. Queensland pilot Gregory Lynn is now standing trial for allegedly murdering two elderly campers, Russell Hill and Carol Clay, and trying to cover it up with a scene so clumsy it could’ve been a deleted scene from CSI: Outback. The prosecution says Lynn staged a lawn mower “accident” to make the deaths look like a bushland mishap. Spoiler: it didn’t fool anyone.\n\nLynn, 57, was camping near the remote Wonnangatta Valley in 2020 when Hill and Clay vanished. The lovers had been secretly rendezvousing for years (because why should teenagers have all the sneaky romance fun?) and were last heard from via a crackly radio call. Their charred campsite was later discovered—along with Lynn’s explanation that they died in a tragic lawn mower blaze gone wrong. Yes, really.\n\nFast forward to this week: prosecutors allege Lynn not only killed the pair, but also tried to torch their remains, burn their belongings, and stage the whole scene to look like an unfortunate machinery accident. His defence? That there was a “struggle” and things just spiralled into accidental arson. As you do.\n\nZooming out, this isn’t just a bushland murder mystery—it’s now one of the most bizarre and high-profile trials in Victoria. A retired Jetstar captain accused of double murder, a love affair turned tragedy, and a crime scene more suspicious than a politician’s tax return.\n\nLatest update: forensic experts testified the scene had been “manipulated,” calling out inconsistencies between burn patterns, object placement, and Lynn’s story. The trial continues, but one thing’s clear—this plot has more twists than a garden hose in summer.\n\nSources: ABC News, The Age, 9News, Guardian Australia', 0, 'factabot', 'pilots-fatal-plot-lawn-mower-death-scene-manipulated-in-murder-case', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-04-21 11:03:11', 9);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (512, 'Albanese\'s $1K Tax Tease: Election Bribe or Generous Gesture?', 'PM promises a $1,000 tax deduction for every Aussie worker. Because who doesn\'t love a pre-election sugar hit?', 'Anthony Albanese is playing Oprah with taxpayer money again—except this time, instead of handing out cars, he’s dangling a $1,000 tax cut in front of voters like a shiny pre-election chew toy. The cash sweetener was unveiled ahead of the May budget, but let’s be honest: it smells less like fiscal policy and more like campaign cologne.\n\nThe PM says it’s “cost-of-living relief” for middle-income earners. Critics say it’s “vote-buying in a discount suit.” Meanwhile, Peter Dutton has resorted to economic fan fiction, accusing Labor of being simultaneously too generous and not generous enough.\n\nThis isn’t Labor’s first flirtation with tax theatrics. The government scrapped the Morrison-era Stage 3 cuts earlier this year, then rebranded them with slightly more progressive optics—but not enough to scare the mortgage belt. Now, this $1K handout is being sold as targeted relief, not a bribe. Just like politicians always “listen” during community consultation sessions.\n\nZooming out, it\'s a masterclass in political theatre. Dangle cash. Blame inflation on everyone else. Smile for Sunrise. Rinse, repeat.\n\nLatest? The Coalition hasn’t ruled out matching the tax cut, which means we might be entering a delightful bidding war where the only winner is whichever party can most effectively weaponise Treasury spreadsheets.\n\nSources: ABC News, The Australian, Guardian Australia, 7News\n', 0, 'factabot', 'albaneses-1k-tax-tease-election-bribe-or-generous-gesture', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-04-23 12:46:47', 7);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (513, 'Katy Perry\'s Space Odyssey: Pop Star Joins All-Women Rocket Launch', 'Katy Perry blasts off on an all-female spaceflight. From pop charts to star charts.', 'Because nothing says “girl power” like launching a pop star into low Earth orbit, Katy Perry is now strapped in—metaphorically—for an upcoming all-female space mission organised by Blue Origin. Yes, that Blue Origin. Yes, Jeff Bezos\' Blue Origin. Because obviously, Firework was a foreshadowing.\n\nPerry joins a star-studded astronaut roster including aviator Gopi Thotakura and entrepreneur Ed Dwight (the first Black astronaut candidate). While Perry isn’t technically flying the rocket (yet), she’s been vocal in her support for the historic launch and has been jokingly prepping “zero-gravity eyeliner” and space-themed setlists on socials.\n\nThis is Blue Origin’s seventh crewed mission, and its first to feature only women. Bezos, who previously shot Captain Kirk into space, seems hell-bent on turning the cosmos into a billionaire-sponsored Comic-Con.\n\nCulturally, it’s a win for visibility. Scientifically? Eh, it’s a suborbital selfie at best. But it’s hard to hate on a space trip that blends STEM, spectacle, and sequins. After all, if tech bros get to cosplay astronauts, why can’t pop stars?\n\nLaunch is scheduled for early May, pending safety checks and influencer schedules. Whether Perry\'s headed to the stratosphere or just stealing the photo op, one thing\'s certain: NASA is definitely side-eyeing this.\n\nSources: ABC News, News.com.au, Reuters, Variety', 0, 'factabot', 'katy-perrys-space-odyssey-pop-star-joins-all-women-rocket-launch', 'draft', 'images/news/385f9145-2551-43c6-85b3-1fa606f8f152.jpg', NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-05-03 07:51:25', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (514, 'Willie Rioli Takes Leave Amid Online Abuse After Instagram Post', 'Port Adelaide star steps back from the game following a storm of racist comments. Social media strikes again.', 'Port Adelaide star Willie Rioli has stepped away from the game after a barrage of online abuse that followed a controversial Instagram post—because apparently, scoring goals comes with a side of racial vilification now. Again.\n\nRioli’s since-deleted post referenced the death of Indigenous teen Fred Amos during a police pursuit in Perth, accompanied by the hashtag #justice. Cue a storm of outrage, racist vitriol, and the kind of toxic online commentary that proves Australia still hasn’t learned how to talk about race without imploding.\n\nThe AFL says it’s “supporting” Rioli. Translation: releasing generic statements while hoping it all blows over before the next round. Meanwhile, fans are divided, and Indigenous players across the league are once again left carrying the emotional burden of calling out injustice and performing under stadium lights.\n\nIt’s not the first time Rioli’s name has trended for reasons unrelated to footy. The 28-year-old has faced everything from suspension to spotlight, and through it all, the media has been quicker to dissect his tone than address the racism aimed at him.\n\nThis week, Rioli requested time away from the club, with Port’s leadership backing his decision. One silver lining? The scandal has sparked fresh calls for stronger AFL protocols on social media abuse. Again. For the fifth time in five years.\n\nSources: ABC Sport, AFL.com.au, The Age, 7News\n', 0, 'factabot', 'willie-rioli-takes-leave-amid-online-abuse-after-instagram-post', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-05-02 20:15:53', 7);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (515, 'Outback Town Drenched: Levee Breaks, Floodwaters Rise', 'Thargomindah faces devastation as a levee failure leads to widespread flooding. Nature\'s not playing fair.', 'It’s raining, it’s pouring—and the outback is absolutely drowning. The tiny Queensland town of Winton, better known for dinosaurs and dusty pubs, is now flooded after the local levee gave up the ghost. Locals woke up to find streets turned into streams and pub beer gardens doubling as wading pools.\n\nThe levee, designed to protect the town from the sort of rain you’d expect once every few decades, was overwhelmed by a one-in-50-year downpour that decided to show up uninvited and angry. Authorities say over 100mm fell overnight, with emergency crews scrambling to help stranded residents and livestock alike.\n\nThis isn’t Winton’s first soggy rodeo, but with roads cut off and power patchy, the situation is turning biblical. Locals are using tinny boats to move essentials, while the council pleads with gawkers to stop “popping by” to see the chaos. Yes, someone did try to launch a kayak down the main drag. No, they weren’t wearing a life vest.\n\nThe bigger story? Climate-fuelled weather events are becoming routine, and infrastructure built for last century isn’t keeping up. Insurance costs are skyrocketing, federal response times are glacial, and small towns like Winton are left swimming—literally—in neglect.\n\nSources: ABC News, Courier-Mail, BOM, The Guardian', 0, 'factabot', 'outback-town-drenched-levee-breaks-floodwaters-rise', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-04-20 08:08:37', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (516, 'Paraplegic Stands Again with Robotic Help: Sci-Fi Meets Reality', 'A paraplegic man takes steps with the aid of a robotic device. The future is now, and it\'s walking.', 'Call off the next Iron Man reboot—science just gave us something better. A Perth paraplegic has stood and taken steps for the first time in over a decade, thanks to a robotic exoskeleton that looks straight out of The Matrix and moves like a dream on steel stilts.\n\nThe man, injured in a motorcycle crash 14 years ago, was trialling a Japanese-designed exosuit as part of a new rehab program at Fiona Stanley Hospital. Once strapped in, the suit senses muscle signals and translates them into movement—basically like borrowing a set of robot legs from a sci-fi future.\n\nCue tears, applause, and a ton of people asking if it’s covered by Medicare (spoiler: it’s not). The machine costs upwards of $150,000, but for patients and researchers alike, it’s a glimpse at what modern medicine can actually do when it’s not arguing over bulk billing caps.\n\nWhile it won’t replace wheelchairs overnight, the tech is a massive leap—literally—for mobility therapy. It’s not about walking marathons. It’s about dignity, independence, and telling gravity to get stuffed.\n\nLatest update? The hospital’s seeking funding for a full pilot program, with hopes the tech could be rolled out in more Aussie clinics. Until then, the dream walks one robotic step at a time.\n\nSources: ABC Perth, WA Health, The West Australian, 7News\n', 0, 'factabot', 'paraplegic-stands-again-with-robotic-help-sci-fi-meets-reality', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-05-02 20:51:54', 7);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (517, 'Craft Beer Flooded by Supermarket Giants: Indie Brewers Cry Foul', 'Independent brewers accuse big supermarkets of saturating the market. It\'s a hoppy mess.', 'Crack open a cold one—unless it’s from your local indie brewer, because they’re getting squeezed harder than a lime in a Corona. Australia’s independent beer scene is under siege as Coles and Woolies ramp up their craft-style private label beers, pushing tiny brewers to the edge of extinction.\n\nBig chains are now stocking their shelves with fake craft—“locally inspired” beers that sound artisanal but are brewed en masse in factories bigger than the actual towns they claim to represent. The prices? Dirt cheap. The marketing? Suspiciously hip. The impact? Brutal.\n\nIndie brewers say they can’t compete with supermarket scale and shelf space dominance. Even popular names like Young Henrys and Balter (which, yes, is now owned by CUB) are feeling the pinch. And don’t even mention tap contracts—those are locked up tighter than Dan Murphy’s on Good Friday.\n\nBehind the fizzy facade, it’s another David vs Goliath moment. Except Goliath has a marketing team and unlimited hops. And while consumers think they’re drinking small-batch, handcrafted bliss, they’re mostly chugging down corporate cosplay in a brown bottle.\n\nIndustry leaders are now calling for mandatory labelling that separates real independents from the conglomerate cosplay crowd. Until then, it’s buyer beware—and brewers screaming into their fermenters.\n\nSources: Brews News, ABC Rural, Sydney Morning Herald, Financial Review\n', 0, 'factabot', 'craft-beer-flooded-by-supermarket-giants-indie-brewers-cry-foul', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-05-02 05:13:54', 8);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (518, 'Lady Gaga\'s Aussie Tour Tickets Cause Fan Frenzy Over Pricing', 'Fans are reeling over ticket prices for Lady Gaga\'s upcoming Australian tour. Poker face? More like broke-er face.', 'Mother Monster is coming down under, but judging by the ticket prices, she might be flying first class on a private unicorn. Lady Gaga’s upcoming Australian tour dates triggered a full-blown meltdown this week as presale seats launched with prices that ranged from \"meh\" to \"do I have to sell a kidney?\"\n\nBasic seats? Around $250. Decent view? Over $400. VIP experience with a blurry Polaroid and half a handshake? Pushing $900. Fans rushed Ticketek like it was a Black Friday stampede, only to be met with queue crashes, page reloads, and soul-crushing “sold out” messages.\n\nNaturally, Little Monsters took to Twitter/X to air their grievances. Some blamed bots, some blamed capitalism, and some just posted crying memes wearing meat dresses.\n\nThis isn’t the first time a megastar’s Aussie tour turned into a financial Hunger Games. Taylor, Beyoncé, now Gaga—it\'s clear that concert tickets are the new crypto. Price surges, mystery fees, and “dynamic pricing” that somehow always feels like punishment for having taste.\n\nLatest twist? Resale sites are now listing seats at double the original price, with fans begging Live Nation to intervene while simultaneously begging their banks for a loan.\n\nSources: The Music, Pedestrian.TV, ABC News, Ticketek', 0, 'factabot', 'lady-gagas-aussie-tour-tickets-cause-fan-frenzy-over-pricing', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-05-05 12:05:21', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (519, 'Tiny Slice of Sydney Up for Sale at $60K: The Catch? It\'s Minuscule', 'A postage-stamp-sized plot in Sydney hits the market for $60,000. Location, location, lack of space.', 'Real estate in Sydney has officially jumped the shark—and landed on a patch of dirt smaller than a doormat. This week, a 1.6 square metre slice of land in Chippendale hit the market for $60,000. That’s $37,500 per square metre—for a plot you couldn’t even pitch a tent on without breaking council bylaws.\n\nThe listing proudly describes the site as “rare” and “unique,” which is just real estate code for “completely useless, but we dare you.” Technically, the land could be used for “storage” or “a café table,” but realistically it’s the size of a pizza box and about as practical as buying a driveway in Monaco.\n\nOf course, the internet ran wild with ideas. Pop-up espresso stand? Tiny gallery for one ant? An NFT museum with zero shade and negative equity?\n\nBut underneath the viral chaos is a reminder of just how bonkers Sydney\'s property market has become. First homebuyers can’t afford actual homes, but someone’s paying sixty grand for an awkward crack in the pavement with postcode clout.\n\nThe auction is still open, and realtors are betting on hype over function. Which, to be fair, is basically the entire Sydney housing model anyway.\n\nSources: Domain, News.com.au, The Guardian', 0, 'factabot', 'tiny-slice-of-sydney-up-for-sale-at-60k-the-catch-its-minuscule', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-04-18 12:44:19', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (520, 'Fish and Chip Shop Owner Serves Up Sass to Salty Customers', 'A fish and chip shop owner claps back at rude patrons online. Serving seafood and shade.', 'Over in Victoria, one fish and chip shop owner is fighting the cost-of-living crisis—and rude customers—with deep-fried sass and a side of sarcasm. When complaints over prices and “long waits” flooded her Facebook page, owner “Lynnie” clapped back with responses so spicy they belong in the tartare sauce.\n\nOne post read: “We’re not McDonald’s. We don’t flash fry frozen cardboard. We make food. It takes time. Calm down.” Another? “If you want fish for $2, go buy bait.”\n\nLynnie’s pub-level roasts have now gone viral, with her no-nonsense attitude earning praise from customers who are tired of keyboard warriors and entitlement masquerading as feedback.\n\nBehind the banter is a real struggle: ingredient prices are up, staff costs are rising, and small businesses are barely scraping by. But while some shop owners grovel for good reviews, Lynnie’s approach is simple—don’t like it? Don’t come back. Or do. She’s not fussed.\n\nThis week, the shop saw a surge in orders thanks to the viral sassstorm, with regulars posting selfies next to a chalkboard that now reads: “We don’t argue with clowns.”\n\nSources: 9News, ABC Regional, The Age, Facebook\n', 0, 'factabot', 'fish-and-chip-shop-owner-serves-up-sass-to-salty-customers', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 01:37:57', '2025-05-02 22:22:00', 12);
