INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (531, 'Sydney Mother Abducted, Found Dead in Burnt-Out Car', 'A 45-year-old woman was kidnapped from her Bankstown home and later found dead in a burnt-out car in Beverly Hills. Police describe the crime as \'unprecedented\' in violence.', 'In a crime that’s left Sydney reeling, a 45-year-old mother was abducted from her Bankstown home and later found dead in a burnt-out car in Beverly Hills. The horrifying sequence of events unfolded late Thursday night.\n\nAround 10:30pm, a group of up to five masked men stormed the woman’s home, assaulting her and her two sons. The younger boy, just eight years old, suffered serious head injuries after being struck with a baseball bat. The intruders then forced the woman into a black SUV and fled the scene.\n\nApproximately an hour later, emergency services responded to reports of a car fire on Welfare Avenue in Beverly Hills. Firefighters extinguished the blaze, only to discover a body in the back seat of the vehicle. While formal identification is pending, police believe it to be the abducted mother.\n\nSuperintendent Rodney Hart described the incident as “horrendous” and “unprecedented” in its level of violence. He emphasized that the attack appears targeted, not random, and that the family was not previously known to police.\n\nThe eight-year-old boy underwent surgery and remains in intensive care, while his 15-year-old brother was also hospitalized for assessment. Their father, who was interstate at the time, is returning to support his sons and assist with the investigation.\n\nPolice have launched Strike Force Bushfield to investigate the incident and are urging anyone with information to come forward. The community is left grappling with the brutality of the crime and the trauma inflicted on the surviving children.\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian, 7News, ABC News, NSW Police', 0, 'factabot', 'sydney-mother-abducted-found-dead-in-burnt-out-car', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 07:49:35', '2025-05-05 05:18:11', 18);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (532, 'Aussie Surfers Lead at Bells Beach Pro', 'Australian surfers Molly Picklum and Ethan Ewing are leading the Rip Curl Pro at Bells Beach, aiming for top spots ahead of the mid-season cut.', 'The Aussies have decided to stop being polite and start being gnarly. At this week’s Bells Beach Pro, local legends like Jack Robinson and Molly Picklum are cutting through the surf—and the leaderboard—like it’s their personal backyard pool. The waves are roaring, the crowd’s frothing, and the mid-season WSL cut? Looming like a bad ex.\n\nRobinson has been delivering clean carves and big heat wins, looking more composed than a yoga instructor on chamomile. Meanwhile, Picklum is continuing her quiet slay, stacking points while half the field tries to stay upright. If it weren’t for the brutal cut line, you’d almost think this was a chill beach holiday.\n\nBut this comp isn’t just about hang tens and GoPros—it’s survival season. The WSL’s Hunger Games-style mid-year cut means anyone not in the top 10 is packing their board bags and returning to the influencer circuit. And the judges? Let’s just say consistency isn’t the vibe.\n\nAs of today, Aussie surfers are topping the charts and fending off international rivals who look increasingly rattled. The message is clear: this is Bells, not Bondi. You either earn your spot, or the Southern Ocean eats your dreams.\n\nSources: WSL.com, ABC Sport, The Age, 9News\n', 0, 'factabot', 'aussie-surfers-lead-at-bells-beach-pro', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 07:49:35', '2025-05-02 20:24:54', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (533, 'Queensland Floods Prompt Mass Evacuations', 'Severe flooding in Queensland has led to widespread evacuations, with emergency services conducting numerous rescues amid rising waters.', 'It’s 2025 and somehow Queensland is still allergic to waterproofing. Torrential rains have turned entire towns into inland lakes, with thousands now evacuated and SES crews working overtime to rescue everyone from pets to pensioners. Nature, once again, has no chill.\n\nBundaberg, Rockhampton, and surrounding regions have copped the worst of it, with rivers swallowing roads and evacuation centres overflowing. Queenslanders are used to a bit of weather—but not when it brings crocodiles closer to the servo than anyone asked for.\n\nThe government says it’s “monitoring the situation closely,” which usually means standing near a whiteboard and hoping someone else fixes it. Locals, meanwhile, are sandbagging with one hand and doomscrolling flood maps with the other.\n\nClimate scientists are pointing (again) to intensifying weather patterns, but let’s be real—if politicians put as much effort into disaster prep as they do into ribbon-cutting photo ops, we wouldn’t be Googling “can u insure a canoe?”\n\nThis week, 1,800 residents have been told to evacuate, dozens of roads remain closed, and forecasters say the rain’s not done. Time to build the ark—or at least a better flood plan.\n\nSources: ABC News, Bureau of Meteorology, 7News, Courier-Mail\n', 0, 'factabot', 'queensland-floods-prompt-mass-evacuations', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 07:49:35', '2025-04-20 08:03:39', 6);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (534, 'Mental Health Crisis Among Homeless Youth', 'A new report indicates over half of Australia\'s homeless youth experience suicidal thoughts or self-harm, highlighting urgent mental health support needs.', 'Australia’s homeless youth aren’t just sleeping rough—they’re mentally hanging on by a thread. A new report has revealed that over 70% of young people experiencing homelessness are battling significant mental health issues, and no, posting about it on RUOK Day isn’t fixing it.\n\nThe findings come from a national survey of support services, with frontline workers painting a grim picture: underfunded mental health care, impossible waitlists, and kids being discharged from hospital into literal tents. It’s giving “system failure” with a side of “how is this still happening?”\n\nMany of these young people fled trauma, domestic violence, or the foster care maze, only to end up couch-surfing, living in cars, or navigating crisis motels that make prison look appealing. And the kicker? Most are under 25, meaning they’re still technically someone’s “youth engagement” policy statistic.\n\nGovernments across the board keep pledging more funding, but what hits the ground is a confusing tangle of charity handoffs, red tape, and hope-fatigue. The phrase “wraparound services” is thrown around a lot—but try getting wraparound care when the service closes at 5 and the hotline is engaged.\n\nThis week’s report has sparked calls for urgent reform, but judging by past performance, urgent might mean “eventually, if we remember.” Until then, kids in crisis are stuck waiting—for housing, for therapy, and for adults to get their act together.\n\nSources: The Guardian, Mission Australia, ABC News, Youth Mental Health Coalition', 0, 'factabot', 'mental-health-crisis-among-homeless-youth', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 07:49:35', '2025-04-25 23:15:23', 10);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (535, 'Kia Launches Tasman Ute in Australia', 'Kia has unveiled its first ute, the Tasman, in Australia, entering the competitive market dominated by models like the Ford Ranger.', 'Kia’s finally entered the Aussie ute wars with the Tasman—a dual-cab diesel beast that’s part workhorse, part lifestyle flex, and 100% gunning for the Ford Ranger’s lunch. Priced from $42,990, it undercuts the Ranger while promising 3.5-tonne towing, off-road chops, and a cabin that’s more tech-lounge than tradie truck .\n\nThe Tasman comes in five variants, including the top-shelf X-Pro at $74,990, which offers all-terrain tyres and a 252mm ground clearance. Kia claims it’s the “most Australian vehicle” it’s ever built—developed with local input and tested in the outback, deserts, and even Sweden, because why not?\n\nBut is it enough to sway the HiLux and Ranger faithful? Time will tell. For now, Kia’s betting that a bold design, competitive pricing, and a dash of Korean swagger will carve out a slice of the ute pie.\n\nSources: \n7NEWS\n \n@RACV\n \nWhichCar', 0, 'factabot', 'kia-launches-tasman-ute-in-australia', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 07:49:35', '2025-04-29 05:10:04', 13);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (536, 'Groovin the Moo Festival Cancelled Again', 'For the second consecutive year, the Groovin the Moo music festival has been cancelled, citing financial challenges and industry-wide issues.', 'Groovin the Moo has been cancelled for the second year running, leaving regional Australia without its beloved music festival. Organisers cited the need to find a \"sustainable model\" amid rising costs and industry challenges .\n\nThe cancellation follows a string of festival woes, including Splendour in the Grass pulling the plug on its 2025 edition. Industry experts warn that without government support, Australia\'s festival scene could face a prolonged downturn.\n\nFor now, the Moo Crew will have to wait and hope for a revival in 2026.\n\nSources: \nThe Guardian\n \nRolling Stone Australia\n \nABC', 0, 'factabot', 'groovin-the-moo-festival-cancelled-again', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 07:49:35', '2025-05-02 17:05:15', 17);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (537, 'VCAA Board Dismissed Over Exam Bungle', 'The entire board of the Victorian Curriculum Assessment Authority has been dismissed following a major error in last year\'s Year 12 exams.', 'In a move that’s as overdue as a Year 12 assignment, the entire board of Victoria’s Curriculum and Assessment Authority (VCAA) has been sacked after a review into last year’s VCE exam fiasco. The blunder? Publishing sample cover pages that accidentally included real exam questions—viewed 6,000 times before the tests .\n\nEducation Minister Ben Carroll called the incident \"unacceptable,\" noting it was the third major exam error in as many years. A new interim board and CEO have been appointed, with reforms promised to restore confidence in the VCE system.\n\nLet’s hope this marks the end of the exam blunders.\n\nSources: \nThe Guardian\n \n9News\n \ntheaustraliatoday.com.au', 0, 'factabot', 'vcaa-board-dismissed-over-exam-bungle', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 07:49:35', '2025-04-19 06:39:03', 4);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (538, 'P-Plater Caught Speeding Three Times in Four Hours', 'A P-plate driver in New South Wales lost their license after being caught speeding three times within four hours, highlighting road safety concerns.', 'Some teenagers test boundaries. This one tested the speed limit, the patience of police, and basic common sense—three times in four hours. A 19-year-old P-plater has been charged after allegedly racking up three separate speeding offences on the Hume Highway, topping out at a brain-melting 215 km/h. On her red Ps. Yes, really.\n\nIt all began around 10:30am near Gunning, where police say she was clocked doing over 130 km/h in a 110 zone. Instead of taking the hint—or, say, a nap—she was back on the highway an hour later, this time allegedly doing 215 km/h near Tumblong. That little stunt got her plates pulled and her licence immediately suspended.\n\nBut wait—because this is Fast & Furious: Wagga Drift now—she was allegedly caught again around 2:10pm near Table Top, doing 201 km/h without a licence and without legal plates. The only thing faster than her car was the speed at which she racked up charges.\n\nNSW Police are, unsurprisingly, not impressed. They described her behaviour as “ridiculous” and “incredibly dangerous,” which is polite cop-speak for “what on Earth were you thinking?” The charges include dangerous driving, driving while suspended, and removing a police-issued confiscation notice.\n\nShe’s now due in two courts—Albury in April and Gundagai in June—giving her plenty of time to reflect on her brief but furious joyride. Her car? Impounded for three months. Her chances of getting insurance again? Somewhere between slim and “try a bicycle.”\n\nSources: ABC News, 9News, NSW Police Media', 0, 'factabot', 'p-plater-caught-speeding-three-times-in-four-hours', 'draft', NULL, NULL, '2025-04-18 07:49:35', '2025-05-04 14:36:03', 20);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (539, 'Sydney Mother Abducted, Found Dead in Burnt-Out Car', 'A 45-year-old woman was kidnapped from her Bankstown home and later found dead in a burnt-out car in Beverly Hills. Police describe the crime as \'unprecedented\' in violence.', 'In a crime that’s left Sydney reeling, a 45-year-old mother was abducted from her Bankstown home and later found dead in a burnt-out car in Beverly Hills. The horrifying sequence of events unfolded late Thursday night.\n\nAround 10:30pm, a group of up to five masked men stormed the woman’s home, assaulting her and her two sons. The younger boy, just eight years old, suffered serious head injuries after being struck with a baseball bat. The intruders then forced the woman into a black SUV and fled the scene.\n\nApproximately an hour later, emergency services responded to reports of a car fire on Welfare Avenue in Beverly Hills. Firefighters extinguished the blaze, only to discover a body in the back seat of the vehicle. While formal identification is pending, police believe it to be the abducted mother.\n\nSuperintendent Rodney Hart described the incident as “horrendous” and “unprecedented” in its level of violence. He emphasized that the attack appears targeted, not random, and that the family was not previously known to police.\n\nThe eight-year-old boy underwent surgery and remains in intensive care, while his 15-year-old brother was also hospitalized for assessment. Their father, who was interstate at the time, is returning to support his sons and assist with the investigation.\n\nPolice have launched Strike Force Bushfield to investigate the incident and are urging anyone with information to come forward. The community is left grappling with the brutality of the crime and the trauma inflicted on the surviving children.\n\nSources:\nThe Guardian, 7News, ABC News, NSW Police', 0, 'factabot', 'sydney-mother-abducted-found-dead-in-burnt-out-car', 'draft', 'images/news/6b2a96e1-68f5-41f7-908c-e7e8863b2360.webp', NULL, '2025-04-18 07:49:41', '2025-04-18 22:21:43', 3);
