INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (622, 'New Study Finds That Sitting is the New Smoking, Standing is the New Sitting', 'Health experts now warn that sitting for extended periods is detrimental, but standing all day isn\'t much better. Next up: lying down is the new standing.', 'According to a groundbreaking new study out of UNSW, your office chair might be slowly plotting your demise. Researchers have declared that sitting too long is “the new smoking”—which makes sense, given how many of us now start the day by lighting up a double-shot oat latte and settling in for an 8-hour screen stare.\n\nLead researcher Dr. Emily Lasker warned that even the smug people with standing desks aren\'t off the hook. “Standing is the new sitting,” she said, effectively cancelling the entire ergonomic-industrial complex. Cue the collective groan from every tech bro who paid $2,000 for a desk that gently vibrates.\n\nThe study tracked over 12,000 Australians and found that prolonged sedentary behaviour is linked to heart disease, diabetes, and the existential dread of watching yet another Slack message come through. Even regular exercisers weren’t spared. “You can’t out-jog eight hours of inertia,” said Lasker, destroying the last excuse held by gym bros everywhere.\n\nThis isn\'t just a health issue—it\'s an identity crisis. Are we supposed to squat between meetings? Lunge to the photocopier? The wellness industry is already gearing up to sell “active furniture” like treadmill chairs and kettlebell laptops. One startup is even pitching “dynamic power posing” as a subscription service. God help us all.\n\nIn response, the government launched a “Move More, Sit Less” campaign that’s basically just a PowerPoint with a dancing stick figure. Meanwhile, corporate HR departments are panicking over how to rebrand “email time” as cardio.\n\nSo next time someone catches you pacing during a Zoom call, just tell them: you\'re not weird—you’re health-conscious and ahead of the curve.\n\nSources:\n\nThe Australian (22 April 2025)\n\nABC News (22 April 2025)\n\nUNSW Media Release (22 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'new-study-finds-that-sitting-is-the-new-smoking-standing-is-the-new-sitting', 'draft', 'images/news/f8a17ca0-3178-4f81-a73e-1a646f4aeb79.webp', NULL, '2025-04-22 03:03:20', '2025-04-22 03:05:03', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (623, 'Stock Market Takes Nosedive; Investors Blame Mercury Retrograde', 'The ASX experienced a significant drop, with some investors attributing the decline to astrological phenomena rather than economic indicators.', 'The ASX had a Monday morning tantrum, wiping billions off the board like a toddler knocking over Duplo. But while analysts cited rising bond yields, global jitters, and China’s latest export grumbles, a surprising number of retail investors are pointing fingers skyward—specifically at Mercury, which apparently entered retrograde just hours before the crash.\n\nSocial media lit up with frantic memes, crystal emojis, and #blameMercury hashtags as TikTok finance gurus warned followers not to “sign contracts or invest during a retrograde.” One even burned sage in front of a stock ticker. Did it work? Absolutely not. But it was great content.\n\nBlue-chip stocks fell like they’d seen a ghost. Tech shares were especially spooked, and mining stocks tumbled after iron ore prices wobbled. But it was crypto that really had its astrological moment, dropping faster than a vegan sausage roll at a Bunnings BBQ. Traders on X (formerly Twitter) declared it “vibe-based investing season,” and honestly, they weren’t wrong.\n\nMeanwhile, the Reserve Bank stayed silent, possibly because they were still processing how Mercury got involved in monetary policy. The irony? All those folks who mocked astrology last week are now nervously Googling “when does Mercury retrograde end” and lighting tealight candles.\n\nLatest update: ASX has slightly recovered, but investor confidence remains shakier than Elon Musk’s Twitter password. Economists are urging calm. Astrologers are urging rose quartz. Only one thing is certain—everyone’s broke and no one wants to admit it was the moon’s fault.\n\nSources:\n\nFinancial Review (22 April 2025)\n\nThe Guardian AU (22 April 2025)\n\nNews.com.au (22 April 2025)', 0, 'factabot', 'stock-market-takes-nosedive-investors-blame-mercury-retrograde', 'draft', 'images/news/26471781-5cc9-42e7-af32-88d26661c3ea.webp', NULL, '2025-04-22 03:03:20', '2025-04-22 03:05:29', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (624, 'Reality TV Star Discovers Reality, Shocked by Lack of Script', 'A well-known reality TV personality ventured into the real world and was reportedly baffled by the unpredictability and absence of retakes.', 'Tara-Lee Bright, former contestant on Love Prison: Byron Bay Edition, is having a rough week. After leaving the show’s perfectly curated chaos of tequila-fueled “romances” and producers whispering drama prompts in her ear, she attempted to re-enter the real world — only to discover it was unscripted, under-lit, and didn’t come with a ring light or a free brunch.\n\nBright, who once called herself “a vibes-based entrepreneur,” posted a tearful TikTok about the “toxic unpredictability of non-curated living.” Turns out no one claps when she enters a room, exes don’t magically show up at parties to fight, and Centrelink isn’t impressed by her 237,000 followers. “Where’s the storyline?” she cried. “I don’t know what character I’m meant to be!”\n\nPost-show life has been harsh. Influencer sponsorships dried up after she accidentally mistook a sunscreen ad for a crypto scheme, and her new podcast, Bright Ideas, has fewer listeners than her mum’s WhatsApp voice notes. Fans were quick to comment: “Girl, that’s just life. We’re all off-script and underpaid.”\n\nThis little post-reality meltdown has sparked a debate about whether we’ve bred a generation who think confrontation should come with a lighting crew. Psychologists say it’s a growing identity crisis. Boomers say, “Get a job.” Gen Z just says, “Relatable.”\n\nLatest update: Tara-Lee is reportedly “taking time to find herself,” which seems to involve a lot of green smoothies, sponsored retreats, and definitely no rent payments. If reality bites, she’s still trying to find the filter.\n\nSources:\n\nNews.com.au (22 April 2025)\n\nThe Guardian AU (22 April 2025)\n\nDaily Mail Australia (22 April 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'reality-tv-star-discovers-reality-shocked-by-lack-of-script', 'draft', 'images/news/8a47b5a5-75a0-4393-8db6-a47a3ab538fe.webp', NULL, '2025-04-22 03:03:20', '2025-04-22 03:09:57', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (625, 'Tiny Homes Trend Grows: Australians Now Living in Dog Kennels to Afford Housing', 'With property prices soaring, some Australians are downsizing to the extreme, converting pet accommodations into human dwellings.', 'In today’s episode of Australia: The Housing Crisis Remix, meet the latest trend: people turning dog kennels into rental properties. No, not metaphorically. Literally. As house prices enter their villain arc and rents shoot higher than ScoMo’s post-office speaker fees, some Aussies are downsizing so hard they’re sharing square footage with golden retrievers.\n\nOne Melbourne couple went viral for converting their oversized dog kennel into a “micro studio” complete with fairy lights, a foldable mattress, and a compostable toilet. The rent? $120 a week—bargain, if you ignore the fact it’s technically classified as a “pet structure.” “It’s cosy and minimal,” they said. Translation: “We can’t afford walls.”\n\nThis comes as new data reveals that housing affordability in major cities has collapsed into a punchline. Sydney’s median house price just hit $1.6 million, and even outer suburb units now require the blood sacrifice of a firstborn and a six-figure deposit. First home buyers are either fleeing to rural towns or trying to Airbnb their childhood bedrooms.\n\nProperty developers are calling it “adaptive living.” Economists are calling it “dystopia with better marketing.” Meanwhile, politicians are offering solutions like stamp duty tweaks, which is a bit like fixing a flooded house with a paper towel.\n\nAs of today, councils are scrambling to enforce zoning laws as more backyard kennels quietly become housing solutions. One local councillor described the trend as “deeply concerning,” while admitting his adult son is currently living in a caravan with a pet cockatoo.\n\nIf dogs are man’s best friend, they might also be our new landlords.\n\nSources:\n\nABC News (22 April 2025)\n\nThe Age (22 April 2025)\n\nDomain (22 April 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'tiny-homes-trend-grows-australians-now-living-in-dog-kennels-to-afford-housing', 'draft', 'images/news/7caeeedf-177d-431b-9410-9434ec7ba4bd.webp', NULL, '2025-04-22 03:03:20', '2025-04-22 03:06:51', 0);
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (626, 'New Wellness Trend Encourages Screaming into Void for Stress Relief', 'Forget yoga and meditation; the latest self-care craze involves yelling into empty spaces to release pent-up frustration. Experts say it\'s surprisingly effective.', 'Self-care has officially gone feral. In a shocking turn of “this can’t be real, but somehow is,” the latest wellness trend sweeping Australia is… screaming. Not in therapy. Not at your ex. But into the void. Organised primal scream sessions are popping up in parks, parking lots, and wellness retreats, where stressed-out millennials gather to collectively lose their minds—politely, of course.\n\nThe concept? Show up, stretch a bit, then absolutely unleash. No judgment, no shoes, just you, a bunch of strangers, and the sound of 30 office workers howling into the abyss like emotionally scarred banshees. “It’s cathartic,” said one attendee. “Better than paying $300 to cry quietly in Pilates.”\n\nThe trend started in Sydney’s Inner West (obviously), where a local yoga instructor-slash-sound healer decided guided meditation was too calm for the current economic climate. Now it’s spreading faster than a burnout diagnosis, with “void scream” pop-ups listed on Eventbrite under tags like “spiritual release,” “vibrational detox,” and “BYO throat lozenges.”\n\nExperts are cautiously optimistic. Psychologists say screaming might help release tension—though warn against doing it during meetings. Boomers, meanwhile, call it “nonsense,” while secretly yelling into the void of Facebook comment sections every day.\n\nThe government has yet to comment, but we’re expecting a taxpayer-funded “Scream Responsibly” campaign by June. It’ll probably feature a beach, a softly-spoken narrator, and a note not to disturb wildlife with your emotional baggage.\n\nAs for the void itself? Still bottomless, still quiet—until another scream is added to the pile.\n\nSources:\n\nSBS News (22 April 2025)\n\nThe Guardian AU (22 April 2025)\n\n9Honey (22 April 2025)\n', 0, 'factabot', 'new-wellness-trend-encourages-screaming-into-void-for-stress-relief', 'draft', 'images/news/59cc2c0a-18e0-4f95-9d51-b1592801ebce.webp', NULL, '2025-04-22 03:03:20', '2025-04-22 03:08:24', 0);
