INSERT INTO `news_old_new` VALUES (14, 1, 'Australia\'s Two-Tier Economy: Prawns for the Rich, Instant Noodles for the Rest', 'A woman spends $60 on a prawn entrée and declares Australia has a \"two-tier economy.\" Meanwhile, the rest of us are just trying to afford avocado toast.', 'Australia’s Two-Tier Economy: Prawns for the Rich, Instant Noodles for the Rest\r\nThe Players: The $60 Prawn Lady vs. The Struggling Masses\r\nMeet Australia’s latest economic philosopher: a woman who ordered a prawn entrée, paid $60 for it, and had a revelation—Australia has a “two-tier economy.” Yes, folks, never mind the rising cost of living, the housing crisis, or stagnant wages; the moment of truth arrived between bites of overpriced seafood. While she dined in a bustling restaurant full of people apparently rolling in disposable income, she had an epiphany: some people can still afford luxury, while others are rationing their instant ramen. Groundbreaking. Someone alert the Reserve Bank.\r\nThe Drama: Bougie Dining vs. Budget Survival\r\nThis whole “two-tier economy” debate isn’t new. For years, experts (you know, actual economists) have been pointing out that Australia is splitting into the haves and have-nots at an alarming rate. But somehow, nothing hits quite like seeing a full restaurant while you\'re crying into your Coles-branded spaghetti. With house prices at nosebleed levels and inflation turning basic groceries into luxury goods, it’s not shocking that some Aussies are wondering why certain people are still out here popping bottles while others are calculating whether they can afford an extra egg this week.\r\nThe Big Picture: Who’s Actually Feeling the Squeeze?\r\nThe real kicker? The people who feel the crisis most aren’t the ones making headlines about it. Renters, minimum-wage workers, and single-income families aren’t splurging on fancy entrees—they’re juggling bills and praying their landlords don’t “renovate” them out of their homes. Meanwhile, cashed-up professionals, property investors, and anyone who bought real estate before 2015 seem to be doing just fine, thank you very much. The economy isn’t collapsing for everyone—it’s just squeezing the life out of anyone who isn’t already ahead. But sure, let’s focus on restaurant crowds instead of, say, wage stagnation or corporate price gouging.\r\nThe Latest: Another Day, Another ‘Shocking’ Observation\r\nThe internet has, of course, gone wild with reactions—some people nodding along, others rolling their eyes at the obviousness of it all. Meanwhile, economists continue to publish actual reports showing how wealth inequality is growing, but who has time for data when we have dramatic prawn-related anecdotes? The government, as usual, will probably announce a “review” of cost-of-living pressures before promptly doing absolutely nothing. Bon appétit, Australia!', 0, 'Paijo', 'Australia\'s_TwoTier_Economy:_Prawns_for_the_Rich,_Instant_Noodles_for_the_Rest', 'published', 'images/news/2LMl0JjNn68rC3JIz8QSBTdMvUtrUa8hBTmsVlFK.webp', '2025-03-03 09:55:42', '2025-03-12 07:19:04', 0);
